highpower: I was in power on my high school track team my senior year. I had the power to push my fellow teammates and make sure that they were working hard and doing what they were supposed to be. I liked the feeling of that but sometimes I felt a little mean and didn't like having to yell at a teammate for not doing what they were supposed to be doing.

I was in the position of power when my dog wanted a treat, but did not want to do a trick for it. I had the power to not give my dog what she wanted until she did what I wanted (high-five, roll over, shake, etc.). My dog knows where the treats are located and just kept pawing at the door. I wasn't frustrated that my dog didn't do what I wanted her to, I thought it was funny. It was funny because I was in control and she was practically begging for a treat, instead of just doing a trick. Doing a trick would have been quick and easy, but instead she wanted to waste all this energy whining and pawing at the door. It feels good to have a sense of power, but I wouldn't want to be in control all the time. I wouldn't want people (or my dog in this case) to be dependent on me. My dog was dependent on me for a treat, since she can't open the door and get it herself. Eventually, I felt bad because I felt like I was teasing my dog and torturing her by not giving her her favorite snack, so I gave in and gave her a couple milk bones. She's too dang cute, with those puppy dog eyes!!

I recall a time around my junior year that I got two people together. My friend Zack wanted a girl named Taylor as his girlfriend. He wanted to be with her but he did not want to risk losing the friendship. So I decided to talk to Taylor on how she felt about the situation and she did not want to lose him as a friend either. I ended up getting them to go on a double date with me to see if anything was easier. It got a little easier as the week went on. Then I told my friend Zack he needed to ask her out already and just see how being boyfriend and girlfriend would feel. I said if you never try you will never know how you guys truly feel. In the end they dated for about 2 years and were the perfect couple. All because my friend listened to my advice on what to do.

when I was working in a nursing home and we were short staffed, other staff members came to me looking for help. I felt over whelmed at first but later on felt respected enough that they came to me for help.
I feel good when I help any one to get what he/she want.

One time one of my friends came to me asking if i wanted to go to a movie with him and he really wanted to go but was only allowed if he took one other person. I was the final say and my decision would choose the outcome of either him watching this movie he wanted to see or not see it at all. I felt bad that i could not go, therefore taking away his chance of seeing it that night.

I babysat for my job, and it helped give me experience for becoming a teacher. I think it was a good experience and I was able to do a good job. I have been babysitting since my freshman year in high school and over time I became more comfortable in doing my job.

One time I was put in charge of training a co worker who had just started working at my place of work. It wasn't really a memorable experience, I just showed them how to do some things and had them come back to me if they had any questions. Everything went smoothly and they seemed to catch on pretty fast.

There have been several times where I have felt to be in the position of power with my sibling. We are 7 years apart and I am the younger one. All our lives I wanted to be in control and have anything she wanted or I wanted to have more than she had. On her birthday one year, I decided to run away because no one was giving me attention, remind you I was around the age of 7. After becoming the center of attention once no one knew where I was, I felt horrible. I realized that there was no reason I should have acted that way. I cried, and I apologized to my entire family. Not only for acting out of character but because I did indeed scare everyone.

I am currently working as a manager and that position is one of power. I am the leader, the head, the boss of the other student workers. On a daily basis I have to delegate tasks to my fellow workers. The weird part about this is that they are my employees in a sense but they are also fellow students. We are on the same level, but not at the same time. Sometimes I do feel bad giving tasks out to them because I could just do them myself, but it is my job to delegate and if I do not have the time to oversee and do the task then I have to have them do it. But every task I give someone I make sure I can do myself and would be willing to do myself.

This situation was over the summer when I was in a management position.  I enjoyed my time very much and I feel I help new people learn what they were suppose to know well and was able to communicate well with them.

In high school I was the captain of our girls varsity basketball team. I was voice for both the coaches and my teammates when relaying information and goals for the team. I made sure my teammates were on time to practices and games, understand deadlines and expectations, and made sure we worked together as one unit. I know at times my teammates might have been frustrated with me when I pushed them harder in practice, but I know that it was improving them and our team success as a whole. I had to be forceful, understanding, and have a good sense of leadership and listening when being in this position.

One time I was helping out with an event in ice skating. All the younger kids were coming up to me because I was the person who was in charge. They would come to me if they needed help or had any questions. Being in power made me feel like I was in charge and I felt important.

In high school i was in charge of organizing my schools homecoming dance. I had final say on a lot of the things going into the planning. I felt like i had to much control and it was very overwhelming at times.

I am a manager at a store and so one day, one of the associates was not doing what I asked of them so I pulled them aside, told them they could clock out and leave and called in another associate who would do as they were asked.

I was in a position of power during cheerleading tryouts for a club team and I was in charge of choosing girls for my own team. I felt bad for the people who weren't very good but I had to exclude them from my team. I was in their position once so I know they will be okay and if they are unhappy then hopefully they will work harder. I don't usually like having all of the power but I want things to be organized and exactly how i wanted them.

Junior year of high school I was the manager of an art club event to set up the junior/senior prom. I had the ability to set people in certain positions and to do certain tasks to get our prom decorated and ready for the big night. I was entitled to critique their abilities and also set them somewhere else to do a different task if I didn't see it fit. It made me nervous being in such a position. I was very uncomfortable having to replace people once they started working and was afraid to hurt another person's feelings. It was exciting to participate and what all of it come together, but the power wasn't something I liked.
I worked at a retail store and I had to train new employees. I liked the feeling because i knew what I was doing and it felt good to help others learn something new.
Babysitting. I felt important. Yet, I felt that if I wasn't in charge something bad would happen. I had to be good at being in charge otherwise I would lose my job.

My brother wanted to move back in and my mom left it up to me to decide whether he did or not. We do not get along at all. I felt like I could finally get what I wanted with him, to not have him around anymore.
I felt in control because I decided what happened during that time period. Also, I controlled what the people around me were doing.

I am a member of the campus activities board here on campus. Our job is to find exciting events to bring here on campus through concerts and comedians, many different fun things. The last position of power I was put in was at the Mayday parade concert. The stage provided did not have a wall to block the students from climbing up on stage, so fellow cab members and myself were in charge of security. We had the position of power to stand at the foot of the stage, in front of all the fans and make sure no one touched the stage but us cab members. By doing so, we were put in a position of power and controlled the other students.

I was babysitting my cousins who were around three and five years old. I felt like I was in control and that I had the power to tell them yes or no. However, all of that power was kind of nerveracking because I had full responsibility for those kids and if something happened to them I would be in trouble and never have that power again. On the other hand, I felt like I was in control and that was a good feeling.

I work for a foot doctor and when it was time for me to come to college, they had to hire someone to replace me. When they found someone to replace me, it was my job to help train them. I had the power to control what the person who replaced me was learning. It was different for me because I wasn't used to having power. I was nervous and hoped I was doing a good job at training her.

Working as a server in an Assisted Living, I was frequently appointed to the position of training new incoming employees. This event was where I taught them how to the job, and how to do it well. Being in this position, I enjoyed telling people what to do and how to do it correctly. I feel that I do a great job as a server and I want to train people how I work because it is the best way to do it. Throughout my time working at this Assisted Living, I trained many people and I enjoyed it because I was able to see them thrive, thanks to my leadership.

Recently, one of my friends told me that they wanted to lose weight. Since I have extensive knowledge on the subject of nutrition and exercise, he came to me for advice on how to achieve his goal. I'm a calorie counter, so I believe that calorie counting is the overall best way to go in terms of achieving any fitness related goal. While sharing my knowledge with him and telling him the next steps he needs to take, I felt as if I had the power of knowledge that he needed in order to accomplish his goals. It felt good sharing what I know and explaining myself on the subject. He has been trying to calorie count lately, and seeing him taking my advice and trying so hard makes me feel good, and the feeling of helping someone out based on what I know is something that satisfies me.

When I was at my old job and I had to teach a lady with one arm how to through a discus the right way. I liked it because she was older than me and yet I was the person that was in control because I had the most knowledge on the subject. I was the teacher and the helper in that situation.

The most powerful moment I felt was the day a friend of my mothers was at our house and he was attempting to pull her away from her marriage because he wanted to have her for himself. When I found him trying to make a move on her I was infuriated and shaking violently. However, this was during the winter and my car had gotten stuck in the driveway so I held my anger in and had him assist me in freeing it and then I let go of the barriers I was using to hold back my anger. I told him to get off of our property When he tried to play dumb about it and ask me why with a look of innocence and confusion, I informed him that I had caught him in the process of doing making a move on my mother and that he had no right to be anywhere near my mother and to do that kind of thing to her. I reminded him that he also has a wife and kids at home and that he was not welcome at our home again and if he ever did come back or tried anything with my mother again, I would be right on his doorstep to inform his wife. The whole time that I was yelling at him my mother was telling me to calm down and stop yelling but I refused and continued until he got in his car pathetically trying to apologize for his wretchedness and left. That was the most powerful experience I have ever felt keeping someone from getting what they wanted. I was livid and had made a grown man suddenly turn into a boy who had been caught doing something wrong and had cowered in regret until he could flee apologizing the whole way.

I worked as a lifeguard in a LifeTime Fitness and our supervisor couldn't handle her job and was far less experienced than I was in her position so she handed off supervising duties to me and I had to run the pool and all of the guards.  It was my job to make sure everyone was where they needed to be and deal with and complaints from the members.  I remember being exhausted from dealing with people all day but also a sense of accomplishment because I had still done a better job of coordinating everyone than my supervisor.  I thought the job would be much more difficult than it was.  Everyone listened and did what they were told to do and everything went quite smoothly after I took over.  I experienced some adrenaline whenever I had to kick people out of the pool or explain to someone what the could and could not do.  Both the members and the staff held me to a higher standard after that which made me proud.

Many of my friends frequently ask me to edit their papers for class and when I read them I can't help but judge their mistakes like improper word usage or incorrect grammar. I'll help them as much as I can without hurting anyone's feelings, and it usually goes okay once we've finished the paper. A lot of times I usually end up writing the majority of their paper for them, which makes me mad, but also makes me feel better at articulation in a weird way.

When I went home, my younger sister asked me if I would pick her and her friend up from a haunted house. I was in control because I got to choose whether or not she got to go or not. I liked having this power but I also felt bad because I wanted her to be able to have a good time.

I was captain of the cheer leading squad in high school so I was able to give directions on what to do to multiple people at one time.  They had to show respect to me and my co captain.  I enjoyed being in a higher position during high school but the responsibilities were difficult at times and it was a lot to be in charge of.  It was fun at times since people had to listen to what you had to say, but it was also a learning experience about working with others.  It taught me that not everyone is going to respect you no matter what your status is but you have to be able to handle every different type of person you come in contact with.

Once I was the team leader and I had to assign jobs to each person so that things ran smoothly and effectively. I became frustrated when others didn't follow directions and work hard, but those who did what I asked of them, I was pleased with.

I work at the UPS Store and we had hired a new girl. She had some training with my manager, but one day me and her were left alone to work together. It was kind of weird because she was older than me so I automatically assume the older person has the authority, but she couldn't because she was still unsure of what she had to do so I was that person that she came to if she needed help or had any questions. I didn't mind it. I would expect her to need help and have questions because I went through the same thing. It was weird, but I'm glad she was comfortable enough to want me to help.

Recently, I was voted as the New Member Class Vice President of my sorority. The President was not there, so I was forced to instruct the other members on what to do, and what their jobs were. It was not that big of a deal, but I felt like I was helping a lot of the New Members in my sorority. It felt good that they wanted me to be in that position.

I was elected as a state representative when I attended Buckeye Girls State, the summer after my junior year. This position gave me the opportunity to speak as the voice for fifty other girls in my community. Public speaking terrifies me every time I have to do it; however, I felt encouraged by my peers and their positives attitudes influenced during this situation. Without their help and encouragement, I don't know if I would have been able to give those speeches in front of the crowd I had to talk to.

I babysit a 5 year old girl in the summer and if she wanted to go to the pool that day i made sure that she cleaned her room and picked up her toys first. If she didnt, then we wouldnt go to the pool. I felt bad at certain times because she didnt want to always pick up her toys but it was something that had to be done.

I was the president of National Honor Society at my high school.  I was in charge of event planning as well as informing members of upcoming events.  I also was there if anyone needed help.  Even though it could be stressful at times, I really loved it.  I got to e an authority figure but I was also able to be there for people when they needed help.  I loved helping members as well as community members through service projects we did.  I made a lot of friends and I gained experience in leading others.

I was a group leader for an assignment in class. I was in charge of assigning tasks for my group members. I enjoyed being in charge because in that situation I was the most fit person to lead. I felt like I would be able to get the job done correctly if I was heading the group. I still did my share of work, but made sure everyone else was doing theirs as well.

I was in charge of prayer group at my highschool and held the power of dictating several choices. Often I would choose when and where to meet, what "breakfast" snack was served, when the bible study began, who took prayer requests, who prayed, and other similar decisions. I felt a sense of joy over the fact that my power helped lead to the groups success in the two years I ran it, but at the same time I felt distant from the rest of the group. I would often spend so much time trying to make things perfect that I forgot to enjoy the time I had. Most of the time though, prayer group and leading it gave me a sense of comfort and hope because it helped boost my faith as well as the faith of those who attended.

I was in charge of my group project at work and what we had to. I pretty much let the group figure things out though I was only there if they really needed me to. I kept them on task and focused but when it came down to what the group was going to do i let them provide some options then i selected from those options. It was weird being in charge of a group of my peers. I didn't want to make anyone mad or have a bias on the best idea so i had them write their ideas down on paper then submit them. That way i didn't know who suggested what. When i finally chose our project i was glad because the group was not upset with my decision they went with what i thought was the best plan and they worked hard and executed it to perfection. It is weird being in a position of power or responsibility but i like it. It feels natural to me.

When i babysit i have the children do chores before we are aloud to do activities or chores. At first the children do not want to do the chores but then i keep mentioning the reward. By them doing the chores not only is the parent then happier when they arrive home but the child learns responsibility.

I was one of the co-captains of the swim team. I tried to get the team to be one big group and cheer for the other members of the team. I was happy and honored that I had the oppurtunity because i felt that the team should be a united front and we should be one big family.

I was in a situation of power when I taught lessons in a classroom.  I felt confident and happy to be teaching students.  I thought that most of my lessons went very well and the students enjoyed themselves during the lesson. I also thought that they had a good understanding of the topics covered.
I do not recall anytime where i was in the position of power.

I was babysitting my younger siblings when i was still kinda young myself. I was 13 so old enough to stay alone and i guess watch my brother and sister. I made my brother do stupid small things for me like get the remote or get me a bottle of water. My little sister was just there to watch T.V. with me. I felt great while my parents were gone but when they got back I felt really bad like I had done some thing horrible.

When I was trying to get my friend out of her dorm, I used power of facts. I gave her a list of reasons in my head as to why it would be beneficial to go out and try new things. I could see she was nervous at first but with my persuasion and kind words I was able to control how she approached a new environment. I felt like my technical peer pressure helped her in a powerful way. By her non-verbal communication I was able to reassure her that things were going to be okay, fun, exciting and empowering. I had the power at that moment.

I was helping someone train at my work one day. I felt a little more rushed and overwhelmed because I was doing more of the word and then having to explain everything to the new person. In the end of the shift I hoped that they actually picked up on a few things so the next time I worked with that person and did not have to my work and also most of theirs.

I was the captain of a dance team and I had to watch them and make sure they were doing routines right.  I was glad so many people relied on me.  I felt as though they all trusted me and I felt more confident in my abilities.  However, I was very stressed when I didn't know routines myself or could not help them.

When i was the main worker at a day care center for my church, all the children there were in my charge. I had to feed them, settle their arguments and make sure they did not joke on something and die ect. Being in charge of them made me feel relaxed because i did not have to prove myself to someone above me, but at the same time I would prefer someone else to be in charge because of something went wrong I would not have to be alone in responsibility. I enjoy a job more when I have a boss of some sort so I know exactly what is expected of me.

I'm in a position of power everyday with my children. I have a 2 year old and a 5 year old, who i am in charge of everyday. I love them very much, and thankful that i have them. i try to teach them right and wrong, moral etc.  I feel that is my duty. I love the job of a parent and feel lucky to have it.

By being captain of my high school dance team, I held the power to move people into forms, judge weather they should make which team, and helped decide if they were captain for the year after i graduated. Many of the dancers that I didn't think were very good were put into the back of forms or didn't make competition team. Most of these dancers thought there were the best on the team and resented me for making these decisions. Being in charge of so much made me very stressed and I hated the way my teammates resented me when I did not do something they wanted.

My senior year of high school, I was the captain of my Varsity volleyball team. I was in charge of captain meetings as well as any problems that had become evident between the girls. I felt honored to have this responsibility yet very pressured because I had never held an important position such as this ever before. I understood better what it took to hold a position in power such as team captain, and thought more of my position on the team.

I was class president of my class so I was the main person to decide our class shirts and who would be in our homecoming skit. I thought I was very fair, because I let anyone participate in the skit. I felt fair having the final say on the class shirts since we had a vote.

I was in a position of power when I worked at a volleyball camp. I was in charge of what they were supposed to do and how they were supposed to go about each drill. It was very uplifting to have people look up to me as a authority figure. They would usually listen to what I had to say and had a greater respect for me than my peers do. Overall It made me feel good to b able to hold the attention of so many different people.

I was a gymnastics captain in high school and I had to report to the coaches which teammates were not participating in exercises, warmups, or who didn't show up to practice. Even though a lot of these kids were my friends I would still report it and it didn't bother me, but they did get in trouble... oddly in the end most of the kids that continuously got in trouble started to look up to me.
A position I was once in was babysitting my brothers. My parents were gone for the night and left me in charge. I just told them what to do and not do. It wasn't that thrilling of a job.

At the place where I work (a daycare) the children needed to turn in their school work to me before being allowed to go play. I felt like this is normal, teaching them that work comes before play is teaching them an essential asset for later in life.

When I babysit I feel that I am in a position of power because I have the ability to control the children and the responsibility to keep them acting politely and kind, and get them to follow the rules their parents have established.  I used to be a nanny and I felt that I was almost a mother figure to the children because I was around them so much, and they sometimes showed respect to me and at other times showed none.  I feel let down when I am not able to control them, and when I am I feel proud of myself.

I was the captain of the soccer team in high school and I felt like I could listen to peoples' opinions and such and make sure everyone felt the team had chemistry and was running smoothly. I enjoyed it but some days got to be a little much.

I think an incident where I am the one in power would be proabably during school. There are speech classes to where the audience would be able to evaluate the person speaking. I often get conflicted emotions to evaluate them on the spot. It's hard to evaluate someone you don't know very well, but it's a task that one has to do to make the person a better speaker.

For about two years, I was the president of my high schools Anime Club. Each year, I was faced with plenty of leadership decisions. One such incident was at the beginning of my senior year, when a few members of the club had gotten into a heated argument and were repeatedly volatile with one another for several weeks. Wanting to preserve a friendly environment in Anime Club, I pulled the three of them aside and presented them with an ultimatum; They had to work out their problems once and for all and leave it out of club meetings permanently, or I would ban them from attending club anymore. Eventually, this lead to truce of sorts. While it was incredibly frustrating to deal with, it was empowering to know that with my leadership position, my word and orders were enough to sway them to stop what they were doing immediately. It wasn't an abusive sort of power I felt, but rather, comforting.

I volunteered at a rehabilitation center where i evaluated the patients progress and helped them achieve recovery. It was very difficult at times to keep the patients attention and teach them ways to cope with their situation. I liked having the power to help them achieve a goal and even though almost all the patients were stubborn at first, they learned to complete the activities that helped them get better.
i was a teacher for an 8th grade class, it was nice to know that they listened to me and valued what i had to say

During course evaluations, i feel i have a chance to tell a professor how i am really feeling or just brush it off and be nice. Unless I have a real problem with a teacher then i will give them a good eval. If not, then i give constructive criticism because no one deserves to be torn down for no reason.

I was in the position of power when I played tennis.  When winning a match, I would feel confident, excited, and powerful.  Events that would occur would be my style of play.  I would play more agressively and go for shots that I would normally not take if I was losing.  In the position of power I would think of myself as a much better player and think of how I could be better and who I was to beat next.

i was a volleyball coach for 11 year old girls and i had the power to decide who made the team and who got cut. my feelings were both excited and scared because i did not want to have to crush any little girl's heart or dreams
I was placed in the "supervisor" postion at my job as a lifeguard. I felt as if I was equal to the rest of the emplyees, just had more respobibilites than they did.
Felt like I was in control and I felt more comfortable giving instructions than being given instructions.

I was in a position of power when I was participating in sorority recruitment.  Because I am already a member of a sorority, I got to talk to the potential new members and judge if I thought they should be in my sorority.  I gave every girl I talked to a score depending on if I wanted her to comeback to the sorority.  I was in power because I got to help decide what sorority they would end up in.  If I talked to a girl that I liked, then I felt happy that I could chose to bring them back, but when I talked to a girl that I did not think was a good fit for the sorority, then I felt bad for them and wanted to give them a higher score then they may have deserved.  When I was talking to each girl, I thought the entire time about how I was going to rate them.

While helping a friend study for a class, I controlled the answers, which would be what they wanted, to questions that I asked them regarding the subject and I also had to evaluate their ability in being able to answer the questions. I feel relatively calm in situations like that and I like being an altruistic person in that position. I also feel as though I'm taking on a very beneficial role. It makes me feel as though I am in a heightened purpose or role.

when i worked in an icecream shop i held a sense of power only because i was put as manager for the shop and i had to regulate the actions being taken by my employees. i felt great and i was very confident in evaluating a situation for my employees
I was baby sitting my younger siblings. They just sit on the couch and play on their phones, so it was really boring for me. They are well behaved so I didn't have to do anything really.

One night my friends and I went to a party and each of them had had quite a bit to drink. Previously during the day my boyfriend said something to my friend but she wouldn't tell me. I know that when she is drunk she always will tell me what I want to know. Because I was the DD for the night I knew if she wanted to go anywhere I would be her way. About two hours in she wanted to go to another party. I told her that was fine but before I took her anywhere she was going to have to tell me what was said. So, I said to my friend very nicely, "hey, what did he say to you earlier?" I didn't want her to think I had been waiting so right when she told me I let it go and acted like I didn't care.

I was a nanny this summer, so I was in this position a lot. For example, if one of the kids didn't do a chore I would threaten to take aware their gaming device if they didn't do it in the next ten minutes. I felt mean at first about it because I don't like being bossy, but they always did the chore so I was okay with doing it. Even though they wined in the beginning, they were fine once they got their game back.

I was captain of the varsity volleyball team in high school. I was in control of my team and it felt good to have some kind of power over them. I didnt take my power too far where I would make them feel bad. I just put my experience and my knowledge of the sport into action. I pushed them to do better and we did get better.

A time when I was in power was when I was the captain of my volleyball team in high school.  I evaluated each individual and when I noticed one girl wasn't doing her part to help our team, I had to step up and talk to that girl.  I felt that I had to put my self at a high standard because I was in a position where I expected something from people.  Sometimes I felt stressed and worried when I had to confront someone regarding their attitude because I didn't want my teammates to dislike me.

I used to work baseball camps back in high school and being a leader of those camps made me feel in power. I would evaluate certain campers and give them instructions on what to do at certain stages or just general advice about the game of baseball. I felt in total control because these kids would believe almost anything I would tell them. I became power hungry. I loved the feeling of controlling the situation and being the figure head.

I was in a position of power when i was Captain of the Varsity track team. I felt that i was very deserving of this position because i would always put forth my best effort. Also, i felt that i was a good leader for the girls. I always kept in touch with them and was sure to know if they were missing practice and for what reason. i did not however, let the title of "Captain" get to my head. i stayed humble through it all and showed everyone that im no better than the rest. I got to also help the coach in deciding who would throw in which event for specific meets. it was a great honor to have a big responsibility and leadership role.

In high school, I was in charge of a very exclusive club at my school.  There were so many people interested in the club that we had to take applications from students and pick who got to participate.  We had a system in which we gave a different number of points for people's application on the application in order to rank the people who wanted to join, but being the leader, I had the overall say of who got into the club and who did not.  It was hard to not let everyone in the club especially if they had a good application or I knew them personally.  I wanted everyone to get accepted but I had to cut a lot of people out which made me feel bad.  I knew that because I had that power that I really needed to pick the people who not only had a good application, but also wanted to get in the most.  It did feel good knowing that people really wanted to join the club based on how many people applied.
I can't recall a time really...I mean maybe a small thing like I had a cookie and they wanted one and I jopking said nahh but then gave them one..but I dont think thats really power..

Yesterday I took another experiment provided by the psychology department. They're experiment made me feel like I was in a position of power because I was able to express my opinion by evaluating certain people without fear of any consequences other than investment of some of my free time. It was enjoyable since the experiment was originally voluntary, and I didn't have to worry about anything but the experiment during that time.

I was in charge of running a meeting and giving out tasks to other group members. My thoughts were all over the place. I had to think and consider all possibilities in order to choose the right people for each task. There was a lot of pressure and responsibility on my shoulders as group leader. I wanted the project to be successful and run smoothly.

While babysitting middleschool aged children, I experienced difficulty in using my power effectively.  While their parents had told them that I was clearly the person in position of power, as I was being paid to watch them, the oldest felt that they were in power because they did not need someone to watch over them and were fully capable of creating rules and providing for themself.  It was extreemly frustrating having no control over the childs want for independence and clear disregard for my rules and demands.  While trying to keep the child safe and happy, I lost control over my position of power and did not know what to do.
It felt good to be in power. It is a huge responsibility to control something all on your own and it makes you feel empowered and strong.
My little sister. Every time I babysat her, I rewarded her by extra time watching television and so i felt power.
Recently had to observe new fencing referees to evaluate their performance. I was nervous and excited to have the responsibility since it was my first time.

When I convinced a friend of mine to change her major the first week of school. She was complaining about her major: Civil Engineering, primarily because of Calculus, which she wasn't very good at. So after I failed to help her understand Calc, I decided that maybe she would be better off dropping the class altogether. She came to me after a quiz and asked me what to do, and I told her to switch majors altogether. I feel as though I helped her made the right choice; she doesn't resent me for it, and she loves Biology, which doesn't require a lot of advanced math.
When I baabysit my cousins im in power over them. This makes me feel good and powerful,but also nervous becasue if something were to happen to them it wpuld be my fault.

There was a time where I had the power over my friend because she had done something wrong and i was the only one who k new about it. I did not blackmail her to the extreem, that would have been wrong in my part. I did get some beneficial things out of that. It felt good to have power even though that power wasnt the best kind of power.

I conducted an experiment in AP stat in high school to see which type of incentive worked better on high school students; positive or negative. (technically positive reinforcement or punishment). It was supposed to be a group project but I decided to take it on myself as I would have more control of the situation. I gathered volunteers and administered three tests, sparing the details of the test exactly i had a baseline, and then one I'd administer positive reinforcement (doughnut) and one where I'd administer punishment (electric shock). During this whole process I had control of everything, materials, the volunteers and the work. In independence I had found power and it felt, while demanding, great.

I was named captain for my high school softball team, and our coach wanted me to hold people accountable and make sure they kept working hard through the season. Though it's not a lot of "power", it still elicited a feeling of being in charge. I felt important and respected not only by the younger teammates but also my coach.
My sister wanted a cookie that I had. There were no more left. So I told her that if she painted my nails for me I would give her the cookie. So she agreed and I gave her the cookie.

I was a hebrew school teacher of about 6 kids. I felt good because they all had a sense of respect for me and looked up to me. It was a good feeling and because they respected me I respected them making them enjoy class more and making me enjoy teaching them more.

The only time I really felt in position of power was whenever i was doing a side project for myself and having others join for fun. I am usually a follower when working with others whenever it comes to classes, but since this was a fun story creating for a show I felt free to do what I wanted with others. I was in charge since the story was using my idea, but the people were friends who would not mind helping. I showed them the outlines, told them what i was planning and they came with ideas for parts I was missing and did the a few designs. Whatever I did not feel right on, they did not mind changing it. We argued on some parts, but it was like arguments that were violent, but rather to get the point across. We also had multiple times of laughing. I still check on the there part of my project to make sure they do not get too caught up on a possible mistake. I tell them in details what is wrong and they accepted. The story project still is not completed since there are classes we have to focus on, but I am making we get to it at least.

I nanny a 6 year old and I am "in-charge" of her. It is my job to determine if she should be rewarded or punished for her actions throughout the day. Sometimes it can be stressful and I have to think about her best interest and what her parents would do in the situation.

When I volunteered at my local hospital back home, I was given the position of the leader of my floor. I was in charge of about four other volunteers (both male and female). I was a little nervous about being the one to evaluate them, but other than that, I was responsible and unbiased with the power given. Everyone had a job and everyone was treated the same. Power isn't something to be used negatively although it usually is. It takes responsibility to be given one.

At the beginning of this year we had try outs for the Men's club volleyball team. I am the president of the club team and ultimately the deciding factor on who makes the team or not. We had two open gyms and then an official try out. After the try out I had to make the decision of who to cut and who to keep on the team. This was a very stressful event for me because I had both friends and former players trying out this year. However, they were not good enough to make the team. I was torn on how I should approach them as well as the right things to say. I didn't want to hurt their feelings but I also had to keep in mind what was best for the team. I ended up sending them an email explaining that they were not on the team, but could still be on the practice squad as needed. After this, seeing them around campus became somewhat awkward and uncomfortable. We would still be friendly to each other but I could sense a bit of resentment.

I don't really have a situation but I guess the best example would be when I was the judge of a Halloween costume contest and I felt I had the power to give the places to the best costume as to my opinion.

In high school, I was on the class council and we were in charge of planning Senior Prom. Some people in the class had outstanding detentions or other issues that prevented us from selling them prom tickets. I felt bad about it because they could not experience the fun prom we planned but at the same time I did not feel badly because it was their own fault for not serving their detentions and even receiving them in the first place.

One position of power I can think of off the top of my head is a time in high school when I played for the soccer team. It was the conference championship game and we went into penalty kicks. I was the one of our last players to take a kick and if I made it we would win the game. If I missed we lost. I felt the pressure of all the fans and my team on my shoulders. Unreal amount of pressure. I ended up missing the shot and we lost the game. Fortunately, it was a game that didn't end our season because we still qualified for state. It was just a game that could have given us a higher seed.

high school track season my senior year i was named sprint captain of two groups the sprinters and hurdlers. whenever they needed help with form or step for relays they always asked me and i as well lead practices and girls workouts when the coach was absent doing paper work and placing girls in their next event for future meets based on times.

I was president of student senate and for homecoming. I was the main person instructing events and prep rally and also In this event, I was to pass out candy to individuals. People swarmed, cheered, and yelled for candy. Even though it was small, it was weird, but nice to see the power i had over them. They all tried to convey me to give them candy or they tried to sneak up and steal it from me. This made me feel go about my self. I gave candy to those who cheered the most and left the people who were trying to steal without any.

The event was voting for my sorority's elections of officers. I felt like I should pick the people who best fit the position best by their personalities. I felt bad when I sometimes didn't pick my friends for the position because I felt like I was obligated to.

While I was in high school I was part of a committee that decided things that the school needed. By doing this we represented the student body as a whole but the complete student body never had a say but the effects of our decisions still had an impact on their experiences.

As captain of my volleyball team I had to chose a girl trying out to fill one more position for the team. It came down to two girls who I liked a lot so it was a very hard and stressful decision. I didnt want to have to say no to both of them and had to go with my gut.

I believe that when it comes to power, women have the same mutual power over men. For men, the situation had started with a relationship with a man and ended with him wanting sex from me. I do not believe that men need sex more than women but I'm just implying that men lack the sense of control that most women possess when it comes to sex.  I wouldn't consider this as one situation because it has happened multiple times and I'm sure that it will happen again.  The most powerful men in society can appear to be the weakest, vulnerable human beings when it comes to a woman. The funny thing is that she doesn't even have to be pretty, as long as she has boobs and a vagina, men will change their whole lives to get in bed with them.

Last time was when I was working in a group for a class presentation. I started just kind of dividing the work among us, and the others accepted it. I took charge of the group and project. It felt satisfying, I like being in that position.
At work I was a trainer for Starbucks. It was nerve-wracking, kept you on your best work ethic, and extremely focused.

When being the one to decide if my younger cousins were going to get McDonald's or sandwiches for dinner, I felt greatly superior to them.  Not only did they have to clean their rooms but they had to clean them according to my standards.  I felt a great deal of responsibility.  Even though they were not cleaning their rooms for my liking and only doing it to get the food they wanted, I still felt as though they didn't want to disappoint me.  I kind of thought about how easy it would be to get them to do whatever else i wanted by just controlling what they got for dinner.  Almost like I had never-ending power.

The first thing that came to mind is when I would baby set growing up. Since I was significantly older than the kids I would be watching it felt appropriate for them to listen to me. If I was watching kids that I new very well I would feel comfortable and for the most part have fun with the job. With kids I did not know well, I would feel anxious because of the fear of their parents judging me for not directing them the correct way.

In volleyball practice when I am blocking. If I block the ball that means that the other person has failed. I feel really good about myself and excited and full of emotion. The person I blocked feels bad, almost disappointed and has to think, how am i going to improve so that I do not hit the ball into the block next time.

I used to be the president student council. Every time we had a meeting or hosted an event everyone turned to me looking for direction and insight. I liked this because it made me feel important and ultimately things would go my way. Of course I was open minded to the ideas of others, but if something was completely against my personal feelings I could disregard them. I felt strong and proud to be in this position.

An incident when I was in a position of power was when I used to babysit because I made the decisions of when the child I was watching should go to bed, do their hw, etc. Making the decisions for another person definitely comes with responsibility.

I was chosen to be the captain of my volleyball team my freshman and sophomore year in high school. I used this position to instruct people on the court about where they needed to be and when. It was hard being in this position because I did not want people to think I was being bossy or rude because I was telling them what to do.

I was captain of my soccer team my senior year of high school and made other people carry the equipment so I would not have to. It may have came across as mean, but I did it when I was an underclassman so I did not feel that way. It was more of a "rite of passage" I guess for me.

I used to be a key holder at a retail store, so I controlled the inner workings of the store as well as things like recommendations for reviews. It was simple things like bathroom breaks that made me feel really uncomfortable, another person should not be allowed to tell you when you can go pee.

I had the opportunity to promote someone to a leadership position. It usually goes to the candidate with the highest seniority. But I promoted the applicant with the least seniority simply because he qualifies extremely well better than all the others. I was questioning my self at the time whether I did the right thing. I was also given the leadership based on my seniority. I felt like an unethical person but did the right thing for the organization. Finally when people realized that was the right decision, they started appreciating it but mainly did the opposite in due time.

I got placed as a team leader for the day at my work place. I got to be in charge and help my team do the best to succeed. It was kind of overwhelming because I had people coming to me for help and I was the one that had to give them the right answer. It was also stressful because I had the managers watching  my every move. If I messed up it was all on me, and if anyone on my team messed up I was also to blame. Overall it was a great experience that tested my leadership skills and tested me on how well I can handle stress.

i worked at a daycare, and was in constant control of the children who were under my supervision. i felt empowered, but also felt a duty to oblige to make sure every child in my care was well taken care of

I was an executive member of Student Council in high school, the Vice President to be specific. There was an elected member that was not performing his job very well and it was reflecting badly on the rest of council. The executive council met and discussed the idea of impeaching him. All of the members were very harsh about his performance and about his character. I agreed that he was not doing his job well but I considered his age and that he was inexperienced and just needed some guidance. Still the others decided to put him up for impeachment. When the idea was presented at the next council meeting he was upset by this news and I felt bad for him and I felt awful standing next to the people telling him that. The next week he presented a speech to try and persuade people to vote for him to stay. He was not very popular at school and in council so it was not helpful. I still had not decided which way I would vote but hearing everyone say bad things about him behind his back made me feel terrible. I knew he had done a terrible job but I felt he could be helped. I still voted for him to be impeached, and hoped he would still come back. He was impeached and never returned to council again. I loved is passion for council and after that vote it was lost. It's only in retrospective that I realize how much power was given to myself and the other members, and at the same time how little. We are powerless to the mob mentality and now I wonder if the much power should be given to people that age.

I was instructing my coach's son in horseback riding and was in a position of power because of being able to tell him what to do in order to improve his riding abilities. I felt very uncomfortable because my coach (and his mother) was there watching and listening. I thought I would make a mistake or tell him something wrong and she would be upset that I was giving the wrong instructions since she knows more than I do about the sport and how to teach it.
Once i went shopping with my mom and cried so i could get what i wanted.

Last Sunday, I was passing out tickets for a fundraiser event at our church. I was instructed by the priest that the tickets are for church members over the age of 18 only; However, I was approached by a lady who wanted a ticket for her younger son, so I refused. I was assertive and told the lady that the instructions were clear from the priest that the tickets are solely for individuals above the age of 18. The lady got upset with me and I started getting more assertive by raising my voice a little (I did feel a little angry and frustrated at this point since it seemed very simple and straightforward). Finally, I told her to go speak to the priest about getting a ticket for her younger son if this is truly a major issue that she needs solved. When the lady went to the priest, I did feel belittled and a little shy that I had almost no authority over the little conflict that occurred.

An incident when a friend needed to borrow a textbook from someone but she knew it won't be given to her. She pleaded that I ask for the textbook on her behalf as the person was more likely to give it to me because of the relationship I had with that person. I could see the desperation in my friend and enjoyed having the power to determine if she gets the textbook or not. I however was ready to help as helping people makes me happy, so I readily obliged her request.

I was in a position of power at my last part-time job. I was the senior on shift therefore I had most experience working and was able to encourage my coworkers to complete their tasks and work efficiently. I did not feel "bossy" or in command, but I did feel respected and mature compared to my other coworkers because I knew that they were looking up to me and expected me to lead the directions and ensure that our shift of work went well. It felt good being the leader but it was also stressful because if there was a mistake, I would be the one to blame.
This summer I was a nanny. Every day I was responsible for the child; she was really sweet and almost always listened to what I told her to do. I love her very much.

The most recent one is the teacher evaluations. Students have to evaluate the teachers or professors. It is a way of expressing my thoughts about some mean and nice profs. It feels like i'm finally allowed to express my thoughts about the courses, I feel very relieved

Group project.  After completing a group project, i was asked to evaluate my peers, some of which did not do their job effectively. during this evaluation i felt somewhat stressed, and was thinking about how to give the evaluation; whether to correctly state their unsatisfactory work efforts or to just give them a good evaluation based on personal knowledge.
When my friend was in a bad relationship, she was hurt, depressed and wanted the relationship to work at all cost. So i made effort to talk to the guy and he changed, and today they are both happy.
A friend wanted to use my speaker, i was hesitant but knew i would get something out of it down the road.

Being in power over something that you are knowledgeable about is a good feeling. I am an experienced artist and at different workshops I have taught several people new things. Its a good feeling to be good at something and acknowledged for it
i was with my sister, and every time she would do something that i did not like, i would tell her to stop, and she would get punished. I felt powerful somehow, because she obeyed me, and i felt good.

The time when I was in a situation of power was when I became the president of the peer mediation program in my high school. I had to help run meditations, evaluate new comers, and help plan important events and trips for the program. This made me feel very good as a person because I love working with people. Being the president of the club taught me many things as far as leadership skills and power.

On the crew team I was in a position to put everyone in a mindset to be able to finish the particularly hard workout we were doing. With my words I controlled how pumped they could be to finish, and if I did not to my job then many would not have finished.

A few weeks ago, one of my colleagues was in desperate need of an editor for her video she had to submit the following day. She asked me to do it because I am a video editor, but I said I was very busy and couldn't do it. She told me she was desperate, and I realized I could ask for something in return; in fact, I could ask for anything. I was in power because she needed to me to edit the video. I decided to ask her for some money in exchange and she quickly accepted. I edited the video and got the amount of money in return. I felt very satisfied with my decision.

A particular instance I was in power would be when I was the only one of my friends who had a license. I would be the only one able to drive and thus a lot of what we did that night depended on my ability or willingness to drive somewhere. I would feel good that everyone depended on me, but I would also be annoyed that they almost always relied on me. A thought I had was "I can't wait for everyone to get their license."

When I almost got into a accident when it was not my fault. An old lady almost hit me. She did not know how to react when we both pulled off the road. I had power and told her that she was not doing the right thing in that intersection. I was angry and mad. I probably should not have told her she was wrong but she almost hit my car! I had a lot of emotions during this event.

A lot of my friends come to me to seek advice or to have someone listen to them and I feel a lot of pride in that. That being the ability to have people confide in me and it's empowering but also overwhelming because I do not experience power a lot of the time, I tend to identify more as a follower rather than a leader, so it's a good feeling, but also a bit odd to be in a different position than I am used to.

I am a gymnastics coach.  I had a new coach shadow me for a time recently, in which I critiqued her coaching and taught her how our gym functions.  She did something that was not the best decision, so I had to tell her that and what a better decision would have been.  I was slightly nervous to tell her, because I am not her boss I am just a more experienced coach, but she had to know to not do similar things in the future.  She was thankful for my advice in the end.

I was a coach for a youth lacrosse league for multiple years. I had the ability to run the players if they were misbehaving or not listening. I also had the power to personally teach them specific skills. I enjoyed the attention and admiration I received from such a young group, and enjoyed watching them learn and grow. I was never tempted to employ punishment solely because I had the power to do so, I only punished athletes of whom misbehaved.

President my high school christian club in which I organized the events that we were going to conduct over the school year. I was able to make individuals in the club to cooperate and work on this project by requiring certain tasks to be done. It was a lot of work but it wasn't too difficult to manage at the time.

I am captain of the cross country team. Everyday I could make decisions that overruled others. For example, I could choose what exercises to do before practice no matter how difficult. Even if my teammates complained I made them do it anyway because I knew they would be benefiting. During times like this I feel frustrated when others question my logic or complain for the sake of doing so.

I was the varsity tennis captain in high school. I had to lead practice and make sure my girls were always on time and giving 100%. I felt like I had a lot of responsibility. At some points I felt pressured, but it was rewarding. I often thought about how I could better my girls and how I could get them to show up on time.

I was fighting with a friend and they wanted to come to a party with me but knew they couldnt come if i was still mad at them for what they did so i had the control over they went to the party or not. i was mad cuz of what they did and didnt feel sorry because they messed up, they then went from being sad to mad and then i just didnt care because i had a fun night and they didn't

When I was in a situation of power, I felt very in control of my emotions as well as the people surrounding me. However, with responsibility comes anxiety and perfection. The situation was when I was captain of a sports team and I had the final decision over team gear.

When I was a summer camp assistant this past year, I was able to direct children to different activities and get them to follow directions (like "sit down" or "please be quiet and listen"). I was in a position of power, but I didn't use my power as the adult or assistant teacher to hurt or take control of the campers in a harmful way.

I was helping someone with their homework.  I was abler to finish it by myself, but they were stuck and needed to get it done since it was due.  During the time I felt anxious to make sure they were able to get it done on time.  Also I thought I needed to provide a good explanation on how to do the problem so they wouldn't need help on it again.

My sister wanted a piece of candy that I had, so I told her that she would have to do whatever I wanted for the next hour. I felt in control and powerful because she would do whatever I told her to do in order to get the candy.

In high school I was the captain of the softball team. At first I liked the idea of being in power and being in control. That soon changed when I realized the responsibility of being a leader. As the team began to slack, it was my job to pick them up and motivate them to do better. During this time, the team would get punished for their lack of effort and the coach blamed me for this. When I tried to motivate them, they just became angry with me and didn't like that I was in control. I didn't like the feeling of telling others what to do and having to discipline other people my age. I thought I would like being captain, but I didn't at all.

The most recent situation where I was in a position of power was at the grocery store with my brother and he wanted a pack of gum. I only brought enough money to buy what we needed and didn't have enough to buy his pack of gum. He was upset and I felt bad I didn't use my debit card to purchase the gum for him, but I was low on money and didn't want to waste it on gum.
When I was a dance instructer I was able to evaluate and critique technique of individuals.  I often felt uneasy doing so.

I was in charge of an event where I had to create a dance and soundtrack, teach other students the dance and perform it in a show. It was important to impress our audience so I wanted to make sure everyone knew the dance well, but my main focus was for everyone to enjoy themselves because the dance would ultimately look terrible if they weren't having fun doing it. I was in control of 12 girls and the production itself along with two other girl's who had their own group of 12 girls and a dance. I felt a lot of pressure to do as well as the girl's had done in the years before me, excitement to perform, nervous on the day of the event and powerful that I could make the dance look exactly as I wanted. I was also nervous about other's expectations and out performing the other two girls. I did feel slightly uneasy at first because I didn't want to be an over bearing leader, but I did want them to listen and take direction.
I was president of the band and chorus at my high school. I enjoyed being able to create change in a positive way and leading underclassmen to be proactive in the chorus and the band in the future

My senior year of high school, I was captain of the cheer team. I remember that there was a junior on my team that thought she had the ability to input her say over mine, and it felt very belittling. Here I was, the captain of the team, being put down by one of my fellow team mates. It made me feel small. Then one day, I decided to take power into my own hands, and pulled her aside to let her know that it was my call that was going to matter. If I was going to say something, she was going to listen. I remember feeling very bad and guilty for calling her out, but after she told me she respected my authority, I felt relieved.

I was a manager of a large school store. I helped determine their grade in the class and was in charge of their duties. It was difficult managing students older then me and the same age but it was a great experience.

I was a stage manager. I was constantly concerned about the emotional state the my crew was  under. I understood that the time we put in was very difficult combined with academics and that our director was not always emotionally supportive. So I was constantly trying to make up for what they were lacking from her. When I had to be strict or stern it worried me because what I wanted was better or more efficient work, and not to lose a friend. Although I had come to the conclusion that a friend would understand the postion I was in. It was very pleasing and satisfying to see the end product (the play and all its components) and to see everyone so pleased with what we had accomplished, and pleased with their individual work. It was stressful work but definetly rewarding.

During my senior year of high school, I was secretary of the National Honor Society. At the end of the year during May, we held our annual Induction Ceremony where we inducted the new members (juniors) into the society. It was part of my job to ensure that the new members attended the rehearsal and knew what to do throughout the ceremony. I felt authoritative, in control and a little stressed. I felt some stress because I had to make a speech and wanted the ceremony to go smoothly and professionally. I was also excited because the Induction Ceremony is the biggest event for National Honor Society and being part of the board felt good.

Being a TA is an interesting feeling. I am more knowledgeable in the subject than the students that I help, but I certainly don't know everything. I need to help them without giving away answers. I feel good when students understand something after struggling with it, but I feel inadequate when they ask me a question that I don't know the answer to.

It was stressful because they would all want to tell me what they think they should be doing and what they should get, but i was the one to decide everything that happened. i got frustrated easily and often times got angry when they wouldnt listen.

I was put in charge of writing and directing my schools traditional play at the end of senior year.   Every year it is different, because the play is based off of teachers, students, and jokes within the graduating class.  So, as expected, students came up to me and asked if their joke/idea could be used.  I felt happy that they felt trusting enough to tell me their joke, and write it into the play the way I would envision it.  However, I also felt bad at times because most of the time students had jokes that were to offensive that it would be highly inappropriate for me to include their jokes.  However, knowing that their jokes would not be in the play (due to them being in it), I had to tell them that it could not be in the play.  I felt that I did the right thing.   I was trying to make everyone happy.
I have been in this situation when I am babysitting.  I enjoy babysitting so my feelings were happy.  I do not feel an extreme confidence or power when I was in control of a situation.
I felt very unsure of myself and would take back my directions if the person below me made enough fuss

At my job I used to supervise someone who I really do not like and who really does not like me due to a preexisting conflict where we ceased being friends. She got paranoid that I was trying to make her look bad so she requested a change in supervisor. My boo and I discussed the matter and my boss told me that she believed this person was all over the map and not being consistent or accurate. I agreed and due to poor feedback from her costumers we took away one of her shifts. I felt to delicious about the whole thing because my supervisor was supporting my beliefs that this person was a mess.

This summer, I was the captain of my travel soccer team. I was able to control different situations and evaluate my team members. It was a sense of power to me. I normally don't like being the center of attention, but soccer is something I love to do so I felt good about it.
I can't think of anything at the moment.

I am the only one of my roommates who has a car so i have the power of being able to control when we go and get groceries and other products. I try to make it fit more into my schedule but i don't necessarily like the ability to have power over other people. I think that it is easier to let everyone have a say and not use the power negatively.

I work in Terraces dining hall here as a student manager. This means that every time I work, I am in a position of power over all of the student workers (who are mostly freshmen). I can tell them to do things, re-do things if they did not do them well enough, get things for me or help me with things, etc. I love having that power over someone else; it makes me feel not better them, but in a better place than them. I love being able to tell people what to do and to be able to control situations.
I was in my dorm room with a bunch of guys on my floor and I controlled what we watched on the t.v. Everyone was laughing and having a good time.

I'm a ref so every weekend I control multiple soccer games. I have to keep the parents, players and coaches in check. It is a demanding job because the parents take the games too seriously considering it is rec soccer. I like my job because it pays well and it's easy when the parents behave. It has taken me many years to get as confident as I am now. I used to take the screaming parents very personally when I was 14 and it seemed to me the parents did not realize that I was only two or three years older than their daughters on the field.

On Halloween when I was younger I used to be the best at trick or treating. Because of this I had a large amount of candy that all my friends were jealous and envious of. Often, my friends would want my candy and I'd only give it to them if they did something for me. It felt really good to control my friends and have them do whatever I needed them to do.

I had an extra ticket to a red sox game and all my friends wanted to go.   They were all trying to do me favors and get on my good side so i would take them.   During this time i was able to get them to do certain things for me, like do clean my car etc.   It felt good being in this positions since i had control over my freinds in regard to the game.  IT made me feel confident, strong, and happy to be in this type of situation, but at the same time, sad because i could only take on of my friends which means i would let down 3 others.
I was the leader of a group for a school project. If I didn't keep everyone on task, we wouldn't have gotten a good grade. It was hard, but I liked being in charge.

A particular time I was in a position of power was when I was about ten years old and I was in school. I was at lunch with my friends and we were trading baseball cards. I wanted a derek jeter card and my friend had it. I controlled the situation by forcing him to give me the card for my pudding by telling him how worthless the card was and how great the pudding was. When in actuality it was in reverse and the card was better than the pudding.

A time when I was in a position of power was when I was a captain on my soccer team. I could delegate who did what in terms of set up and pick up and was I was also responsible for voicing my opinions with my coach about individual player's performances. This made me feel like I had a great deal of burden on my shoulders, but it also made me think that it was now my duty to set the example and try to be the best individual I could be. With that responsibility I would have to make the correct decisions and always act appropriately. It was strenuous but beneficial.

at the summer camp i worked at there was a situation where the cops were called because of a trespasser came on to the camp ground acting very inappropriate in front of little kids. A lot of people dint know how to handle the situation, so i had to take control and mediate then situation

While attending boarding school, all the students were required to be on a cleaning team. Some students had the opportunity to be the head of a cleaning team, which counted as their job. My job was running the kitchen cleaning team. I supervised the girls who were cleaning the dining hall after breakfast, lunch, and dinner. If they were not cleaning properly, my job was to notify them of what they were doing wrong, and what they can do to improve in the future. I really enjoyed this job because I was also able to help the cooks before and after meals. I also got really close to the chefs on a personal level, and they helped me work through a lot of my issues, and for that I am eternally grateful.

I am not often in a position of power. I do not like the idea of controlling the ability of another person to get what they want. I taught elementary school students in Guatemala last summer and I was in a position to evaluate those individuals. The situation was enjoyable and fun and I rarely had to exercise power over anyone unless I was asking the children to calm down, participate better, stay on course, etc. Overall, it was a rewarding experience.

I was the President of National Honor Society in my senior year of high school. I was the leader on the executive board and the club overall, so during meetings I was in charge of how events were planned, who played what role, and what ideas were to be carried out. I loved being able to hold a powerful position but only because I was not limiting one's abilities, I was guiding the progress toward achieving meaningful and helpful goals for the community.

I am going in to teaching so I substitute teach often.  I am in power of the classroom and dictate for lack of a better word the children in the class. I guess I would say I enjoy being in power and having control.  It angers me when I am not in control and the children do not listen.  These feeling apply to other situations in which I was in power as well/.

When I was in a position of power I felt happy and comfortable. I thought that now people were looking up to me because I was in power. And lots of people would suck up to me because they knew I was in power.

A time when I was in the position of power was when I turned 18 years old. I felt liberated because I could make my own decisions regarding my well-being at the time. It was a bit overwhelming because I still considered myself to be a child. However, when it came to making my own choices I felt in control.

I worked as a camp counselor one summer and I was responsible for the happiness and safety of the campers.  It was a good experience and I enjoyed having that responsibility.  It could get overwhelming when the kids weren't cooperative, but those situations only helped me develop stronger authoritative skills.
A relationship that I was not as into as the girl. she would try very hard to keep the relationship going, but I put in minimal effort.

When I was with my fraternity brothers doing a recruitment event, we had to tell the pledges to clean up.Even though we all were around the same age, I still had power over them because of the social hierarchy within the organization. I felt like I was superior to them in a sense, the superiority didn't make me treat them any differently but I know that what I said do was basically law.
I hosted a party. I felt stressed out but also in control.

I was the captain of a soccer team. I was in charge on the field and led practices and training occasionally. I felt in control and respected, but also felt like I needed to be held to a higher standard.

I was captain of the soccer team in high school. The position made me feel uncomfortable since I didn't see myself being any better than the other players on the team. I would seldom assert my power for fear of being ridiculed.

I was at work, and my boss asked me to get something done but he specifically told me to delegate it to someone else.  I felt encouraged that my boss had confidence in my leadership skills, but I also felt a little bit anxious, as I do not like to tell others what to do.  But, my boss clearly told me to delegate the task so I did.

At work, people are dependent upon me to get food to serve to our customers, so I was able to control the ability of the server's on whether or not they would be able to serve them. I felt very rushed and stressed, but in the end everything always turned out positively.
I edited stories for my school newspaper. I had the ability to slightly alter contributing writer's work. I enjoyed editing.

when i was the captain of my high school field hockey team. I would direct them by telling them what drills we would do, where games and practices were and when they needed to be places. This was sometimes stressful, mostly fun and a great way to make connections with girls on the team

I was a camp counselor for multiple summer, the last being 2 years ago. I was the head counselor and was in charge of campers, a junior counselor and a counselor in training. I was told to evaluate the progress of the jr counselor and the counselor in training and report back every tuesday. Throughout the week I helped both become better leaders and helped them find a voice within the group.
I haven't actually had any real experiences of power. The only one i can really remember involved what restaurant me and my friend went to because it was my decision.

I was in a position of power at work because I was in charge of training the new girls coming in.  I was in control of the tasks they completed in order to be trained properly.  When I was training the new workers, I felt important.
When drove to cinnci over the weekend i was able to decided how many people i wanted to come with me and who i would allow

In my fantasy league I have the best running back. Everyone wants him I have the ability to sell him at a very high price. I there for sold him for 3 great players and I now win many Match ups. I feel great I thought it was a good move.

When I was leaving my receptionist job to go to school for the fall I had to train the new  incoming girl. I had power in telling her how to do things and I could tell her to do my job while I just sat there with her. Eventually I did not sit with her anymore and let her do it on her own but I was still at work. I felt that she was capable to do the job because it was not a hard task so I didn't think there was a purpose for me to sit with her all the time.

When I was a senior on our volleyball team I felt as though I could lead the team.  I could watch and help the underclassmen.  I felt good being able to lead and be a influential player.  I especially felt this way when I ran a volleyball team for younger girls.  I could tell them to do whatever I wanted and they would have to listen because i was the coach.
