I was in a position of power when I was a camp leader this summer. I led my students through their day to day activities and made sure they were doing what they were supposed to be doing. It felt good  because I was able to practice my ability to teach.

I have been in a position of power, when I was working for my internship this past summer.  I was given the task of teaching all of the other interns the process of walking and mapping for the devices that we were looking for.  It felt great knowing that I was able to teach these people, a lot of them older than me, how to do this procedure.  On top of that, it felt great knowing that my direct bosses believed that I could handle this job and teach the other interns properly.

I was captain of the crew team my senior year of high school so I had a lot of power. I was able to direct people to places I wanted them be or make them do things they were supposed to do. It made me feel like I was in control of the situation at all times which made me feel good.

I was captain of the golf team.  I felt like I was a leader and I had a responsibility to be there for the team if need be; I also felt that I had to play well in events and tournaments to show that I deserved the position.

I think babysitting would count as a situation in which I was in power. For example, I have the power to decide when to make dinner, and thus when they get to eat. I guess it doesn't feel like power as much as responsibility when I'm actually babysitting though. I'm responsible for taking care of the kids and making sure they get fed when they're hungry and follow their parents' rules.

In school I was on the treasury committee and I was on the board that decided who gut funding for their group, activity, etc. I would say that's a pretty powerful position considering I helped determine whether what they wanted got funding or not.

My fraternity was having a party and  I could control whether or not my ex-girlfriend was allowed to come. I told her not to, and it made me feel as if I was in control of my life and that I finally had some degree of power over her.

A time in which i was in power was the last time i was baby sitting. When i went home i needed some extra spending money so i babysat for my neighbor. It was alright i told him what to do so thats good

One incident where I was in a position of power was when I captained my high school volleyball team.  Our coach tended to put a lot of responsibility on me, making me help choose practice plans and even discipline the girls on the team.  It was liberating to be able to plan drills, because the coach was usually unsuccessful and not at all creative, but attempting to keep order on the team without the ability to take players out of games or control lineups was extremely unpleasant.

As a team leader for a class project I was in power. I had the power to allocate jobs for the project and essentially tell people what to do. It felt good to be able to decide what everyone would do and not be objected to being told what to do myself. Being given that power made me feel confident. It also gave me some anxiety as I worried I would be blamed for anything that went wrong or that member of my team would become resentful of my seemingly superior position in the group.

Senior year of highschool I was a cheerleader and was captain of my squad. i had to help, teach, and instruct 15 other girls. It was alot of fun but definitely put some pressure on myself. I had to teach the other girls a dance I had made up. We made formations and taught the girls the moves and counts. It was definitely a position of power because I was the one in charge. My coach was helpful but we had to do most of the work, she just was over seeing our progress.
My senior year of high school I was a judge for my high school'd dance team. I felt i had a great deal of power over the other girls because i decided if they made the team or not.

My senior year of high school I was editor-in-chief of my journalism class. As editor-in-chief I had the power to ask the staff for favors and assign them things to do. I also had the power to correct them and teach them. On many instances if I felt lazy and did not want to get an interview I would just ask one of the staff members to get it for me. Having so much power felt very good but it was also stressful because if something went wrong then the blame would go to me. Overall I think it is a great experience and I think everyone should be in a position of power at least once to see how it feels.

An example of this would of been my senior year. I was a senior captain on the soccer team, I was president of the school spirit club, and was class vice president. I was in control of a lot of different things and having the power was very nice.

I am on an executive board for my sorority. When someone gets in trouble, I have the power to decide what their punishment should be along with some other board members. When one of my friends was in trouble, I had to listen to what had happened and help decide what her punishment should be. It was difficult because she was my friend so I wanted to be lenient but I knew I had to treat her like everyone else. So, I tried to be as unbiased as possible and give her the punishment she deserved.

In high school when I was a senior on the football team the coach asked for my input on who I thought should start as the safety opposite me. It was a good feeling knowing that the coach trusted my input enough to use it in the decision making process for who should start at that position. I was honored knowing this and I took it upon myself to really look at the other guys and how they worked and how well they could read plays in order to make my decision.
I was the capitain of my hockey team sophmore year and felt impowered because i was respected.

I have held many positions of power through out my life.  Some of these include elected positions, appointed positions, management promotions, or committee heads.  The time I felt most in power was the time I was hired by my local city government.  It was a fairly good job, with an fair salary.  I felt most in control when I was told that I had two staff members working for me in my department.  I was certainly excited, as I like being in control.

In high school I was the leader of a certain club. I was able to assign people to activities, responsibilities and other things. I felt in control and in power. I like being in power so it was a good feeling because I could make the decisions that I thought were good and see how they worked out.

A situation in which I was in charge is whenever I babysit. I am in control of what they are doing and I have power over the children in the time being that I am babysitting them. In my opinion it is nothing special to be in power. Some people like being a leader and being in charge, but for me I do not care for the situation.

I was the cheer captain at my high school. A number of times I was responsible for practices so we could all get what we wanted, a win and to look very talented. I do not mind being in charge, when it is something I know very well I like to be the one in charge making the decisions.

Throughout high school I was a member of the Rush Junior Auxiliary Board which is a board of about 80 high school girls who raise money in various ways for the Chicago Memorial Hospital. On this board I was the vice president of sales which meant I was basically in charge of the things we sold at our various fundraising events throughout the year. As the year came to a close, the entire senior executive board held meetings with the girls who applied to be on the executive board in the following year. I was in charge of choosing who would replace me as the vice president of sales and this left me feeling very powerful. I also found it stressful because multiple girls applied for my position and I felt bad letting girls down. The power was stressful but also rewarding.

I was in a position of power when I had to be a judge for a show case perform at my high school. I was picked random to be a judge. As a judge we had to pick the top three places. The event show cased many different types of talent. There were people who knew how to perform well and others that were there for the fun of it. When it came down to actually picking a winner I felt very stressed. I didn't want to hurt anyone's feeling, which made it more difficult to pick a winner. In the end since it was a competition I knew I would have to choose a winner. I had the power to pick who the winner would be. I don't think I would want to do something like this again.

I was a camp counselor for three summers so I was in charge and in control of 8-12 children each week, and my final summer I was also in control of several other counselors. I did my best to help my co-workers and the kids too. They are all still people and I am not one to abuse power. I just like to help and my skills often lend themselves to a leadership position.

Sophomore year of college I was elected as new member educator for my sorority. I was in charge of holding meetings to inform the new members about our chapter's history and significance, and to make up ice breaker challenges so that they would be able to get to know each other better.
My senior year of high school, I was captain of my varsity poms squad. I had complete control of the team. I felt very powerful and enjoyed leading everyone.
I was a qb. I controlled the offensive side of the game. When my team won I received the credit and when we lost I got the blame
I am in a position of power in my workplace. I am a manager of a pool, so i can tell snack bar people to take out the garbage or to tell lifeguards to send another guard up in the chair.

During Fraternity rush, I was in a position that impacted whether some of the prospective candidates were given a bid or not. It was an interesting occurrence because these prospective candidates were nicer to me than they would have most likely have been if I was not in this position, hence I was put on a pedestal in their eyes. Although short-lived, it made me feel powerful

In high school I was on dorm aid duty at night in the dorm and I was in charge of making sure all 50 of the girls in the dorm were behaving and were being quiet. Having the authority and being the "one in charge" was a strange feeling because you dont have that power until you are a junior. Therefore i was always use to having to respect the dorm aid on duty but instead it was my turn. I felt confident and was excited it was finally my time.

I have been in a group, we co-work to finish the course task. I was the group leader and I needed to finish evaluation after we handed the task. I felt it was imporatnt to evaluate my group members because it would direrctly affect their grade, which means I was responsible for them. I should be very serious and just for the evaluation. So I did my best to objectly evaluate how they work together and how contributed each individual. I did not feel like it but I did not feel hate it either, I just feel I need to be careful with it.

I helped run a tryout this past summer for a summer baseball team. Along with my friend, we were in charge of evaluating the players and giving them a grade for each of the parts of the tryout. This was putting me in a position of power because I controlled whether or not the kids would make the team based on my grade. Throughout the tryout, I kept thinking to remain unbiased and completely fair. I felt as though I did this successfully, but I couldn't help but feel guilty when I marked down a bad grade or wrote a bad comment about a player.

I was babysitting my cousin who is 10 and he wanted to go to a movie so i took him and his sisters to the movie where he wanted every snack and treat he saw and I had the money to pay for everything so i told him he could only have one and he got frustrated but i told him he cant have it all right now. He stopped pouting and picked the sour patch kids and i bought them and we went to the movie. I was annoyed that he couldn't control himself and that he didn't know after 10 years that he cant possibly eat all those snacks and that his mom probably lets him get them.

I was an NHS officer in high school, and I helped decide who would be chosen as a replacement after I graduated. Each prepared and gave a speech and were asked a series of short answer questions as to why they were the best candidate.

I was babysitting my nephew who was 4 at the time. He was really wanting to eat some chocolate cake for lunch but I couldn't let him have that as a meal. It was a weird feeling for me to control what another person was eating. I am the youngest child so I had never really babysat before. Also, being a college student I sometimes eat cake or ice cream for a meal so it felt hypocritical that I had to tell him he could not do that.
I felt sorry for those individuals, as I am usually very nervous when someone else is in a position to "evaluate" me.

During summer, I was a manager in a clothing store. All of employee obey my orders everyday. I think it is a good experience. Someone listen to you. I have power to control everything. However, I also have a responsibility to the whole thing.
When I was a coach.  I taught players how to perform better.  I felt good about what I was doing

When I was captain of the volleyball team. I was able to make decisions for the team about what our jerseys/spirit wear would look like, about the food we would have at tournaments, our music playlists during practice. I liked to be in control

I was part of my fraternity's E-Board last year. From this position I was able to evaluate the needs of my fellow brothers and bring them to the other E-Board members to better the functionality of the house. A specific incident of this was when we were looking for ways to better brotherhood involvement when it came time for recruitment. Many younger brothers voiced their opinions to me and through effective communication strategies I was able to help implement a new recruitment program for this coming year. These brothers were satisfied with my efforts and the current program is being put to the test this week. I felt very excited about the program when I first presented it and am now impressed by the results that we are getting from my work.

I was helped lead at my church's children group, Awana, and the children had to recite verses to the leaders. As a reward for correctly reciting Bible verses, the children receive an Awana dollar and the leaders sign their name in the part of the book that lists the memory verse. When children would recite the verse to me, I controlled whether or not they did not need to work on the verse more and if they were able to get their reward yet. Sometimes, children would get frustrated at how long it was taking them to remember the verses. When a child would recite the verse(s) to me and did not get it correct, it was not pleasant to tell them they needed to work on the verse some more.

At an internship I had last summer, I was in a position of power because I controlled whether people got paid based on how I said they behaved that day.  If they behaved well then my boss would pay them for that day. However, if they did something disruptive or hurtful to another person they would be deducted in pay for that day.  I felt like i had control over the situation.  I was very easy going, only reporting an incident if it was very disruptive.

I often babysit. When the kids want something that I know I can't let them have, I always feel bad end up saying no anyway because I know that's not what their parents want for them. I don't enjoy being in power over other people.

When I used to babysit kids in my neighborhood, I had power over them. I could tell them when to go to bed and basically tell them what to do. It felt like I was in control of them and they had to obey my rules and I. It feels like I have more strength and can do more then them.

In middle school, I was the president of student council. One night, we held a fundraiser for kids in grades K-8. This fundraiser was like a game night, so different classrooms held different games. As I was observing each room, one particular room, and girl, caught my attention. There was this little kindergartener girl who kept trying to win a dessert from the dessert walk. She was probably in there for 45 minutes. Eventually, she gave up, crying, feeling disappointed. I noticed this and decided to let her choose two desserts because I felt bad. Once I saw her face and how happy she was, I felt great inside. I love helping people out, and I love being able to just say she could do it because of the position I held.

This summer I babysat three little boys, ages 2, 4, and 6. The four year old and the six year old would get in fights sometimes, and would call each other names or hit/kick one another. To punish them for their actions I would put them in time out. I put the four year old in a 4 minute time out and the six year old in a 6 minute time out. I felt bad putting them in time out because they would cry and get upset with me, but it was something that I had to do.

Currently as a Vice-President for ASMSU, the Student Government at MSU, I directly oversee a staff of four,and have some power over our elected student assembly.  I use this position of power to help those that I oversee accomplish their goals,and the goals of the organization.

When I was the most knowledgeable member of my group for a computer science project, I had power over my other group members. My team members relied on me for setting meeting times, distributing the work load, and making sure everything got done. Because of my power, I felt in control and it was nice to be able to have control over others who looked up to me.

I am in a position of power when I am at my nannying job.  The kids have to listen to me and I am in charge and have control over what they do.  It makes me feel responsible and I have a feeling of maturity.

I was playing a  Video game with one of my friends, i was the leader of the team because i had better items than him. I felt really good, like i am better than him in every way, and i wanted to protect him from others.

I was asked to babysit my boyfriend's little sister for the weekend. She wanted to have people over for a bonfire and it was up to me if I was going to let her or not. I was very uncomfortable because her and I are friends, so it was expected that I would allow for her to have people over. But at the same time, she has been acting up lately and so her parents wanted me to stay at the house to make sure she did not do anything bad. Her parents said it was up to me if I wanted to let her have people over but I was nervous things would get out of control and I wouldn't be able to handle it. I ended up letting her have a few friends over and nothing bad happened but I didn't like being responsible, especially when her parents trusted me.

I played Basketball in Germany and was the best and oldest on my team (which does not mean that I am very good). But as a team captain I tried not to get to close or too far apart from other players. When there was a fight I tried to stay neutral and not take one persons place and hit on the other one, even so I sometimes had an own opinion. In general I tried not to shout at people when they did something wrong. But sometimes I could not control it.

I was in a position of power when I elected for someone I knew not to become president of an organization. Since then, I have felt extremely guilty about my decision but know that I made the right choice.

Throughout high school I was a member of the girls' varsity soccer team. As of senior year I was captain. I was in charge of choosing what lifts we do during conditioning, what our crossfit would be following practice, as well as giving extra laps to girls who felt they did not need to participate. This made me feel that I deserved respect, yet, it also made me feel that I needed to earn it. I thought I had to put myself through whatever punishment the underclassmen would have if I made the same mistake. For example, if someone did not go in for a header on the ball they had to do an extra mile and would be immediately pulled out of the game by our coach. I made sure the same rules applied to myself.

When I baby sit I am a position of power. I control when the kids get what they want. I also control the consequences that they receive for there actions. This makes me feel powerful. It also makes me feel good that I can make them feel good. It is also increase pressure on me to some level.

I was in a position of power was when I was involved in grading exams for a middle school/high school extracurricular event (Science Olympiad - Hereditary event).  I felt important and validated (I'm a genetics major) and like I was responsible for grading correctly and fairly.   The grades I gave the student teams correlated to what place they earned in that event and if they got a medal or not.  This was for the state competition, so it felt very weighty and important.  It was exciting and I enjoyed the responsibility, and I felt like I held my commitment to these students participating in the event.

Over the summer I worked in a child care center where I was mainly in charge of facilitating the events and activities in the classroom. With the help of my coworkers and building manager, I planned daily activities, took care of the children, and oversaw an entire classroom. At times it was overwhelming, depending on the amount of children and the particular personalities of the children in attendance, however most of the time I enjoyed being in charge of the classroom and interacting with the children. There were times when I wish I had more assistance and times when I wish I had less, but overall I felt comfortable in my position.

I teach swim lessons at my local YMCA and as a swim teacher I have to manipulate situations to get what I  want, a child to learn how to swim. I really enjoy being in this position because it usually has a very positive affect on the kids. Sometimes it can be frustrating have kids that won't listen or stay still, but it helps me build as a person too.

When I was at high school, I became the assistant of my history teacher. At the the beginning, I felt excited, and I tried to do well. I had to help my teacher take students' homework. Sometimes, I needed to help him to correct the homework, and I helped other students to review the course. I also had to do well for my history grades. It made me tired, but it really great. I really appreciated to my history teacher, because he gave me the opportunity to do it.

In high school I used to be one of the judges of a scientific research competition. the winners would go to another level of the competition and finally be awarded by the Emir of my country, so it was quiet an important thing for students. I was feeling responsible, and anxious because I want to be as fair as possible and forget that the contestants are actually my friends since kindergarten!

I was once the leader of a club and it felt satisfying as well as powerful. to some extent weak when events i planed hadn't turned out as successful or if an individual person hadn't followed my orders.

I was recently given the power to train new workers on the basics (opening and closing procedures, shelving, and general knowledge for the job) and if they were approved by me they were allowed to be a full time worker, but they had to meet or exceed my standards before I gave them the nod of approval

I was placed in a squad leader position in the Army reserves. I was told to manage my troops and lead PT. I was excited but nervous because the last squad leader who was a female did a great job, and i wasn't sure if i would do as well as her.

I was captain of my high school senior varsity soccer team. I had a say on who is in the roster, who gets to play and how we play. I felt confident in my ability and I felt like I had control over my teammates. I felt like I could influence their performance to another level with my talking.

I've been in power many times when babysitting. You are able to control the children's actions and discipline them when necessary. You are able to control their feelings and let them know what they are doing may not be the right thing. My main focus while babysitting was how I would keep the children safe and out of harms way. I felt powerful because I was able to make the decisions and give yes or no answers.

Babysitting you always have a position of power. When I have power I always have full responsibility for what happens. I enforce rules to make sure everything is going the way it should be but I also take into account what the others want.

When I was on leadership for a highly competitive cultural dance organization, I would often judge whether a person had the skills and talent to be a member. There were try-outs every year, and often several people were to try-out for two years before being able to join the organization. The people who were seriously interested would practice throughout the year to get the position, and it was my duty to judge their performance. I was in a position where I could cut off people who were "almost there," but who could use some more work. Usually, people saw it as an opportunity to refine their talents and try-out the next year. I felt powerful, confident, and glad that I could influence growth in their lives. It was a position that many people have abused before, but I saw it as an chance to better the other party over myself.

I was a in a position of power when I got to select who was on our football team and what positions they played. I felt bad sometimes when I had to put the less athletic players in less fun positions.

I was a middle school volleyball coach, therefore I had power over the middle school kids that I was coaching. It was a pleasant experience because the kids listened to me, whether that be because I was intimidating or just because they were good kids. I would coach volleyball again because I enjoyed the coaching position and being able to teach kids about the sport.

I was in 6th grade and I happened to know my brother secret. I used that to make he does what ever I wanted to. I felt like I was his boss that he has to always follow my orders. I thought that it was kind of fun being in a position of power.

During this position, i can basically ask people to do the things i want them to do because i am in a position of power. So for example, if i want to get something or finish something, i can text them or tell them to finish these things for me. Or buy something for me without paying. The world will be much easier for me because of the position of power.

I supervise students cooking and serving. Often, I feel unqualified to make a decision over them when it is something simple. However, I feel strict on them performing a task to my specifications when it's important or skilled. When students do a poor job, I often give them several chances before they become unteachable in my opinion and I dislike working with them due to their lack of ability in that situation. When students perform well, I like them and allow them freedoms.
I was playing volleyball in middle school and I was a captain of the team. I could tell my teammates what the plans were and tell them what the positions they should be.

a time when i personally held a lot of power was when I was watching my younger brothers while my parents were away. I didn't think too much of it, it was pretty much all the same when my parents were there as they were gone. instead I was helping my little brother vs. my mother and father. One thought that crossed my mind is that I don't want kids.

I felt like I was in a position of power when I was a T.A. for a Lyman Briggs Chemistry Lab. I was particularly in charge of making sure the students did the tasks they were presented at hand. One time, though, I caught a student cheating on a quiz. I typically feel in power, but because I was in a work setting, I was more afraid than I felt empowering. Therefore, I unfortunately turned my shoulder and talked to the other teacher of the class. It was not until the following week that we said for students to keep their eyes on their quizzes. I made it a point to stand near the person cheating and keep an eye out on him the whole quiz-taking period. I am still mad at myself for not standing up and saying something about it. Had it been any other time where I felt like I was in control but not in a work setting, I definitely would have said something, especially from experience.

I was captain of a sports team. Deciding how and when the team completed certain tasks (such as wearing a certain color uniform), was a little challenging. Not everyone always agreed, so it was up to me to make the decision and pick for the majority. It was a role a assumed, but thought nothing of it, other than to please my teammates.
Babysitting younger family members. I was wondering if they would actually listen to what I was saying or think because I am not their parents , they didn't have to listen.

Over the summer, I interned at a mortgage lending company. One of my main tasks was to create performance reports for senior leadership. As such, I was given much responsibility since I was able to report on how team members were performing. Since much of their salary is based on production bonuses, I was a key part in ensuring accurate and fair wages for the time I was there. Often, team members would email me asking how and why they were at the production level they were at, and I had to explain to them how bonuses were calculated and how I obtained the production level that I did. Sometimes, people were unsatisfied with this and felt they should have been receiving more bonus, at which time I was required to prove that the calculations were correct.

I directed a skit for my senior class and wrote the script for it. That meant that I decided the content that would be in the skit. People often came to me and gave suggestions and I decided what I would add in for them. It was nice because I was able to control most of the aspects of the skit so the final version of it was very much how I wanted to be, but it was also difficult to ensure that everyone else got what they wanted and were as involved as they would have liked. Overall it was a really nice experience.

I got a job and volunteered in an non-profit organization. Many of my friends came to talk to me when they met me in the library. They acquired the detailed about the events and how to apply them. I felt confident and honored about myself . And I need to work hard and to be a better exemplar.

This past summer I was a camp counselor for a camp whose participants were teens and young adults with special needs. As a counselor I had the opportunity to plan activities. These activities needed to be understandable and fun for every camper to participate in.

When I was president of a particular club in High School the adviser of the club asked me to evaluate each member in an attempt to see who would fit for office. It was very weird to be honest, evaluating my friends and such because I felt the need to give everyone good evaluations. Everyone wanted the good evaluations and what kind of friend would I be had I not helped a friend. In the end, I gave most of the club a good if not great evaluation except for those I felt were truly unfit.

This summer I participated in an internship and one day during the internship I led a volunteer day for the other interns and was asked to give feedback on how they participated.  We all were in a food pantry warehouse sorting food, and I was frustrated because of the interns were not helping complete the task so I had to do extra work at the end to finish what they hadn't finished.  Overall I really liked the day because I was working with the other inters instead of my coworkers.

I was the captain of the track team and whenever I wanted anybody to stretch or run certain races, they would listen to me. I felt good knowing that people would listen to me because I was high up on the team.

I was a section leader in my choir in high school. I had the ability to change their grades if they regularly didn't come to sectionals or class without an excuse. This put a lot of pressure on me because there were some cases where I knew the choir member had a very good reason for missing because I was close to them on a personal level, but I couldn't allow myself to give them special treatment over anyone else in my section. Being a quiet person, I also found it hard to control my section during rehearsals and make sure they were on task.

I was captain of my high school soccer team my senior year. I didn't necessarily feel empowered, more of a leadership responsibility. I enjoyed having this role on the team as I had more of an influence on my team and our coach.

group discussion in Spanish class. we were given a grade on our performance from the person to our right. the members of my group and i were all very understanding and did not grade harshly at all but still gave them helpful criticism.

An incident when I was in power was a couple months ago when I was babysitting. The girl that I babysit wanted a Bigby coffee and it was up to me to take her there and get her a coffee. I told her if she got her homework done and cleaned her room, we would go get a coffee. It was a somewhat easy way to get her to get her to do her chores instead of taking something away from.

When I teach Pilates I am in a positon of power. I tell the students what to do and they have to listen. I felt like it was an important responsibililty and that I have to respect their willingness to submit to my requests.

I was chosen to be on a review board that awarded a certian amount of scholarship money to high school seniors for the FFA. I felt like kids in high school shouldn't have been the ones to be awarding the money to the students; adults should have been the ones to do that. I also felt that some of the other people on the review board weren't doing it fairly and were giving more money to their friends instead of who deserved it becuase of their hard work.

it felt good to have power because it was easy to control the group and have them do what i needed them to do, but i didnt enjoy dictating them and seeing that they didnt enjoy my instructions sometimes.
Last time i was in a position of power I had something that someone else wanted and it felt good but since i am a nice guy i let them have it for nothing in return

A situation that i usually feel empowered is when someone lies to me and i confront them about it.  They know they've been caught and i have the power to ask them why and make them tell me the truth.  I dont like being lied to, i actually really hate it.  When that happens its not necessarily good feelings because im not very upfront with my feelings and such,  i think i feel disappointed and probably hurt if its someone im close to.

the last two summer i have been in oppertunitys to be in power on the roofing crew that i worked for, in witch time i was given the power of forman and head mason and i used those postions to push the guys i was working with to work harder and to also have fun while we were working. as a result we were able to get the jobs done faster cause we wernt thinging of it as work.
IM not sure of any situation I had power.
Grading someone else's presentation for a class. I felt powerful, and extremely uncomfortable. I was concerned about grading fairly rather than too harshly or leniently.

I was a baseball coach for my brother's team last summer.  I was the hitting and infield coach, and had very good results.  I felt comfortable in this position, but not overly powerful.  I really enjoy being around kids and helping them, especially in a sport I am passionate about.

I worked as a manager for a class of twenty. I was responsible for grading papers, and keeping the other students on task. I felt a bit apprehensive about the experience as I was younger than those I oversaw by several years, yet I tried to keep them on task without seeming tyranical or bossy. Apparently I was rather good at this task as I received manager of the quarter in my first quarter working there.

When I was a sophomore, I was left to coach freshmens in my belonging dance club. They are almost beginners, so I got nervous. I have to coach them for one month and make a work. At first I was anxious to teach them well, but they practiced and akked me for advice. They gragually got better. At last, we made a good work and I was so happy.

When I worked as an EMT in Missoula, I ran lead on a bad car crash where one person did not survive and the others were critically injured.  It was very stressful at the time telling others what needed to be done with my patient.  They did survive but one other patient did not.  I remember thinking that I wished I had more experience going into the scene or someone with more experience would have take lead.  It was good for my skills and being able to step up to the challenge.

In high school, I was the class president. I had the power over everyone in my sophomore class. I was able to be the voice and their opinions on things. I felt great and powerful because everyone respected me, everyone came up to me when they wanted something done or something changed. I was their representative and it felt great that people relied on me to change something for them. I enjoyed that year.

An example of a time when I was in a position of power was babysitting. The kids had to listen to me and I could tell them whether or not they could do something. Their parents trusted me and I had to be responsible. Some aspects were enjoyable and I like kids, on the other hand, being responsible for someone else's life can be straining.

I used to work at an Oregon Athletics Club (OAC) back when I lived in Oregon. I was actually the eldest among my employees and so whenever something would happen and our supervisor was not around, they would look to me for help. I usually either took control over the situation or let them handle it on their own. If I felt as though they could not handle it on their own, then I would go and do it. However, if I felt they either could do it on their own or needed to, then I would allow them to do it especially when it came to things such as cleaning up messes, fixing something broken, or helping out a customer.

In high school, I was a student athletic trainer for all of the basketball teams. If a player got hurt during the game and the head trainer told me to go out and help them, I was put into power to decide if he/she should remain in the game depending on the extent of their injuries. Also, I would tape the athletes before a game. I would tell them what tape job I should do depending on their injuries, or if they even need to be taped.

I once had a breakup from a long-term relationship and it was because I didn't like my girlfriend anymore but she still liked me, so she repeatedly told me she would whatever I want in order to get back and I asked for nothing but to leave me alone. It was the first time I had power over someone and could've taken advantage of them but didn't and I feel good about that.

This summer, my friend and I went to an Avenged Sevenfold concert. I bought a sweater from their concession stands and it was my absolute favorite. During the concert, my friend was holding my sweater and I was wearing his Oakley sunglasses. Sometime throughout the concert, he dropped my sweater and did not pick it up. We were traveling throughout the crowd during the concert and ended up in the front of the stage, so he lost it. He said he was too afraid to pick it up because he did not want to get trampled on by other people around him. Mind you, it was a $70 sweater. I ended up keeping his Oakleys as collateral until he either bought me a new sweater or gave me the money to buy a new one. It took him several months and although he was not buying me a new sweater he was still continuously bugging me for his sunglasses. I was so angry at him that I wanted to break his sunglasses and call it even. Eventually, though, I ended up giving him his sunglasses back and he did not buy me a new sweater or give me money for it.

I was student council president, and it was my responsibility to prepare for concessions for a volleyball game. I had the power to purchase the food, assign work times, and delegate duties. I felt, as I often do, when given power that I had no power at all. When I have no power, I don't have to worry about outcomes or other peoples responsibility. I simply have to do my job and enjoy doing. However for this, it was my responsibility to make sure that things worked out smoothly. This meant actively communicating and taken on the responsibilities that i delegated. There is something enjoyable about it though, because I had the freedom to make sure that things were done competantly which often at a young age you are forced to watch things get done ineffectively without any input.

Mamy times while volunteering I was in control of many over seeing tasks of others. While doing this I would feel the stress sometimes, however, knew that it was helping others to make their busy jobs easier. Such as our camp out trips having to make sure all the items were in place, and tents set up in the right way.

Over the summer I managed a custom motorcycle store, as well as planning events and PR work. I made the schedule, as well as having the power to hire and fire employees. It was kice being able to do this, as I could make decision best for the store as I deemed necessary. However, I constantly worried about whether or not I was making a good decision as well as about the feelings of the employees over which i presided.
I was captain of my dance team, I felt that I was good at helping them and teaching them.
I was a teacher's assistant for an anatomy lab. I liked teaching but it didn't make me feel powerful.

I was the captain of my basketball team in high school. This was a very fun and awesome position because my team relyed on me to lead them and help them win. I loved this experience and took it as a great honor. I was honored to have my teammates look up to me for advice and guidance and I also loved having my coach be the one who always came to me when something on the court needed done.

I wanted my older sister to clean up the kitchen so I told her to do it. I was fustrated because I told her to clean it several times that day. When she doesn't do something I want her to, I tend to give her the silent treatment.

I had the decision to fire or keep on an employee. I felt nervous about making the decision, but decided that they needed to go. I told them as straight foreward and easy as i could. I felt nervous and bad about the cituation at first, but afterwards i felt relieved that someone better vcould have the job and that things would run more smoothly.

Teaching someone the trade of painting put me in the position of being in control. I could effect their job status and pay. I like being in leadership roles generally speaking, whether it be because I like power I'm not sure. I think I do like being able to control people to some extent, or I would not like being in the position. But I like the feeling of having the answeres to problems and being the person that others come to for guidance.

All during high school and the last part of middle school I was a camp counselor at a week long 4-H summer camp.  The campers randged from the ages of 5-15.  As a counselor I was incharge of running the camp, keeping the campers entertained adn happy, and ensured their safety.  Planning for this camp took about three months because myself and the other counselors had to come up with an overall theme, shirt colors, games and many other things to keep the campers happy and so that they could get the best out of their week.  The week leading up to that week in July was always nervewracking.  The week during was stressful, and the week after I was very tired.  But for those five summers I spent as a counselor I wouldn't do anything different about it.

I was asked to be a reference on a job application for a friend of mine.  The situation was a bit difficult because I really liked my friend as a person, but I did not believe that he would do very well in the position that he was applying for.  However, I did not explicitly say that I didn't think he would do well.  Instead, I merely outlined the positive characteristics that I saw in him and decided to let the employer figure out if he would be a good fit for the position.  In that case, I didn't enjoy being a reference because I didn't feel confident in my ability to highly recommend him for the job.
I coached a local soccer team. I like helping the kids. Soccer is my favorite sport. Sometimes we as coaches abused our power a little bit for fun but never in a serious manner.
A time when I was in power was when I coached a 6th grade basketball team. I was the head coach so therfore I was in charge of everything regarding the team.

Lying to my father to recieve a $4,000 loan with which to pay back revoked finacial aid from failing a year of college. None of the real information was discussed and I simply made it out as though my current finacial aid wasn't able to cover everything. I feel some, though little, guilt over this, especially since I used his desire to have a relationship with me to accomplish this.

I was a soccer captain and I was in control of everything that happened on the feild and makin sure that the whole team got along and respected each other. I don't mind being in control but I also do not like to dissapoint people either so it was hard to have to stand up to certian people. It was important to remember however that I could not please everyone all the time.

A situation where I was in power over someone would be when I decided to break up with my boyfriend of the time because he has cheated on me. It took me a couple days after finding out to decided if I was going to break up with him or give him a second chance. I didn't enjoy the situation very much although it was very tempting to drag it out and make him have to suffer through waiting. However, I refrained from doing that because I figured that would make me as bad as him.

I was in a position of power when I volunteered for a first grade elementary school class. The children were supposed to obey me and I sometimes evaluated their Spanish reading skills. I didn't really think about the fact that I was in a power position at the time, though, I just did my best to help the teacher and students and had fun with it.

I was a co captian in my high schools drumline. We played at football and basketball games, the pep ralles, music concerts and the spring dance concert. I really liked being apart of that club and it was a fun senior year helping out everything together.

I was the captain of my Mock Trial team in High School. I told the team where to go and what to do when our coach was not around. It felt really nice to have a group of people listen to me and look to me for advice.

I worked at a summer camp and was in charge of 10 elementary- aged kids. I had to make sure they didn't hurt themselves, and I was pretty much in control of all of their activities throughout the day. If anything, it made me stressed out, and I felt a lot of pressure because thier experience was based on what I did or did not let them do. I don't like being in charge of other peoplel, even if they are just kids.
When I worked as a hostess I was in charge of training the other hostess and giving her tasks. That was the most power I've ever had.

In a Deca project, I took over for some portions of the project while my friends took over other parts. I had to make a few phone calls and meet with managers of stores in order to finish the the project. Making the phone calls and meeting up with the managers made me feel a little nervous and scared. What if i said something completely wrong or something that didnt make sense? So I was pretty nervous throughout the whole thing..

Having power makes you feel superior. At my current job, I was assigned to be the senior front desk. Therefore, I have the power to give instruction and command others on what I want them to do. It feels really nice to be able to do it.

I have a little sister and often times would babysit her.  This would continue and I would be able to let her eat a sugary snack or play a certain game or go outside.  My sister and I are very different people, so often times this resulted in conflict because she held different desires than I did.  My feelings on it were that she should've listened to me, but she never really did which I now realize is because of her stage in development.  It makes me now realize that my frustration with her then just showed that she was in the right developmental phase and I should have given her more slack.

I was in the power of telling my niece if she could have all of the clothes she picked out at the store or not because it was my money and I had control of the money so I could say no to the things I didnt want her to have.
When I worked in the child center at a gym, I was in charge of this kids and what they did. It made me want to be nice and understanding to the kids.

I was at a party recently when I learned how easy is really is to manipulate drunk people. There were about 8 people crammed into two smallish rooms, 6 guys and 2 girls. The guys were all vying for the attention of one of the girls(myself excluded). I don't exactly remember how, but I suddenly came to the realization that you can get a drunk man to do anything you wanted by phrasing your desire as a challenge to them. It seemed to have something to do with appearing macho in front of the ladies. I only tested it once but it worked to great success when I challenged my already drunk friend to chug the beer he just opened. It took a little chiding but he eventually caved and did it. I then resolved to not do that again because I feel that this information can be easily abused and I don't want to hurt any of my friends in the process.

I lead and teach many school and other volunteer groups. Since I am the leader I do feel that when I give orders and make executive decisions people often disagree or could feel disinclined to do what I asked. It often feels overly bossy and controlling which makes the originally pride of being a leader diminish.
a camp counselor. Campers were suposed to follow the counselors directions. Sometimes as a counselor it was necessary to say no when somebody asked to do something. It was hard work being a counselor

I felt that I was in a position of power this morning in a class, talking with group members. I just felt like the group leader and like I had the ultimate control over what we chose to do. I think it felt rather natural to me, becuase I am a natural leader and this is something that occurs often for me. It can feel a little overwheling or like there is a lot of pressure on me, but I would rather have that pressure on me than on someone else who is less capable of handling the job of being a leader.

I recall a time during high school when everyone in my government class was to present a bill. Afterwards, we would all vote either yes to have it pass, or no to have it fail. If majority was in favor, the student would 'win' and get five points of extra credit. This made me feel in control.

The most recent one memory I can think of I was simply training a new empolyee at the restaurant I work at, and frankly there really isnt a huge difference from a position of power to a generic position of having those above me. I knew that that person depended on me to know what I was doing and not decieve them, and to be straight forward, but I didnt feel like anything else was really different.

Working as a hostess/waitress at a restaurant i was entirely in control of the pace of the restaurant, the satisfaction and serving times of the guests and the quality of the visit. It was stressful having so many jobs and different people to please at the same time yet comforting to know i ultimately set the pace

I was the sole captain of my high school's show choir last year.  I had been a member since my freshman year and was the only member who had been in the show choir all four years of high school.  As captain, it was my job to get the other members' input on dance moves and song selection and convey them to the choir director along with my own opinions which were seen as more valuable because I had the most experience.  Therefore, I often was able to sway Mrs. VanSlyke into choosing what I believed was best over the others because she often agreed with me and I knew what her preferences were.  I always took an anonymous vote where people could vote on my recommendations of write in their own selections that I would take to Mrs. VanSlyke so everyone would feel like their voices were hear.  I never took advantage of my position here where I could have easily changed voting results or not have had a full class vote at all because I hoped that when the underclassmen who would hold the position later would see that I was fair and would choose to be fair as well.  Also, with this system allowed for me to not be the target of others' ill feelings about song selections because everyone had a say.

I was an officer of my high school Interact Club, as officers we had to interview the applicants who are applying to be officers. I remember reading all their applications and being very excited in the beginning to to being bored at the end. The interview was definitely the more important part of getting the position, i remember looking at the applicants and the way they present themselves effected largely on their scores from me.
We were hiking in a group of 6, i was the leader. I felt very in control, and also apart from everyone else. Still, I liked how competent I felt.

As the eldest in my family, I have been in situations where I had power over my siblings and could dictate if they get rewarded or punished for certain actions or behaviors. Sometimes I think it's a trade-off since I have the responsibility to show the right example. It doesn't always feel good and it doesn't always feel bad.

i was in charge of putting together the entire freshmen retreat at my highschool. it was overwhelming because i had to create the groups, and assign leaders to each groups and pick the rooms they would stay in and i had to make the schedules. the most stressful part was the fact that i had to find 30 families that would host dinner for one night and i had to find transportation for 110 kids and we only had 2 small buses. In the end it felt good when it all came together but the process of putting it together was stressful and overwhelming.

I was conducting a campus event (like an information session). I was the leader (president) and had to lead other officers (vice-president, etc). I felt accomplished, smart, confident, well-spoken, proud, grand. It was a positive experience for me, and I felt like I was a natural-born leader.

In high school, I was the head squad leader of the marching band. This meant that I was the leader that made sure all of the other leaders and marchers were on the task at hand. This position allowed me to both discipline and reward marchers for their work. I enjoyed being in this leadership position because it made me feel like an integral piece of the band; however, it was difficult maintain a neutral stance in my deliberations or decisions. Often times, I found myself on the side of the students whenever there was a problem between the students and the band directors. Although I was partial to the student's opinions, I pride myself in being able to balance both the student's needs and the band director's needs.

I was section leader of the trumpet section in high school.  The director came to me at the end of the year to ask my opinion on who i thought was most qualifies to fill the position the following year.  Of the three potential leaders, one was far too authoritative and failed to command the respect of other trumpet players, one was very eccentric and unable to connect to many of the students that found him weird, and the final was very soft spoken and too nice to make people work when they didn't want to.  It was a difficult decision given the tradeoffs of each, but I finally recommended the third person for the job because they were the most liked and most capable of adapting to the requirements of the position.

I held power when my boss left me in charge of the roofing crew while he was on vacation. I had to exercise my power over the crew by deciding when they could and could not take breaks, go to lunch, call it a day, and decide what job site to work on. My boss also left me orders to decide which workers I needed for each job site. I had to split the ones apart who did not work well together and choose who would do the best job at each job site. I felt very strong and prideful that I was able to instruct people that were much older than me. I was also honored that my boss trusted me so much.

The most recent incident I recall was when I had to choose one of my suite mates to come along with my roommate and I to a nice dinner that my Dad invited me, and two other friends, to. Since I've only really known my suite mates for about 2 weeks, I had to make somewhat of an accelerated value opinion about who I already liked most after a relatively short period of time. I also weighed who might want to come with us, as opposed to who would want to do other things. In the end I chose someone who I had been interacting with more personally and one-on-one than the others.

This summer I was on the Summer Staff for my church's youth group and I was in charge of large groups of middle schoolers for various camp excursions and a missions trip. It was stressful at times but I also really enjoyed it because I got to know a lot of them which seemed to increase their respect for me as a leader.

Last time I had power was when doing peer evaluations for Chem Lab. I was in a position to evaluate them and either harm or help their grade. I felt very indifferent. No positive or negative feelings.

I was a leader of my classroom when I was in an elementary school. I can give a caution to my classmate when they make noise during the class, and had a authority to tell who was being bad at class to the teacher. I handed out some materials teacher gave to me before the class, and I gathered students' homework and gave those to teacher. I felt kind of superior feeling that I am on the top of my classmates. Because of this feeling, some students might wanted to be a leader of the classroom.

Last year I was one of the captains of my High School football team and we had a player on the team that was constantly getting in trouble with teachers in school. Our head coach scheduled a meeting with the captains and he told us that we were the one that would have to decide the punishment for the player that was getting in trouble. I felt bad for the younger player because he was one of our starters, and he might not have know that what he was doing in class was very distracting. However, I didn't feel like a football game was more important than him learning a lesson so we suspended him for two games. he was not very happy, but during and after his suspension from the games we all believed that he had learn his lesson because he no longer got in trouble with his teachers.

My younger sister really wanted to go out with her friends on a Friday evening but my parents were out of town. So she called them and asked for their permission but they did not accept that. She came to me crying and asking for my help. I called my parents and explained that I can drive her to and from the place and stay around the area to make sure everything is okay. My parents did accept my offer and told me I am in charge. At that moment, I felt like I had power! I made my sister happy and made my parents proud of me for taking care of my younger sister and her friends.

I am currently teaching a class at the University of Virginia and also was a TA in a biology course. Overall, I find the idea of teaching others to be fulfilling, and overall enjoy the experience. It can be frustrating at times when the students are not picking up concepts as quickly as you would like, but I feel that this is where the challenge of being a good teacher comes in.

My friends wanted to go to a certain type of store to buy something but they didn't really know anything about that type of store, but I knew so I was in control on what store they should go based on my recommendations.

I was a coach on a little girls' volleyball team. One of my best friend's little sisters was on the team I coached and I wanted to start her and let her play a lot because I liked her, but she wasn't very good. I felt bad for not playing her most of the game but I also wanted the team to do well. I made the right choice. At least, I think I did.

Several months ago, I was given the responsibility of prepping four young girls for a school recital. I had to decide whether they were ready or not and had to make sure that they knew their parts and what they had to do. I felt like the outcome of everything was on my shoulders and whether the girls did well or not reflected my ability to lead them. It was also my responsibility to get these girls to and from the school in a timely manner. Although there was some pressure because I was responsible for more than one person, I am glad I was given the task because I learned a lot about myself my reliability, and my leadership skills.

I was a supervisor of a work center when I was in the Navy. I had to delegate duties to my subordinates, some will diligently follow my orders while others were hesitant sometimes. I remember feeling glad and happy about this opportunity and responsibilities that go along with it. I wanted to make the work center a better place, from the production side and from the emotional side, meaning I wanted everyone to be happy they work there. At times, higher ups with come down on me and I would get annoyed because of the futile reason they needed to talk to me to get stuff done, everything was going to get done if they told me or not. It just seemed pointless and a waste of time to be causing unnecessary stress to me and my work center. There was times when there were minor altercations but everything would simmer down quickly and wouldn't escalate to a worse situation. Maybe I should've been harder on myself and my subordinates.

I was a county captain for my golf team, which meant that I arranged meetings to hear peoples' voices and I was able to change things if there were any problems causing upset within my team and the county. I was happy that I had been chosen to be captain as it was a big role and quite difficult to make everyone happy. I probably wouldn't like to do it again as I am not the most confident person and I do not like to be put in to bad situations that are stressful. I did enjoy the time of being in power although sometimes I wasn't very good at it.

As a lifeguard, I was able to direct people in their actions and behaviors to maintain safety for all those in the waterpark at the time. At the time I was at a position in the kid play area called "ship" where I was to look after a rather large ship with slides and tunnels. I would normally get rather annoyed with the kids that chose not to listen to warnings or commands about their actions and blatant disrespect especially towards someone in a position of authority at the time.
I have never really been in a situation where I have had that type of power.

One of the last times that I was in a situation of power was right before I came down to Nova Southeastern University. I was working at Foodworks Restaurant, and because I have worked there for three years I had seniority over many of the younger kids. While I trained them on the responsibilities of being a dishwasher I remembered what it was like when I was being trained, only now I was in charge. If I did not want to do something I could have just told Evan or Dylan to do something and they would've done it with no questions asked. It felt good to be in control, but I did not abuse my power. I still did all of my responsibilities and didn't throw the burden onto my subordinates

At the beginning of my senior year in high school, I was asked by my dance teacher to help judge the annual auditions for the team. I was on the panel with 2 other former students and 1 current student, not including the teacher. About 50 students auditioned for the roughly 20 spots available. I gave my opinion as to who should move on each round. I assessed each individual by their level of energy, their strength in technique, and their improvement overall. Some degree of favoritism was evident for certain dancers for their immense talent shown throughout the year. For others, I had to think long and hard to determine whether they could keep up with the demands of the class. Some individuals did not have strong technique, but showed massive improvement and were well on their way to mastering technique if given the chance. I knew that for some of the individuals, it was really important to make this team. Cuts needed to be made as hard as it is seeing their disappointed faces. I was once in that spot where making the team was very important to me. For those who were in the middle, I had to envision them on the team and determine whether they could keep up or bring the team down.

On the basketball court, the point guard is 99% of the time in power. They call out the plays and tells everyone where to go because they have a full view of the court and can tell what the defense is giving. When I play this position, I feel as if I run the court. It is always a good feeling because you know what play will work best for what the defense is giving. If that play does not work, we simply try another play until we make a shot. But it usually works on the first try and because of that, I feel happy because my team scored.

A few years ago, I babysat two little boys regularly, and they had to listen to what I had to say or had to ask permission before they did something. It was interesting because of the level of responsibility for other people, and the trust that the parents had in me. I had to be authoritative so that the kids would listen to me, but nice enough to where they enjoyed the experience and wanted me back. It didn't always go smoothly because they were both pretty stubborn, but in the end they usually ended up giving in and listening to me.
I feel as though I am in a position of power when I babysit children because I am the primary care taker of the child(ren), therefore if they want something I would have to comply first.

I was vice president of a Med club in my high school. So I had somewhat of power of people in the club. The fact that I knew I could take away some people's positions if they weren't doing the job done made me be more responsible in my own position. Having that much power over a large group of people makes you be  more concise with the things you have to do. And it makes you work harder.
When I tutored a group of people on a certain subject I was in that position of power.

I served as the president of Business Professionals of America, an organization that revolves around promoting business strategies and an amalgamation of other areas such as mathematics, science, and technology, during senior year of high school. I had to work with several individuals on a weekly basis to raise funds for the group, promote ideas as to how to better the work that they have to submit for their specific events, and follow through with volunteering projects. Sometimes, the rest of the board members did not cooperate well; therefore, some tasks burdened upon me. Nonetheless, I had to balance the work by carrying out tasks independently and utilizing teamwork characteristics. Mostly, I was content, but sometimes I would have to store the infuriation inside- venting would not have been the best choice when I have much else going on already not related to the club.

Leading a team for a game in airsoft. I felt important, responsible, and looked up to. I had to create plans and lead everyone. I felt as though if something went wrong it was automatically my fault. I was looked up to, and expected to win.

A particular incident in which I was in a position of power was when I taught a dance class. I was the teacher for the class and was in charge and stretching them and teaching them a dance I made up. I always dread thinking about teaching classes because since I'm pretty close to age with most of the kids, I feel that they will end up not listening to me. As I teach the class and give instruction on what to do, I find myself actually having fun. By the end of the class, I am relieved that I was able to stay in control and keep everyone under my rule.

A past experience where I was in a position of power was when I was working at my summer job as a lifeguard. As a lifeguard it was my responsibility to ensure the safety of the patrons. If a patron was not following the rules it was my job to correct them. I had the power and authority to address the patrons and what they were doing wrong, as well as take further actions if need be. It was a good feeling to be in a position of power, even if very little.

My brother wanted to eat my sandwich I left in the fridge, but I told him if he did I would tell my mom and dad about his bad grades and all the bad things he did. I was happy I got the sandwich and my brother gave up fighting with me.

I was in an event like this when I was grading tests for a teacher as a teacher's aide. I liked being able to correct grammar, spelling, math, etc. and being able to let that student know it was wrong so they could correct the issue. I liked this because it helped out the student in the long run perform better on their next test.

One time in which I was in a position of power, I was leading my group in a Latin video project. I was given responsibility to direct, shoot, and edit the movie. I think that I was trusted to be able to handle these responsibilities because I had the most experience with movie equipment amongst the rest of my team. It felt especially good that I helped get my team an "A".

I was in charge of a fundraiser in which I was working with high school students. There were about 40 of them I was in charge of and they were split into different groups to do different jobs. For example: serving, ticket taking, kitchen help, etc. Since it was an important event for the high school students I had to really explain things clearly, and monitor them closely. It was also a bit stressful since I was the one in charge of each group to try, and make sure everything was going to plan before, during, and after the event. At the end, I asked for feedback on my performance as well as theirs in order to see what they thought I could have done better or they themselves could have done better. Most seemed to think I had handled the position very well, and because I was comfortable with my job they also felt comfortable in theirs.

The last time I was in a position of power was when I was helping my mom backstage for her dance recital. I was the manager and I had to make sure everyone was doing their job. I had to perform as well as take care of the girls and be sure that the helpers were doing their job. I also had to make sure the girls were in their places and being respectful of the other performers. It was very overwhelming, because I felt that I was doing a billion things at one time. I had to change various times and then take care of the younger girls as well as the helpers, because most of the time they weren't doing their job and letting the girls round around from place to place. So in that instance, I had to take over their job and tell the girls to go to their spots and be respectful. To not be so noisy back stage. It didn't feel like a recital, it felt more like a marathon with all the changes of costume I had plus taking care of everyone in those 2 hours.

When I was in the Marine Corps I was in charge of 6 Marines. I had to ensure that they performed all of their duties as Marines or I would restrict them from going home until the task were finished. when I was asked to help a swimteam hire a newcoach me and others decided on the canidates and evaluated experience knowledge and communication skills and presented the top canidates to a board to select final coach

A time in which I were in a position of power was when I worked in the dental office, I had controlled how much individuals had to pay for their visit. I felt like I had power, like I had experience and like people looked up to me.
I held a clothing drive for poor immigrant children before Christmas. We collected nearly $2000 in clothing.

I had a firm desire to share and impart any of my life experiences and knowledge to the person over whom I had power.  In no way did I, and nor did I feel that I had to, try to abuse and amplify my authority over that person - I was strictly there for helping that person.  I find this methodology to be the most productive, as opposed to using power or authority as a way of committing harm toward someone in some way.

I was volunteering by working as a junior camp counselor. Specifically, I worked with the 3-4 year olds. When it was time for their snack, the children would receive a juice with two cookies (unless they brought their own snacks). Certain children would want more than two cookies, however, I made sure that they only had two cookies. My thoughts were that the children who wanted extra cookies should not have extra cookies, because #1, that was the rule, and #2, the children should not be ingesting so much sugar in such a short time (this would cause them to become extra hyper). Although I did not like to see them momentarily unhappy, I knew that is was better for their health if they did not have any extra cookies.

I was the director, musical director and the designer for the musical at Palm Beach State College called 25th Annual Putnam County Spelling Bee. It was the first musical the school had done in almost 20 years and the first student run musical ever so the pressure was on. I had a lot of hurdles to jump when it came to cast and budget things but overall it was a very rewarding experience. I was able to express my creativity on many different levels and the show was a success. It has since opened up many opportunities for my future.

A week before my 17TH birthday, my then boyfriend of three years and I got into a huge argument. I found out that he was cheating on me for a period of 10-11 months with a young lady that I did not like at all, and he knew that. I was so hurt that I deleted his number, all of our pictures, and told him that I didn't want to see him or hear from him again. He knew how hurt I was and he tried his best to make things right. On the day of my birthday, he popped up at my house after class with 5 dozen roses, 3 perfume sets, and the keys to a 2013 Porsche Cayenne that he rented for me. I refused to accept either gift. He got on his knees, begged for my forgiveness and told me that he would do anything I wanted if I accept his apology. It was at that moment, I knew that I had power over him. I told him to take me AND my immediate family members to dinner that night and he paid almost $400 at The Cheesecake Factory for almost 30 people.

I worked for a hotel and I was in charge of supervising 3 bellmen.  Some where young and some had attitudes.  I found it sometimes draining having to tell or ask them to do things.  It was the worst part of my job, at that time.

Working at my parents medical office, I was in charge of making sure that everyone was taken care of and I had to make sure that the patients left the office satisfied. A position of power I was in was back in high school as part of the student government. An incident in which I was in a position of power would be when I was in charge of a committee at my school's blood drive. At first I was very worried and stressed out because there have been numerous incidents where the food committee fails to have enough food to supply over 300 people, and this task is  particularly hard because all the food has to be donated; we don't have a budget for food. At first I was so stressed out I went to as many food places as possible to get as much food as I could, and in addition to the food the Blood Drive Staff buy for the donors as well, it was enough to last for about 2 weeks after the blood drive! I felt accomplished!

As vice president of student council I controlled the ability of my student council body to get the theme we wanted to have for our prom. positions of power I have been in is when I babysit children and evaluate or control their behavior and punish or reward accordingly. I enjoy babysitting for the taking care of them part not the controlling part though.
I once manipulated my friend to go to the Cheesecake Factory with me.

So everyone has to meet somewhere so we can all enjoy ourselves and I can still be in class without falling asleep.

It felt good to be in a position that was better than the rest of the class. There was a group of students that did not take me seriously and decided to continue not doing their work and chatting. As a dance constructor, I have the power to critique the girls I was teaching. Although I had authority, my power only applied to situations revolving dance. Being a karate teacher give me power over the children in the class to.teaching them the concepts of the art of karate.

There was a time at work when I was able to have the final say if a certain person was promoted or not. I took the situation very seriously and made sure that I didn't undercut the person and their abilities, but I also made sure I didn't over estimate their skill either.

It felt very invigorating, yet stressful. On one hand, I got to make decisions and control situations. On the other hand, whether the situation went well or not all depended on the decisions I made and my attention to the people involved.

I'd feel bad if I did something that upset them in any way. Other than that I dont really like being in a position of power. I would feel too pressured as well as the need to please everyone and I know that is just not always possible.

I had information that another person did not. I was in a position to deliver certain pieces of information that would influence their decision. I ended up giving skewed information that would cause them to act in a way that I deemed the most beneficial.
mentoring a new employee in the work place, felt bad for telling them what to do but it makes them and i a better worker

i was a zone captain for lifeguarding at zoombezi bay and i had to be very work oriented and determine who was doing the best job for the company and it was sometimes very stressful

Whenever I'm driving with friends,  I feel as if I am in control because I am the driver. this mostly happens when we want to listen to music. The driver is always in control of music. However, I never had any feelings about this.

Everyday at work I am in a position of power, I work at Roosters so I control how people's food is prepared and given to them.
