when I was put in charge of a class it made me feel like my word was law and i was really happy and felt very strong and that people were respecting me.

my younger sister was 10 and i was watching her, i would pretty much make her do what i wanted

At my job we were being audited and I was working with people that did not fully understand what they were being graded on so to pass the audit I had to follow them and try explaining different things the auditor would be looking for in their work performance. a position where i was in a position of power was in a soccer game. this made me have power because i was basically a captain so people would listen to me and listen to where i wanted them to go and tell them what to do. i felt like i had a responsibility to run the team and that the team was counting on me to get the game done so that we could win. i felt very important during that moment.

I was in cheerleading and was in charge of teaching cheers, dances and emotions. I felt like someone the younger cheerleaders could look up to or go to for help. I felt like I was a good leader and it made me happy when they would come for help or I was able to fix the things they were doing wrong.

i do not like to be in power. in my job they asked me to take over until the boss came back. i hated it. i was scared to tell people what to do. i felt bossy and i did not like it.

I babysit my nieces from time to time and more times than not, i am the authority figure. After every season of Field Hockey at my high school, we were to evaluate our coach on ethics, skill, and management. I was the only one in a group project who had time they were willing to put in to the project. I was very annoyed and I remember thinking that I was the only one who could be counted on to get the work done

When I worked at a mental facility I had a daily responsibility for other peoples well being and helped with decision making (such as him many cigarettes or money would be given to the individual daily). I was the president of my high school choir. Towards the end of the year, I was made responsible for teaching the music for the entire Spring concert. When I'm with my younger sister, when she wants something, I have the power to decide whether or not she will get it. When I was babysitting, the child wanted to eat a lot of candy.  The parents told me to limit the amount of candy consumed by the child, so I told her no. All through high school, I was the band president. That position was worth a lot more than it sounds like. In my band, people had to play well in order for me to even listen to anything they had to say, no excuses. There were multiple occasions where the trumpet section would have to play their parts repeatedly until I was satisfied. I didn't think I was in much power then. I was doing what I would want any good band president to do, have a good band with great players. I did push them, and at times they were very irritated with what I was trying to accomplish, but it did well for them in the end. I felt as if I was doing what was right for a band president to do.

I am an assistant coach for a swim team back in my home town.  This gives me power because I am in a position to evaluate every individual on the team.  I get to tell them how to make their stroke more efficient and how to make their stroke faster.  This puts me into power because I have more experience and knowledge about the sport than they do, which in turn will help them in the future.

This summer I coached a volleyball camp at Pacific Lutheran University (PLU) for girls aging from twelve to eighteen. PLU's head coach, Kevin Aoki, was ultimately responsible for the success of the camp; however, his assistant coaches were also very important. On the first day, we were asked to evaluate the participants at the camp based on skill. Once all of the participants were evaluated, each coach was given a team of girls that had a similar set of skills. On the second day, us coaches were asked to demonstrate volleyball drills, so that the campers could see how they were supposed to be ran. Then on the final day, our camp consisted of a series of scrimmages against other teams. I personally found it extremely hard to judge the girls on the first day, especially the youngest girls. I knew a few of the girls were trying their absolute, but just weren't talented enough to stay with their friends; therefore, they had to get moved to a different team. Although, overall I really enjoyed the coaching and experience, and being able to see the girls develop their skills throughout the camp.

As a senior in high school I was the captain of my soccer team.  I remember one time someone on the team was having trouble getting along with the others girls and the coach. She came and asked me for advise. I never realized how being a captain makes others look up to you.  It made me feel good and like I was doing my job and had helped someone else.  It felt good knowing that someone looked up to me.

My sister really wanted this makeup set for her birthday, and I had the power and ability to buy it for her. I felt like I had to get it for her since that was the only thing she wanted for her birthday that year. I got it for her.

Over the summer I led a small group of seventh grade girls at a church camp. We went to a camp ground and got to participate in different activities of the three days. I lead small group discussions and really tired to understand what was going on in their lives. Although the camp was exhausting and asking deep questions about their personal lives sometimes put me out of my comfort zone I really love leading the group.

In this incident the other person was always willing to listen to what I had to saw and often followed the things I would do or want without question. Being in power always feels good. For awhile I thought I would be a great CEO because I thought I was making the best decisions for both me and the other person. I thought very highly of myself and was insulted when others thought tried to prove me wrong.

One time when I was babysitting my niece and nephew they were being very destructive and loud. One of them was crying and the other was running around like a chicken with his head cut off. I told them that if they were to be good, meaning that they would calm down and sit quietly and be respectful, they would earn a prize such as candy, or extra tv time. They really wanted to have candy so I could tell that they were going to try their hardest to listen to me. I told them that if they were to be bad even once more, that they would not get either prize and would be sent to bed. You could tell that they were determined to be good, despite the prior events. In the end, they chose to settle down and be nice to one another. They earned their reward and were extremely happy.

At work, I can decide when I am ready to give out samples to customers. I felt in control of my boundaries when I am in this position. I was in a position of power when my boyfriend owed me money.  I kept reminding him of it when he was spending money other ways or complaining about paying for dinner. I felt that I was in power when I was the captain of my high school cheer squad. I was a leader of the team and also had the power to control the team and judge individuals based on their ability. I was in charge of calling what we did at games, and organizing team meetings/bonding activities. I felt that this position was fun but stressful. Being one person, having to organize 20 others becomes a challenge. This taught me different forms of leadership because yelling at the girls doesn't make any progress for the team. I had to learn that being a positive influence was the strongest form of leadership.

One particular event that comes to mind is the time when I was in charge of setting up a project for my group (my group being three nine year olds). Since I was their leader, I had the power to tell them what tasks to perform to get the project completed. Honestly, I felt pretty good, there were some moments of irritation when things weren't done correctly but otherwise it felt good to know that things were getting done. I guess I'm the kind of person that likes to know exactly what happens and how the project is progressing. So me being in charge allowed me to have that knowledge first hand. Also, when the project was completed and they presented it to the rest of the class, I felt relieved that everything had gone smoothly and that it was completed. I was proud of them and happy with the work that they did.
I work as camp counselor, so I have authority over kids. If they want to do something unsafe, I can tell them not to do that dangerous thing, and they have to listen or there will be consequences.

I held an officer position in the Key Club of my high school during my senior year. I was in charge of notifying the club of future volunteer opportunities and events (e.g. charities, food drives, etc.), making sure members were responsible and turned in their volunteer logs on time, and warned them that their membership could be put on probation if they continued to sign up for volunteer events and not show up when the day comes. Though I was an officer, I never felt like I was "in power"; I just found myself as someone who was being a bit extra helpful for my fellow club members to maintain their activeness in our community as well as the club. It was a very enjoyable experience.

As a youth group assistant at my old church I was in a position of power. I was able to determine the schedule of events during an outing. I had power over music choices and game choices. I generally felt that I was prepared but open to opinion from what the kids really wanted. I didn't like to tell kids to stop doing something wrong. I wanted to be the cool guy that let people get away with things that were probably against the rules. I didn't dwell on the fact that I had power.

When I was younger, I had a candy bar that I didn't want, that both my brothers wanted. Eventually I threw it between the two of them and made them fight for it. When I was in a position of power was when I had to look after and take care of my little sister and three cousins while the rest of my family was at a casino for a birthday party. I think babysitting young children puts you in a position of power during the time you watch them. I know I've had to tell kids to behave and stop arguing, and to threaten to take away whatever it is they're fighting over or something they'd like to play with. I don't like yelling or having to take things away from kids but when they don't get along or aren't following set directions that I've been given and they won't listen to me, it's occasionally necessary. For the most part I try to lead activities we can all do for fun or let them do their own thing instead of trying to impose certain activities on them. I like being able to watch the children without having to control what they're doing. I don't want TOO much power over them or to be really depended on.

I was the president for a club at my school , called Student 2 Student. We helped welcome military children and valued their transition into our school. I had to run meetings and direct the activities that we would do. At first, I was nervous to be the "leader" that everyone looked at, especially having to run a meeting for the first time. But after a while, that feeling of responsibility became comfortable and accepting. In addition, I realized that the work I was doing for this club was important and caused change within my school. So after a while, I felt empowered to always wake up and be the position as president, because I found meaning behind my work.

One time I was in a situation of power was when I was the patrol leader for my girl scout troop. To be honest I don't remember much about the tasks that were involved in being a patrol leader, instead I just remember that I wanted the role and was extremely happy to get chosen for it. When I was in a position of power was when I was a captain for a soccer team two years in a row, captain for a fast pitch team, and captain for a basketball team. When I babysit my little brother. I do not particularly enjoy being in the position of power in most cases but I enjoyed it in this situation.

I was class president for my graduating class in high school and it was stressful at times because I felt like sometimes I was the bad guy and could not please everyone. Teachers would also look at me for my responsibility.

The only situation I could think of was when I had to evaluate a group of students abilities in a science class I was mentoring for.  There were individual freshman students who I had to evaluate to see if they needed to start seeing tutors or staying after class to receive extra help.  Although most of the students did need the extra help I felt guilty for recommending they stay for the extra tutoring, and I did not feel very good about labeling them in that way. It is hard to label someone as "needs more assistance", because when they find out they realize that you, as the recommender, think they aren't meeting standards.

A few years ago, I was teacher in a religious ed. class for preschool and kindergarten. It was a good experience, even though it was sometimes stressful. Sometimes, the students would want something I couldn't justify giving them (extra snacks, four drink breaks in a lesson, to play a game when we had to sit down for a story). Occasionally, I wondered if I was making the right decisions.
today, i taught class. It was fun and I was thinking that I was looking forward to how the semester would go

I was in control of my brother the other day and I felt confident because I am used to watching him, however, he was sick and when my brother gets sick he tends to throw up, and he has a bad gag reflex, so my feelings, emotions, and thoughts were on edge and a little worrisome. But, the weekend turned out to be fine and he stopped throwing up eventually. He was weak and sick, but still my happy little guy.

The first thing that comes to mind is team sports. Throughout high school, I was of the team captain for two of the sports I had played. The role of team captain requires a bit of power. Team captains are what keeps the team into the game and also keeps the team's drive for victory alive. I was the catcher for the high school softball team. Anyone familiar with softball or baseball knows that when it comes to where the ball is supposed to go; the catcher is the one to make the decision. Along with the power that is giving to these leadership roles comes some disagreements. Although there is no 'I' in team, sometimes players believer there is. This is where the role of team captain comes to play. So, in some ways team captains act as the mediator.

While working a night event at work I was left in charge by my supervisor to oversee the event and carry out my tasks. The event ran smoothly and everyone carried out their responsibilities and had a good time. Afterwards, I felt good about the success and hoped I would get another opportunity. My boss was pleased wit how the event went and thanked me for doing it. All and all, it was good experience I think many teens miss out on.

I am in this position pretty often.  I was recently promoted to the hardest position at my job during the holiday season.  Because I was promoted to such an important position, I have to constantly be in power over them as well as constantly evaluate those individuals.  Being new to the job, my boss hired seasonal employee's, but now I am in a position where I need to constantly evaluate them in order to determine whether they stay post-holiday season, or if they are let go.  For one of my employees, I feel terrible because she says she is homeless, but she does not perform as well as she should if she wants to keep the job.  Therefore, I feel bad giving her a negative evaluation and letting her go after Christmas, but she shows negative behaviors by calling out often (usually on weekends,) using foul language, and being inappropriate in the work setting.

Teaching other students how to work with final cut pro x. In high school I taught younger students how to work a camera and how to edit footage. It does not bother me to have power or I feel as if I am to bossy. I enjoy being the leader in a team and I feel as if I have great leadership skills.

The last time I was in charge and had power was not too long ago.  I was a camp counselor for children.  I had to watch their every move and was responsible for them.  I loved my job because I love kids, but when they misbehaved I didn't like to punish them because I felt bad; although I know its what I had to do.  Overall, it was a great experience and I would definitely do it again.
When someone needed to borrow from me while we were shopping.  I was in power because if I were to not lend that person money then she would not have been able to purchase what she needed.

a time that I was in a pisiotno of power was when I had to fix a problem with the pipes in my basement and everyone was relying on my. I felt really good because people knew that I was the one from the job and that I could fix it.

As a junior camp counselor a couple of summers ago, I was in charge of a group of 8 year old girls. I feel that having an eminence amount of power is dangerous because of the huge amount of responsibility for others. I feel that self-control is not always a factor when one has a lot of power because we has humans forget that, just because we can do something doesn't always mean that we should.  I knew that i had to make the right decisions for the safety of the campers but I will say that having a little bit of power is always somewhat thrilling.

In my job I am continually in the position of power due to my manager title. One instance was when deciding if an employee should receive a promotion, that situation was tough because it was dependent on my input.

An incident that I felt I was a position in power is when I did my summer job at my school and the children were being very loud and disrupted I told them if they do not stop talking then the instructor cannot do the next activity with them.  The children eventually stopped talking and when this happened I felt that I was respected and felt like a real authority figure.

I was in position of power when I had to evaluate an individual while completing tasks in school. While evaluating, I felt uncomfortable because I did not know the individual. I thought that maybe he was not taking me seriously because of the slight age difference, or maybe because we've never been acquainted previously.

I babysit my cousins sometimes. They are way younger them me so I can tell them what to do. I usually watch over them and give them lunch. They play and watch TV. They do not cause much trouble but would sometimes feel a strong dislike towards me when I don't let hem do something because its harmful. They forget about it quickly but hey give me trouble and do not talk to me for a while. I can control their behaviors by threatening them with time out or no TV. They usually fix their behaviors then.

My high school math teacher asked me to write down the names of anyone who got out of their seats or started to talk while he stepped out of the room. I dint write down any names because I felt bad getting my friends in trouble.

During an extended week at work, I had to take over the manager's position due to a family matter that my manager had to take care of. I had to watch over my co-workers and act as if I was the manager. I felt like I was given a task that I simply did not want to do.

I had a friend in high school named Camel. she always copy my work without even understand my writing which is not good. so one day, I decide to talk to her about it no matter how hard it is because she is my friend. But few days later, se came back to me and apologized and our friendship grow older ad older.
I was captain of my high school soccer team. I felt strong but tried not to put down my other teammates to much. I believed if I failed myself in a game I failed my whole team.

My little brother wanted an Iphone for his birthday. My dad is the head of the family and the one that has the final word. Since my dad was out of house for work for one week, mom let me be in control of the decisions. I though that a smartphone is a little too much for a twelve year old, and so decided not to buy the phone.

Summer of 2012 when I was a camp counselor at the YMCA. Everyday I was in a role of power because I was looking after children and their well-being. I had to make certain judgment calls, and I had the power to tell a child what to do (if they didn't clean up after snack time or something to that effect). I had the power to write them up if they were being disrespectful, or to even talk to their parents at the end of the day. It wasn't so much that it was empowering but more of a rewarding job that carried prestige. The only reason it would be a powerful position is because you have not just one, but many lives in your hands, and that is how you have to think of it. You alone may see something another counselor couldn't which is why it is so important to really look after each child. Ultimately, we called the shots and controlled the outcome of many situations that could have possibly been bad. For example, the Y took a trip to the Eagles stadium. It is so huge an adult could probably have trouble if they got lost. We had to make sure that they stayed together at all times and nobody trailed off. It was hard and stressful, but when you're in that position, you remember your in charge, and if a child isn't listening to you, you always have a choice of what should be done. You take charge of a situation without being mean and they will respect you.  Sometimes, you even change lives  and that kid looks forward to seeing you everyday and next summer. It was a much more rewarding job than stressful.
I president of my high school class. everyone had to come to me if they waned to change or do something major in my high school. T
I don't think I was ever in a position like this.

I was an assistant group supervisor, in charge of children ages 6-10. the children were being to loud in the classroom and I asked several times to be quiet so that we could play another game. during this event I, stopped all classroom activities and they sat quietly in the classroom. I was feeling aggravated and tired. and I thought as soon as I can get them under control we can play another game.

My position of power would most likely be when I worked in my mother's day care. It was powerful because I actually taught these kids and they had to listen to what I had to say and retain the information. I dealt with them one on one as well as in groups. I disciplined them with saying things like "please", "thank you", "I apologize" and things of that sort to instill in them to have manners towards not only other children but adults as well. It was a power that made them learn and pay attention, and It was a good power at the same time. I did not abuse it, because nothing felt better then one of the kids coming up to me and saying "I know how to do this now !".

In high school I was the track captain and it was my duty to not only watch over the team, but to also be a positive example for them to follow. To do this I was very active at my high school and I made sure I showed respect to everyone because I represented my team whenever I was not at practice. I would lead most practices and try my best to push everyone past their own limits so that they could do great at a track meet. Our goal was to win as many track meets as we could and to then go to the state championships. Not everyone was able to make it to the state championships but a large amount made it because they worked hard for it at practice, and I was their to guide them. Being their leader made me feel a strong sense responsibility, because I not only had to train them physically I had to train them mentally as well. However I am glad I did it for most of my high school career because it allowed me to hold a type of position I didn't know I could handle.Now I am comfortable with positions of power.

The only time I had power in a certain situation was when a teacher back in high school commented that I had an awkward hand writing. I felt embarrassed, hurt, and even wanted to quite school all together. My thoughts were if a teacher that already has a major and went to collage is telling me I am not good for collage then I tough it was true I should not be thinking of going to collage. The best part was I was embarrassed hurt and wanted to cry, but that did not stop me from speaking up. I told him he war very disrespectful, and next time he going to criticizes me or comment in my paper to check his spelling before correcting mine. (He wrote awkward wrong.) The best part that professor was the CEO of the school, but at that instance when I spoke I felt the power. I may not had the advantage, but I made that professor regret it to this day I am in my third semester in collage, and I am actually doing pretty well.

I had to evaluate a group of kid's performance as actors for a role in a high school play. As each kid performed I noticed the nervousness in their voice and posture. It reminded me of how I felt when I first started high school, nervous and scared. As each mini performance went on I based their fluentness of the character and acting skills. It made me feel like I had control over each person's life. My decision was part of a life changing situation for that one person. It felt good to be able to choose who was best fit for the part, but afterwards when I noticed all the sad faces of disappointment it made me realize that power is not all that wonderful to have, especially when its controlling other people's lives and outcomes.

Each time I baby sit my nieces and nephews I am seen as a person with power because I may be perceived as an authority figure. I tell them what they can and cannot do, and where to go. I feel that I am only directing them to keep them from harm but I don't feel I have power over them but their situation.

When I go to work I am always in a position of power. I am a nanny to 3 adorable little kids. When I am trying to make a situation go a certain way, for instance,  one day 3 year old Drew wanted me to play outside with him but he had left a pile of food on the floor. Instead of directly asking him to clean up, I will give him a "choice". I said something to the effect of "Drew that is a great idea and while I would love to go outside with you, there is a pile of food on the floor that needs to be cleaned up first" After he cleaned up I gave him a hug and said "Great Drew, now we will go outside!"

I Was once playing a reality game with my friends called Big Brother , and in this game it involves voting people out. So I won a challenge called the HOH , and I was given power to nominate to other housemates for eviction.

At the end of every semester of high school, I had the chance to evaluate a portion of students for their overall behavior by giving them A,B or C. Well, I did feel joy for having such a power, but sometimes it would be difficult for me to judge my classmates, especially my friends. Although I tried to be as just as possible, I would somehow feel guilty(or more accurately, awkward) after I give them bad grade.

Wen m little bother was around years old I use to always make him do what I told him too. One day, my mom told me to dust the tables in the house because we had company coming over. I didn't really feel like doing it so I told m little brother to do it for me. If he disagreed with me I always respond saying "I'm telling Dad." knowing e doesn't live with us. So my brother would take what I said seriously and dusted the tables.

During my senior year of high school I was the editor of the yearbook at my high school. During that year, I learned many things about being a leader. It took a bit of time for the sense of power to wear off, but once it did I felt more a part of the team than I ever had. By allowing me to have the power of editing and guiding the other team members, I found the place where I fit in. I had the most experience with our programs and spent a lot of time helping the other students when I wasn't busy making corrections and editions. It helped me to gain a sense of belonging and helped me to learn new skills. I always thought that the editors, as my previous years of experience showed, were in charge of everything and took advantage of the fact that they were able to do what they wanted with the pages that I had created. I did my best to show my team members that, even though I was editor, their opinions and work mattered to me as much as my own work did.

I was a trainer at my old job. With that job description I have the right to send an employee home if I felt the need too. I didn't really use my authority because it never was necessary. Although, I did get a lot of respect from my fellow co-workers. I felt very respected .

I recently had to train a new employee at my work for a job opening that was e same as mine. This mean I had to show them what is to be expected of them, and what needs to be done when. I felt very in control and it felt good to be teaching someone else something.
I once was in a group project and was made the leader by the teacher. I had to assign peope to projecvts and then report on their performance.

Well, I used to be the "executive of classroom environment" back in elementary school, which is in charge of our classmates whenever we clean our classroom everyday in the afternoon.  It was a pretty big job because you are in charge of the tidiness of the classroom. I could also mark people points off when they don't do their jobs, or if I was having a bad day and he/she wasn't nice to me that day.  Normally, the class student leader is highest position of student leaders. But when it comes to cleaning, I could get to controlled them since they still need to clean the classroom and I could still mark them points off whenever I want.
The only position of power that I was ever in was when I was a camp counselor. I felt more responsible and mature because I knew the group of kids needed structure and that job was for me to do.

My mom, my classmate and I were riding a three-seat bicycle on a mountain. When we rode down the hills, the brake lost control, the bike rushed down faster and faster, we couldn't stop it. There were many other bikes on the rode, a kind of crowd. I control the wheel. I was really nervous, yelling at people to give a way. I afraid we will bump someone or fall off from the cliff. In the end of the road, we decide to jump off the bike because if we got into the main road, there would be more car and more people.

During high school, several underclassmen came to me for unofficial counseling and emotional support. At that time, I wasn't heavily burdened by this sudden placement of power. Also, I did think that some of the issues discussed were petty and trivial, but I was willing to help regardless. More often than not, the issues were with relationships. I don't remember much else besides that.

As assistant to the CEO I was in a position to influence whether or not our IT person continued to have a job. I was able to convey or withhold information about this person's job performance. I was encouraged by our human resources director not to be too hard on this individual, even though the activities and initiatives the tech was undertaking were far beyond not only the scope of his position but also his capacity to execute in a professional and thorough way (not to mention industry standards). Most of those working in this tech-start up have an above average technology skill set, meaning that the mistakes, oversights, and foibles that I witnessed were visible to the majority of the people who worked for the company. And yet we persisted in not providing him with proper oversight. It was within my power to report each and every screw-up and have him fired and yet, I did not. Even though his behaviors and attitudes caused me consternation and aggravation I sought to empathize with his situation and allowed his true superiors (who could wield the hatchet) to make their own assessments.
I guess I am in power at home when my nieces and nephews come over. I try to play and joke around with them but I also am strict if they start acting up.
Usually, I'm the one being controlled or evaluated, unless deciding who lives or dies counts as being in this sort of power.

When I was a soccer captain in high school, I guess you can say I was in a position of power. I would direct the team and they would listen to me and follow my rules. I obviously felt powerful, respected, and I can say that helped my self-esteem. I wanted them to know that I was the captain and that they had to listen to me. It was more of responsibility and team work so I was a very good captain.

Whenever I babysit my cousins. I am in charge of everything that has to do with their well being and also everything else. Sometimes I'll be lazy and make my cousin do something for me. She listens to me because she knows I'm in charge. She rarely fights me.

Felt controlling since I had the final say. I did my best to be a leader without being too harsh.

I was put in charge as the manager where I worked while my manager was out of town. It was nice to be in charge of getting things done and having people who could help me do it. The disciplinary aspect of taking on the responsibility as manager was the downside.

I was put in the position to direct people on what kind of posters the school needed for an 8th grade event at my high school. Sometimes I likes being the leader because when I don't see order and no one will step forward I figure I should take that lead.

I've had to evaluate colleges in terms of what grade I think they deserved while working on a group project. I was in a situation where I had to teach some fellow team mates some technique in the sport. I was able to control what I taught them and what they took out from that lesson. I helped to evaluate students to see if they would be fit for a program called CIVITAS at my high school.  We interview incoming freshman and ask them about their interests to see if they would excel in our program.  The freshman are always nervous when they first come in the room, so I want to make the environment as comforting as possible.  Welcoming them is important and when I went through the same process I remember being really scared.  Most of them don't have the same communication skills however which makes it hard to talk to them.  I feel like I had to press the information out of them sometimes.  The students who answered questions fully and took a lot of time in the room were my favorite because they had a conversation with us rather than answering the questions briefly to finish the interview.  It is a lot of power to have over these students because I am deciding their future at Rio, so I feel like the evaluators were always very friendly and wanting them to do well in the interview so that they could join our program.

An incident when I was in a position of power and a position to evaluate individuals was when I was captain of the lacrosse team.  I had to guide the newer players through the game in order to win. In addition, many of these players did not know how to play therefore, I got mad when we started to lose.  However, even though I was frustrated, I enjoyed teaching the new players how to play lacrosse and to learn the rules that come along with it.  I remember being happy and proud at the end of the season because we were now a well rounded team, and I was aware that I played a part in the achievements of the team.

When I was in a position of power, I was at the time working on my Eagle Scout Award. In middle school, I was in the ASB class, in which I was the leader of the poster-making committee. leading small group in class. i knew some were not as outspoken/shy and needed a little persuasion to engage in task. I still am a little shy at times and know how hard it is to engage on my own sometimes, so I have begun to take the initiative in many academic situations, as of late.
I was responsible for interviewing and training new recruits on the job.  I had feelings and thoughts of responsibility, and pride at the fact that I was trusted with the task.

I do not think i was in a position where i was in power. if i was i don't think i remembered what happened.

it felt pretty good. I got to select the teams for our intersquad game in baseball practice one day. I tried making them as fair as possible but its hard when you know everybody and their talent level. I chose favorites on a couple of tough decisions and gave myself the benefit of the doubt

the situation in which i was in power was when i babysat my cousins. i controlled whether or not they were going to get free time based on their behavior. being in power felt good because my cousins complied to however i asked them to behave.

I was selected to be the leader of  a group project. We had to talk about our research and make a presentation for the class. As the varsity captain of my high school soccer team, i was able to control all the players, most importantly the girls in the forward position. they were eager to score a goal, i made sure i told them how to play as a team and how they have to count on each other to be able to succeed. they listened to my words and turned them into action, they got up close to the goal and started communicating and when they saw the right moment to shoot, one of them did. they were both very happy as well as myself.

The situation was in high-school at cheer-leading tryouts. I was co-captain and I felt very powerful because I knew what it meant to be apart of the cheer team. I had an open mind and I tried to be critical but not overly critical because many people have many different skills.

I was a leader of a group. I would not say I had power since we worked as a group but, if I asked them to do something they would do it. It was more like a project.
no experince

I believe i am good at making tough decisions however i dont like situations where the fate of another human rests on my choice.

When I was playing for a JV soccer team at Point Loma High School, I felt in control because I played very well and helped out my team mates. I would tell what they were suppose to do and how to do it.

When I used to babysit, children would ask me for candy or to go to the pool on a cold and windy day so I would say no. Candy is bad in excess amounts and would have made the children too hyper to handle while going to an unheated pool when it was too cold presented the possibility of someone getting sick. Sometimes it is necessary to tell another person no, if it helps them learn and you can't get everything in life that you want.

i was a summer camp counselor and that put me in lots of power over the campers. I was able to control when they had snack, when they were allowed to play, and also control what we did throughout the day. I felt pretty powerful but also overwhelmed. At my job, I was given the opportunity to be a Crew Lead for a dinner shift because none of the four other Crew Leads were available to work. The responsibilities I had gave me an immense sense of power, for I had to operate the front of the house of the dining area, as well as instruct the other employees of what to do, and when to go on their breaks. I was able to train some entry level employees and evaluate their performances, as well as discuss with them how they can improve in their tasks. I felt as if I was moving up in the ranking as work, and I hope that soon I too can be promoted to Crew Lead and prove my worth and skill at my job.

I feel a position of power when i am watching and taking care of a dog or babysitting a mall child. most dogs and small children are incapable of getting want they want (food, water, toys etc.), therefore I had the power to give them what they wanted or needed.
