Now looking back on it, I guess i did control a lot of they activities and essentially their lives to an extent.

I have baby sitted my little cousin before. He is about 6 years old. When i watched him i was in a position of power because he wasn't old enough to take care of himself. We were at my house playing, and watching tv most of the day. I liked the feeling of him having to ask me if he could do something else or if he could go somewhere. Then i knew for sure what was going on for most of the time. When he asked me if he could watch a certain TV show, i was able to ask him why and watch his reactions of happiness when i decided it was okay for him to watch. It made me feel good to know that he was happy with my decision and i liked the idea that i was able to make those types of decisions even if they seem pretty small.

I host children's birthday parties and so I am in control of the kids and it is my job to make sure that the mom and birthday child are happy. It is also my job to make sure that the party is running smoothly. Before every party, I am usually always nervous. I have no idea what to expect from the party because no two parties have ever been the same. Each party that I have hosted have had their own unique individual experiences. I usually call my parties the Monday of the party and get to know the birthday child and the party mom. This lets me get a feel of their attitude and it lets me get to know my birthday child a lot better. By the time their party rolls around, usually on a Friday night, Saturday or Sunday afternoon, I have prepared a series of activities for the kids to participate in. It is my job to plan the party from start to finish. There have been occasions where I have been stressed because a mom wanted to much from me and other times I have been very relaxed because the parents wanted to just sit back and relax.

In my high school band, I was the section leader which meant that I was in control of the other members in our section..  While I enjoyed having this power, I did not let to get to my head and I was very level headed about it.  At one point I had to decide who was going to play what part and in order to do that, I had to listen to everyone play and evaluate their abilities to decide where they should go in the section.  It was hard to be unbiased since all of the students were technically my peers, but I knew that I had to do what was best for the band.

Once I go out with my schoolmates, two boys who are younger than me, and who are new in San Diego, I play an important role to lead them to go. Every time when I become a leader, I feel confident and do something more efficiently. I think the good effect is resulted in the power, and people could get promotion in their little groups so that it will have more motivation to do things better.

I used to be the caption of my club soccer team at my local high school. I was in charge of keeping all of the players on top of everything and helped them with what they needed. They came to take to me if there was a problem or an issue and I helped them with that. I evaluated the girls and helped my coach pick the line up. I sometimes felt bad if the girl wasn't good enough to be played or had a problem, my thoughts were important to how the team succeeded.

I remember when I used to babysit often, I would be the one in charge of when the kids would go to bed and getting them ready for bed. I would have to make sure they did this at the hour in which their parents wanted them in bed. When I was the authoritative figure for the kids, I felt cool in a way because it felt like I was a parent although I know it wasn't permanent. I can't wait to have children and I think it was very difficult but rewarding to practice being a parent in situations like this one.

Working on yearbook making others do the work necessary. It was not a hard or scary thing to do it became easier over time and allowed for a good return. I also evaluated the individuals that were to take over after I have left, which was easy also.

When I was in high school, our history teacher made 6 different groups and gave home work to each of them (with different topics). I was the leader of my group. However, i didn't read the instructions carefully so we accidentally changed the topic into something else. After working 2 days, our teacher didn't like the work and wanted us to redo it in a short period of time (as punishment). I felt so bad because it was particularly my fault.

I was ASB President at my High School where I controlled the grades of the students involved in the leadership class. It was a lot of pressure to be incharge of someones "future" especially when most of my friends were in the class, but, nonetheless, I had a great time as President.

I was a volleyball coach for a middle school a few years ago. As a coach, I had the authority, and the power to control the players. For instance, I had the power to create the lineup for the games, substitute players and such. I certainly felt great and important as very players respected my role and decisions.

I knew about something that my younger brother had done that would get him in trouble if our parents found out, and I had power in the situation because he would do something for me in return for not ratting him out. I did not require anything from him because I knew that I would find myself in a similar situation soon enough so I did not require anything of him in the moment and waited to be compensated when he caught me doing something later on.

In high school I was one of the leading individuals in the theater program. A lot of people looked up to me, and I was able to direct individuals to get tasks accomplished. It felt good to be looked up upon as a role model and someone with power. However, there were some particular events that I controlled the outcomes to much and people became resentful. I became aware of how people thought of me and changed the way I spoke and directed individuals because I did not want to abuse my power or offend anyone.
I feel good.

I trained a new hire at work so that he could take over my old duties.  I found it is difficult to train people because personalities and perspectives differ.  I also found that because I wasn't his supervisor and he viewed me more as a peer it was difficult for him to trust in my experience - I addressed this with management.  Overall, I learned about myself and I realized how teaching or training someone requires experience also. I had to learn to play with delivery methods so that I could get my point across.

I started going to the gym about 8 months ago and I really enjoy working out there. I told my friend to join my gym so we could work out together. She said that she doesn't even know anything about working about and that she would feel really uncomfortable since she would not know how to train. I finally convinced her and so she went to the gym with me the other day. That day I felt like my mom when she taught me how to do laundry. I demonstrated some workouts step-by-step, I even gave her a mini tour of the gym, and what function had each machine. I also taught her how to correctly use the machines there so she would not get hurt. It may seem as something really invaluable, but I really felt powerful and as if I was someone really important at the gym. I was glad that someone needed my help and I was able to help her.

Last year I was in many leadership roles in clubs at my school. In one club I was VP so I had to come up with ways our club could fundraise. The fundraiser I remember quite well was a cookie dough one. It became very stressful because I had to make sure that people brought in their money and that they were working hard to sell enough. We had to reach 60 orders so that we could place the minimum amount from the company. We were able to reach this goal but not without extending the amount of time. It was extremely stressful but once we finished it I felt very accomplished. In this situation I felt like people were looking to me to complete this task, it made it so much more important to do well and not let them down.

During my junior year of high school, I held the position of the Editor-in-Chief of my school's news publication. It was my responsibility to collaborate with a team of staff writers and fellow editors to brainstorm story ideas for the upcoming issue and distribute the work evenly. It was also my job to establish deadlines, collect and edit work, and graphically piece the articles together. It became immensely overwhelming towards the end of my junior year because fewer and fewer students took an interest in the newspaper and we were very short-staffed. In addition, our media adviser was not very helpful or encouraging. Leading the newspaper became a very negative force in my life, and I decided to quit my position my senior year.
At work I have been put in charge of the retail crew at times when a manager was not available. I was afraid they wouldnt listen to me but for the most part they did.

I felt that with the power I had that I would have to be careful and have to pay attention to others opinion so I could take them under consideration. It is always best to have good teamwork when working a group. But to have that much power felt awesome.
I felt much more confident and less shy than usual.
I felt confident and shy

In high school I was the captain of my dance team. I was satisfying that i could make the team anything that I wanted it to be. I could make individuals dance they I wanted them to so that the dance would turn out the best it could be. However, there was a lot of pressure to live up to the previous captains who had done so well.

I was the vice president of my student counsel in high school. I was in charge of all of the prom decorations, food, theme, etc. I felt very important, but also very stressed about whether the event would be a success or an epic failure. It was a total hit though, so everything turned out ok!

I had a position of power when I babysat my little brother and sister every summer until I started attending college here at A&M. It was normally after school hours, and I would pick my brother up from daycare, and it would normally be certain weekends when my parents had to work. The feelings I had were that I felt dominant since I normally have to listen to my parents, but this time I was in charge as oldest child. The thoughts I had were that I really wanted to be elsewhere, hanging out with friends who had no responsibilities but that was not the case for me.

When I was driving my brother on a trip to get groceries he ask if I would stop at a nearby drive thru restaurant.  I knew I was in control and would make the decision of whether or not we would stop for food.  Even though I was hungry too, I liked the feeling of power so I played mind games with him to make him think we would not stop.

I was babysitting my friends little brother and he is only one year old so I of course held power over him. I feelt kind of nice to have someone rely on you to take care of them. However, on the other hand, he needs constant attention and because you hold the upmost power over him, he has to come to you for everything that he wants.

MY SENIOR YEAR OF HIGH SCHOOL I WAS THE STUDENT COUNCIL PRESIDENT WHICH HAD A LOT OF RESPONSIBILITIES THAT WENT ALONG WITH IT. I WASN'T ABLE TO DO ALL THE ACTIVITIES BY MYSELF AND NEEDED THE OTHER OFFICERS TO HELP ME DO STUFF.

In highschool, I was President of an organziation called Key Club. This club was a volunteering organziation that helped out around the community. As President I was in charge of 30 officers and over 200 members. I felt stressed a lot of the time because of the role and it was my duty to make sure the club was successful. I was mostly stressed out during meeting events because there would be so many people there at once and they would all approach me. I thought it was a good experience overall though because it taught be alot about leadership and responsibility.

My senior year of high school I was in a group called PALs which was a very selective group with a long application process. I had to choose the next years PALs class by using their application and interview as a basis so the weeks which the application process was happening many of the applicants seemed to be "sucking up" to the other current PALs and myself.

In high school I was an officer in drill team. I helped plan how practice was going to be scheduled and helped others become better dancers, it made me feel confident and good knowing I could help others.

I was a fish camp counselor last summer and had control over many incoming freshmen. We instructed them to do yells, go to events, and interact with each other. I felt very nervous at the beginning, but eased my way into the position by gaining the favor and trust of many of the freshmen and felt secure by the end of the four days.

When I was a freshman in college, a close friend and roommate of mine was scared that his girl friend might have been pregnant. I was shocked knowing this because he was unable to tell anyone else. He confided in me something he was unable to confide in someone else. The people around us were very concerned but were unaware of what my roommate was facing. I knew something that other people around us wanted to know but I kept it a secret to protect the dignity of my friends. In that situation I felt reponsible and trustworthy and was happy my roommate saw those qualities in me. Otherwise, he would not have told me something so personal.

When I use to babysit and be in charge of my younger siblings, I felt as if I had the power to tell them anything and they would have to obey.If they wanted something they would have to listen and do as i said or they would be punished by not recieving their "want". I felt important and at the same time sort of pressured with the responsibility and the need to look like I knew what I was doing.

My brother needed some items of his dropped off at work when I wasn't anywhere close to his job location. I told him if he wanted what I had for him, he would have to do anything I asked him to do. It was a good feeling having the upper hand and being superior, but i also felt guilty as if i was abusing my power and being controlling.

My senior year in college, I was the captain of the baseball teram. Everyday I would go out on the field and get the guys going wheither it was getting them started with stretching or pushing them harder to get better. It wasn't a one day deal, it was an everyday thing even just at school when they come upe to me and ask me what are we going to do at practice. At times they wouldn't do what the coach wanted us to do and yes I would get on them. I felt like I was the boss but not one where I am always getting on them. I felt like being the captain did give me a feeling of power but only to a certain extent.

Being in charge of group projects in the present, I'm usually the one to organize it. I usually do not trust most people to get the work done because I was taught in an excelled magnet program where the people I was surrounded with were very intelligent and independent. If we were ever put into groups, everyone contributed equally, and it was never a worry that someone would have to do more or less. I am very confident in the outcome when I am in charge because I trust my own work, however when other people are also doing work, I am skeptical that they have done as good of a job as I could have done doing their part. I like to be in charge, however I like to have people that will work hard along my side.

In engineering, we had to judge the quality of other teams' poster designs for a project, and give them a score based on how well they did.  I felt uneasy, because I don't want anyone to get a bad grade, however, some of the presentaions were not very well done.  Power postitions make me feel this way, because I don't like to let other people down.

We were having tryouts for solos in a show. People were auditioning, and I was one of the people deciding what part each person would get. The most important thought on my mind was not to be biased, because some of the people that were auditioning were good friends of mine. It's hard to be fair without hurting people, but that's how life is. No one always gets whatever they want. I felt bad for the people who didn't get parts, but there is always next year.

This one time I was captain of the soccer team and the coach listened to me on who to play.  I hated one of my teammates because she was lazy and unskilled and I paid my coach in rice krispies to never start her again. I felt bad, and obviously he wasn't doing it for the rice krispies, but we were so much better without her. And I like winning.
I was a manager at the place I worked. I felt very confident about myself and it felt nice to be the one calling the shots for those under my supervision.

One incident when i was in a position of power was when i was on slating comittee for my sorority. We got to choose who we thought would be the best candidates for the next years council positions, and then present them to the rest of the chapter. Even though we may have been friends with some people running, we had to choose what would be best for the sorority as a whole. This put a lot of pressure on me, because you are torn between helping a friend get what they have worked hard for and want so badly, but also to be fair and equal in decisions.

My senior year I was team captain of my water polo team in high school. I was in charge of pretty much everything and worked very close alongside my coach. I evaluated all the players and helped decide who was on varsity, I planned workouts for practices, and ran the team during the game in pool because it nearly impossible to hear the coach during the middle of the game. It always felt very good to be in control of the outcome of the game, and it felt even better when we qualified for state and ended up finishing 7th out of about 200 teams in the state of Texas. I was in charge of the team that made school history, and it gave me a sense of pride because all of the hard work I had put into the sport and team had paid off.

I was vice-president of a health organization in high school, though it had few members. I took on the position as a way to boost my college application and because the club lacked other suitable candidates. I remember mostly worrying over how to manage the club effectively and recruit new members, as well as nervous about how my actions would be reflected in the eyes of other members.

In high school, I was captain of the color guard team and therefore I was the one in power. I managed the times we practiced, the lengths of the practices, the performance attire and other things as well that were sometimes disagreed upon. Since there was twelve members, not everyone agreed with my ways and there was always drama and frustration with each other when they didn't get what they wanted or had to struggle for it.

I was babysitting my siblings and so I was left in charge of what they did for the night. I liked to be in control of what they did at first, but after a while I got tired of it. Eventually I did not want to be in charge anymore.

I was the one of the coaches for our flag football team. I felt that it was my responsiblitiy to win, even if it meant that I had to be strict to the other players. I knew I had to be a little strict, but I didn't want to be because they are still my friends.
From what I recall I have not had such an incident before.
when i was captain of my soccer team- i was nominated captain of my soccer team so i got to determine who started and helped the coach with stuff
When I am driving people around i feel powerful because I have the ultimate decision of where we go. Nobody else can physically make us go somewhere if im not okay with it

While coaching a 17 year old select summer baseball team I was in charge of all the pitchers and catchers on the team.  I controlled who did what and when, as well as in-game pitch calling.  It was a lot of responsibility but I trusted my own judgement and the results tended to always work out the way that I wanted them to with no animosity among the players.
i was babysiitting my younger brothers and i felt in control of because I decided where and when to get food.

In high school I used to be an officer for my class. I would plan different events and people would give their requests to me and I would try to fulfill them to the best of my abilities. I felt proud of the work that it took for me to obtain this position. I felt accomplished when I was able to complete the tasks given to me and I got to see what I was able to do. I enjoyed being in this position and it made me very happy that I was able to do this. At times it was frustrating when people didn't understand what I was able to do and what I was unable to do. I would be criticized for not doing exactly what requested but it only bothered me a little because I understood that I could not make everyone happy. Overall it was a good experience.

As a big sister, I have the responsibility of taking of my younger siblings. There were times in the past when they did not want to obey me. I would use their toys or my parents as an incentive to make them listen to me.

During sorority recruitment I had to have conversations with different girls coming through that were looking for a house. At the conclusion of these conversations, I had to vote on whether or not the girl would return the next day. I honestly did not enjoy this job at all because it was requiring me to make a judgement call that could shape this 18 year old's future in college. I understood at the end of the day that the outcome would by no means be detrimental to the girl, but I still felt that I didn't have enough knowledge to make a fair judgement.

Being president of student council in high school I had to make decsions as to who was qailified in being in the organization and who did not meet the requirements. The descion I had to make was difficult and a bit stressful but I felt that I had made the right choices. I felt responsible for what outcomes I had chose but I was also confident.

When I was in highschool I was the captain of the varsity soccer team. As such I had a lot of control on who gained starting positions and who sat the bench. It wasn't total control, but I did have a strong say. Many players who I considered friends would come to me asking me to put in a good word for them based on our friendship, not on the players ability. This made me uncomfertable because either I was forced to make a recommendation that I was uncomfertable with or I would make a friend angry.

I was the captain of a soccer team.  I had the decision making power as to which girls were chosen for varisty and for JV.  I had a great influence on the coach and the decisions that he made regarding the team.  Also, I was able to influence the starting line-up and the overall game plan against opponents.  I enjoyed this position because I feel that I am a good leader.

I was the manager at a girls birthday party shop back in high school, so a lot of the decisions I made would directly affect each one of the girls birthday parties, so it was important that I was always alert and ready for any situation that would come whether that be a complaint or praise from a parent or a task that needed to be done to make the day more special for the kids.
One time I was the leader of a group and a lot of people had a lot of different ideas and I had to pick and choose which ideas we used and which ones we discarded.

In high school, I was the leader of a club that was very prominent. To get into the club, one had to apply for admission. As part of my position, I was in charge of admitting those who wanted to be apart of the club. Decision-making was tough as I knew I would hurt some people's feelings by denying them entry.

Selecting members for our PALs group, I felt uncomfortable excluding people because I knew everyone really wanted to be a part of the organization. It was hard because we only had a few spots, and many of them seemed like likely candidates.

When I was in high school, I was a leader in a volunteer group. I felt in control because I was able to tell the people in the group what tasks to perform, when it needed to be done, and when they can have breaks. I didn't really feel in control at that point, but once the volunteering was over, I realized how much control I did have over them.

For the majority of the time when I baby sit my little cousins, control is something that I have over them 99% of the time. For instance, my little cousin Brandon wanted to eat the cookies that we made, even though he was not done with his dinner. I told him that the only way he could get to eat the cookies was if he finished all of the food on his plate and drank his cup of milk. Once I told him that, he pouted in his chair for a few minutes then realized that I was not going to change my mind, as I sat in the chair next to him not moving. I watched as his face changed from a pout to a look of determination to finish the food. He finished the plate in a few minutes and got his cookies like I promised.
I was a social committee chair on my high school drill team. It was nice to have some power over the younger girls after being in their position.

A particular time in which I exerted power over an individual was babysitting a 6 year old girl. She continuously begged to be given a can of coke, even though her mom specifically said to not let her drink any carbonated beverages. I saw her trying to grab one, took the can of coke away from her, and told her she was not allowed to have the coke. I knew that coke was not good for her and it would benefit her if she did not drink it. I felt satisfied with my decision and my responsible position.

I was captain of the varsity volleyball team my senior year of high school. It was an intimidating task because it required a lot of hard decisions and difficult situations with my team mates. I had the power to decide what the team wore, where we went outside of playing games, what our shirts looked like, how we rode on the bus, and served as a mediator when girls were having disagreements. There were many times when I felt like I was having to be harsh or mean when making decisions that my team mates disagreed with, but I had to realize that it was my responsibility to make choices for the good of the team, even if there was backlash from them. I tried very hard to think about how I was treating the girls I had power over and taking their opinions into consideration while still weighing in my own opinion and instinct. Having power was difficult and rewarding, I felt very confident in my abilities as a leader and the actions I took with my power.
In a group project, I had the power to influence the grade someone received based on how I felt they contributed to the project. Likewise, they could also influence mine.
When I was captain of my volleyball time; I loved being in power and liked being in control

I was soccer team captain in high school and I often had to give evaluations on my teammates to my coaches. This would have some effect on which positions they got to play. This made me feel a lot of pressure because I liked all of my teammates and wanted to make it fair.

An incident where I was in power was last year when I was in high school. I was drum major of the band and I literally had the power to control the whole band, of course to a limit. I helped them march and play together. the feeling I felt was overpowering in a good way because I loved it, not because I was in power, but because people came to me for help. my thought were that they trusted me and liked me and that made me feel confident. this showed me leadership and again showed me what it felt to have power over persons.
while working with others I feel as if they look up to me as a guide. usually when I know what I am dong I can give orders and people do look to me for guidance

mostly sports events, swimming or capture the flag. I being team captain judged each individuals strengths/weakness and decided where they were in the line up or what positions they would fill. I felt competent and able to control the situation. I felt focused and determined and believe I made a good leader. I talked with my subordinates and felt I made good calls on where to place them while taking into consideration their wishes.

The other day, somebody in my psychology class had forgotten to bring a scantron for the quiz. They asked around to see if anybody had an extra, and I gave them one I'd happened to have. In that moment I'd basically controlled their grade on the quiz. I wondered if anybody else would have offered up their extra scantron if I had not. I was just happy I was able to help and make somebody's day a little easier.

I was a Captain on my softball team for 2 years and at that time I felt like it was my job to guide all the girls in the right direction and to lead by example. To take my knowledge of the game and to pass it on to them. It was a very rewarding experience and I feel so blessed and honored that I had this opportunity

It was during a volleyball game in high school. I was the captain of the Varsity team, and the opponents had the ball and they were about to serve. I felt that that shouldn't have been their ball because clearly the hitter on their team hit it out of the court, and the ref had called it in. I argued to the ref that the ball was hit out of the court and we talked for a few minutes, and the ref finally decided that it was our ball. I felt that it was wrong for that team to feel like they had made that point without telling the truth. But, we got the ball and served it and made the point.

I was a judge of 4-H public speaking contest. I didn't necessarily feel in power, but I felt a responsibility to truly listen and have an understanding of the topics on which the speakers were speaking about because I knew they put a lot of time and effort into this prepared contest.

A position I was in that was a position of power was a staff member at a dance camp in San Antonio.  I had the power of evaluating dancers and rating them on their performance. It felt very good to be in power since usually I feel as if I am powerless and dependent of those in power to reach the goals I have.

I had a lab partner who did nothing during the experiment. She grew up a baby compared to the rest of her siblings and was always handed everything. Upon coming to lab, she fully expected to sit and watch and not participate, but still reap the academic grade from her partner. When she needed the lab data or had questions, I did not think it was right to hand them to her. I had to input long data tables to make seven graphs worth of results and she refused to input a single digit, watching me place everything in next to me. At this point I was angry and refused to give her a single piece. She resorted to cheating another way to get the data. I had and still have no pity for her.

I was part of a student organizational group that was selecting students to go abroad on a trip. I got to interview the students and remember that I had been in their position beforehand. It was strange feeling that I had somehow surpassed that feeling of nervousness to get where I was then.

Every Christmas my family and I all get together at my cousin's house. I have many younger cousins. They all wanted a certain toy that my aunt had brought to the house. However there was only three of the toys left and a total of five of them. I decided to make it interesting and had them play games to see who was going to get the toy. Whoever won the games would be the three who got the toys. As we were doing the games I could the look determination and nervousness on there faces. Each one wanted the toy so bad and was trying their hardest to win. It was a struggle having to give the toys to the top three and the other not getting anything.

On one occasion I had a hat in which my friend wanted to wear. they begged me, complimented me and even went to the extent of making me a gift out of random materials. In this moment, I felt in control because I had something that they desired, and I had the power to decide whether or not they could use it.
During high school I held a leadership position which I was passing down to a younger student. It felt weird being able to control a situation because I also wanted what was best for my part.

In high school I had to help choose the members for a group called PALS. Being a current pal, I knew we were looking for someone who wasn't afraid to be silly or outgoing. So, we made them do some funny embarrassing things and from observing that we then got to decide who was right for PALS and who wasn't.

In high school I was in charge of my bio lab group so I had to make sure everyone got their part done and that the group as a whole was successful. In general, I am a person who does not like being in control over other people because I don't like telling people what they can/can't do or what they should/shouldn't due, however, a small part of me like the power of holding the group together. I felt really good when the group would come out with an A.

I am the older sibling and when I was younger I used to use my greater knowledge and ability to persuade my brother to do something that I wanted. We only had an hour of screen time a day and so usually we would split it up into two 30 minute sections and he chose what to watch for one and I chose what to watch on the other but because I knew that I could manipulate him to watch the full hour of my show I would. It made me feel smarter and content because I got what I wanted fairly easily.

I was in a position of power when my sister, who is a horse trainer, sent me by myself to go look at possible horses to buy. At that point, it was completely up to me to make the correct decision of which horse would be the right one because my sister trusted me with this power. I was nervous but also honored to be given this trust.

When I volunteered last summer for this particular organization that I have been involved with for many years, I felt I had a position of power due to my sonority and my awareness of the processes of the organization. Also my step father co-founded the organization; this also gave me a sense an additional sense of power. During the event, a golf tournament in which the organization put on, I felt I had the ability to give commands to other volunteers.

I was in charge of the NHS fundraising at my high school and it was hard getting everyone to attend, because community service was mandatory. I gave many warnings about having to attend to events to those who never went. At the end of the year the NHS sponsor asked me about the students who did not attend any fundraising events and asked if they should continue NHS next year and I voted no. I felt bad for voting no, but they did not do what they were supposed to do so it would not be fair to the others if they stayed in the organization when they weren't being responsible.

When I was in chemistry lab with my lab partner was an incident I felt like I had power. She wasn't reading the directions correctly, so I had to correct her and take control of the experiment. Even when she went to go ask our TA questions, the TA agreed that we were doing it right because of my help. I basically did the experiment while she got supplies and observed. I felt bad that I was kind of taking over because I'm usually not a bossy person but I also felt good because I knew what I was doing.

My friend Zach needed a place for his girlfriend to stay when she came down to visit him. I told him that if I let her stay with me, he had to take me to at least on a&m football game since he is in the Corp. It was a very mutual agreement and we both ended up happy. That now is our usual deal, his girlfriend stays with me and he takes me to the games.

I was a leader of a group once. There were tasks we needed to complete before a larger tasks. I needed to make sure everyone did their tasks correctly as well as my own. It wasn't that bad. They listened to my instructions, but after a while you kind of get tired of being in charge and responsible for everything the whole time.

Senior year I was the co captain for the volleyball team. During tryouts I especially felt powerful as the coach would come around and ask us what we thought of some people that she had her eye on. In a way it felt good to be important but I felt bad when it was someone I knew well and I was the one telling the coach not to take that person because they simply were not Varsity material.

I was in a position of power this summer during my job as the head life guard of my pool that I was employed at. This job gave me the ability to have a persuasion over other people that worked "for me" as well as the other employees who worked in a similar area of work that I did. Being the head life guard of a very prestigious country club, I had the ability to evaluate other individuals and give them perks and tips on how they could improve themselves in order to be the very best lifeguard they could be. It was also nice to require them to do certain tedious tasks that being head guard no longer required me to do, like fold towels or pick up chair cushions.

I worked at my old job for over two years. By the time I left, I was their oldest employee. My length of time working with the company gained me much prestige. When we received new workers, my managers looked to me to train them. Though we were on the same professional level, I often was treated as if I had power over them.

I remember in high school I volunteered at a elementary school in which I kept students active by playing a basketball game. if the students made a certain amount of shots they received a big prize if they didn't make those shots they still received a prize for participation. what I was doing I felt really good about and at that time as a freshman it felt good to have kids actually listen to me because usually I'm the one taking the orders form others.
I honestly cannot think of a time like this at the moment.

whenever I had to baby sit my little sisters I was always in control over them and they had to listen to what I told them to do. I felt like I was not only responsible for their actions but also anything that might have happened to them while under my supervision.

In some of my projects, I was the leader in power because nobody really wanted to be and was not getting anything done. I had to make them do what they were suppose to do for their own good, because it not only affected my grade it also affected theirs. I really do not like being in power because it is a lot of work to get people to do what they are suppose to do.

One summer, I was in charge of nannying a family friend's four year old son for two days. I would say I was in a position of power because I had to control the little boy and take care of him. I had to make sure he was on task when necessary and monitor his nap time, play time, bed time, etc. The little boy was responsive to my authority, however, being the little kid that he is, he often became cranky or rowdy. On a couple of occasions I had to be strict with him in order for him to listen to me. It was a huge responsibility and I had to be very cautious and attentive. At the end of the two days his mom asked me how he was and because everything went smoothly I could walk away from this nannying job proud, satisfied, and confident!

I believe each person has the ability to be free; therefore, I do not have specific incidence of power, but rather times when I have persuaded or convinced people. For example, last week I convinced two of my brothers to let me have some friends over to their house to watch movies, do laundry, and cook real food since we live in older, smaller dorms. I felt very proud of myself and my skills because my brothers are both stubborn and I managed to convince both of them at once.

As a President for a program, I was able to interview students that were interested in joining the program. I would let them know I was the president of the program just to maybe get them a bit more nervous, but I wasn't mean nor dull during the interview. I was just hoping to notice the potential in the candidates in order to accept them for the following school year. I simply looked toward having a better program and students who really wanted to gain something out of the program itself. That was how I evaluated students along with their grades in order to see the kind of work ethic they had in past classes.

This semester my business class was required to fulfill a semester project requirement in which groups of six individuals would research various topics around the world and present the research to evaluators at the end. During this process, our groups were asked to assign roles to each individual in the group, and I was voted to be the CEO or leader. As the CEO, I had the power of telling the people in my group when and where to meet, and more importantly handled peer evaluations which factored into our overall grade. I felt somewhat anxious because I did not want to let my peers down by grading them harshly, but also wanted to maintain a certain degree of integrity and give honest evaluations. Knowing that these evaluations affected their grades, I gave good yet realistic evaluations of each person and was ultimately at peace with the situation.

I was an state officer for a school organization and i was incharge of leading a group of students to see how well they could perform a simple task that i would assign to them and then question how they felt they could improve. Overall i felt it was a nice experience and everyone had a nice time as far as i knew, i was mainly concerned that no one would get bored or not participate in the activity at all.
I was a summer camp counselor and the power I had over the children made me feel a sense of responsibility.
Because I have a car, I have the power to travel wherever at want. I have the power to offer or reject rides.
i was a student leader in clubs in high school and president of some as well

When I was doing service military in Korea, I was squad leader. Although I was in a position of power, but I was uncomfortable to have the power because I needed to make a choice for my squad and also had to shoulder the responsibility.

Last week I babysat my little cousin Athena. She is only 5 years old so I had power over her. I fed her, played with her and put her to sleep. She trusted in me and I felt a sense of comfort because of that. I was almost like her mom. Without me she would not be able to eat anything or do other common tasks since she is so young.

During my senior year of high school, I was the captain of the school's rugby team. I felt like I had a lot of responsibility as a leader, and I often felt like I had a high expectation to live up to. Therefore, I practiced harder and tried to improve more in terms of skills.

I guess one time when I was in a position of power was in high school when I was the president of a club for seventy plus people. I felt very anxious all the time, and I always felt like I needed to set an example. I always wanted to please everyone, yet gain their respect at the same time.

When I interned at an elementary school this quarter, I was helping out a third grade class. I was leading a small group in games during math and the students were not behaving so I told them we could not play the game until they were sitting on the carpet and not talking. I felt a little bit frustrated and angry, and I was not used to enforcing this much authority. But it was also liberating and I felt powerful because I was able to control the students.

A year ago I was the TA for a  biology teacher in summer school.  I had the responsibility of deciding whether or not to give credit for a student's homework depending on how thorough I believed the work to be.  I usually always gave credit for the homework unless it was completely obvious that no effort was put into it.  I knew that the students in the class struggled with school so it wasn't fair for me to judge their work at the level of what my more academic classes expected of me.  It also made me feel as though I was helping the students pass the course.  I will admit I was concerned with appearing nice to the students since, during the regular school year, they were my peers.

Back in high school I was forced to step up and lead my group in order to pass the class by creating a power point about native plants and the current environment we live in. My peers were very lazy, so I had to make the power point and assign speaking parts to them as well as go into depth in there own areas on the slides presented because they did not do their part and study the lines and basics of our project. I felt overwhelmed at first, but very confident that I knew the whole presentation practically by heart. I didnt like how they did not put in as much effort but it gave me the option to see how much i am capable of by putting me in a tough position.

As an older sister, I constantly am responsible of my little brothers. Being in these type of situations to me feels more relaxing rather than a feeling of responsibility. I enjoy spending quality time with my brothers as I don't have much choice during the school year. Often when I watch them, I ask them and tell them what they can and can't do, thoroughly explaining to each of them why you shouldn't do one particular activity, such as playing in the middle of the road. I don't hesitate to tell them, and I don't feel that by doing school I have more authority over them. I do it because it's in the best of everyone's interest.

I have been placed in charge of group projects and I wanted very badly to receive a good grade, so I made sure the others were doing what needed to be done to accomplish this. I felt strong and yet hated, but I liked the position, because I thrive from being in control.

I was a TA for a class in my community college, and the teacher had allowed me to teach the class after the actual lecture for 30 more minutes so that the students can understand more from a student teacher. This was a great experience as I loved maths and was able to teach the students properly. I would give series of examples to students who would sometimes understand and sometimes not depending on the type of scenario presented by me. I was able to talk to people and they would ask me to help them which made me feel like a person in authority.

When I was biking I took the lead to be in the front of my friend and direct us where to go. Even if my friend may have knew a shorter way, I continued to direct us. She would follow where I would direct us and I felt a confidence in being able to do so. I felt power to have people follow my decisions and sure of my character. I didn't waiver in my feelings and it felt good.

I was in charge of another employee at a job at a fast food restaurant. I felt a lot of pity for the other person because he was incompetent. I did not want to be the one to evaluate him with the truth. I did not want the responsibility. I felt anxious about him reflecting my performance.
Working as a Certified Nurse Assistant, I have had the opportunity to care for for a wide range of patients from infants to the elderly.
Soccer captain. I felt like I could help lead our team to a win. I felt no different when I'm not a captain.

I am a catechist at my church, so I am in a position where I have to teach third graders on Sundays. I have to think of ways to teach children about the abstract teachings of their faith, but they are restless! However, they are very intelligent and preppy, for Sunday mornings. Usually, lessons are set up where desks are arranged in circles, and in this intimate setting, children usually talk with each other and sometimes know each other. I am in power, or in authority, but I can't seem to figure out how to get the attention of children to the point where they are entirely quiet. Despite this, however, I am able to communicate to the children that they need to turn to a certain page, to read along in a book, and I am able to ask them to respond to a question or to read. In which case, if this goes smoothly, I feel that I can move the lesson along, especially when lesson plans have less rigid structure. At the end of the time, I observe my colleague ask the children (as an entire class again) what they learned in that session; this is a process of evaluation of their new-found knowledge, and of our teaching methodology. When the kids leave (we have to tell them to wait for their parents, first, and enforce this rule), my colleague and I discuss methods to improve teaching, and to therefore exert more meaningful authority over the students in such a way that future lessons can be taught smoothly and in an enjoyable manner for student and teacher.

When I was the president of student union back in my high school, I was in charge of running the whole student union and made sure every part work well. When we interviewed the next year student union members, I felt excited, satisfied, and hard to make choice.

when I was tutoring someone, I would ask them to follow my direction, for example, to finish 50 questions or to take a quiz. when I was doing that, I felt a little superior because I had more knowledge than those people, and I felt happy because I could help them.

I was in a position of power when I worked as a intern in a school district. The teachers instructed the students to treat me as if I was a teacher, i.e. they had to follow my instructions. I did not wield my "power" or anything like that, but I was able to use it to make sure the environment was safe, healthy, and a positive learning environment. More important than raw power, I was able to cultivate respect. That made the kids want to learn from me and listen to me, as opposed to ignoring me and running wild. The respect was something that I enjoyed having. It's good to feel needed in the world.

The only incident in which I had a position of power was during an activity at one of my retreats. In the activity, there was a leader, but what the participants didn't know was that I was to act as the worst leader a person could be. My team and I were given a task to build a house out of PVC pipes and wrapping paper. As a "bad" leader, I sat around waiting for people to do their own work. I basically just told my team to do what they wanted to. While they were building, I actually heard my team talking bad about me and were complaining that they were doing all the work and that I wasn't. They did not like this activity at all.
I dont think I was ever in a position of power on another person other than myself

I was an intern for a congressman my 2nd year of college. While doing the internship, sometimes my coordinators would leave the office and would leave me in charge of running the office until they came back. They would often leave for most of the day so everyone else who was in the office at the moment would ask me questions that I believed were beneficial for me to start becoming a leader and growing as a person. I started taking charge of the situations I was in such as answering questions for people who came into the office and giving instructions on who to call next to the other interns. I felt great knowing that I was making a difference, but also excited that my coordinators would be able to see how good of a worker I am. They noticed and over the course of a couple months I started becoming a leader in the office and then promoted to become lead executive for the campaign. I took it as a lesson learned of when an opportunity is given to you to take, then for all sake take advantage of it and make it your life duty to do your best to your abilities.
When the teacher put me in charge of a group for a project. I felt like i had control of their part in the project. Yet I also felt very confident .

I would not describe this event as a situation of power, but it is the closest to power I can think of. I am co-chair for an organization I am part of on campus. We had an incident in which one of our board members posted an picture that did not abide by our policy. I was forced to have to ask her to remove the picture and, along with my fellow co-chair, had to speak to our alumni representative.

In high school, I wrote and directed a musical for the theater department.  The cast was pretty large (around 40 members).  I was excited to be able to direct and guide the students to put on the show the way I wanted it to be, but I was also overwhelmed at having to deal with so many people.  I was constantly stressed out at having to plan rehearsals that would work with everyone's schedules.  In addition, being in charge of the set, lighting, decorations, costumes, ticket sales and so much more just added even more stress.  It was definitely an experience that put me under a lot of pressure, but I enjoyed being the leader and having control.
i have never been in that position of power

I think it would be the time I become a leader of my team to work on a website project. It was hard to get everyone to work and stay on task. When we finally turned something in, I had to also evaluate their work. I had to be honest of those that slacked off and refused to work. I wrote them down and turned the evaluation paper in to my professor.
I follow the person who ask me to do something they favor, one side I am not very happy with people control me but another side that I expect they will reward me as I finish the duty for them.

I was in charge of supervising kids in the UCDMC MIND center.  While their guardians were consulting with child psychologists, I watched children often for over an hour at a time.  I controlled what they were allowed to do, where they were allowed to go, and whether or not they were allowed to have snacks, and what types of snacks they could have.  In the beginning I felt out of my depth working with young children, especially since I had no prior experience babysitting nor did I have any siblings.  I was concerned I would not watch over them properly and was particularly concerned that I may be allowing them to do something that would cause them harm, especially in the case of kids with autism spectrum.  My worries lessened over the two quarters I worked there, but they never went away.  I was most concerned about watching children with whom I could not communicate normally.

In my senior year of high school, I was my school newspaper's sole Features Editor. As Features Editor, I assigned people to write stories, copy edit the stories, and place them onto a layout I made. Although I also wrote, copy edited, and placed stories, I was able to tell people to fix things to how I wanted them. At times I felt bad because I felt like I was bossing them around, but it was nice to have my way and I thought I was not necessarily bossing them around, but telling them how to do it a certain way. I thought I was understanding and lenient yet efficient.

When i was in this situation, I was a leader for my high school picnic event and I basically had to lead everybody and take take them to different events. Many people wanted to do different things at different times and ultimatley I had to the deciding factor. I felt a lot  of pressure and felt that I needed to make wise and fair decisions to make sure everyone will be satisfied. But inorder to finish everything, i felt that I had to take away a lot of freedom and fun and this make me sad.

I was working as a team trying to get speakers to come and talk at an event. My partner was not pulling her weight and so I started to delegate tasks even though it isn't my responsibility. It was nice because then I could have her work on some of the things I didn't want to because she hadn't worked on anything. This meant I had an excuse to give her work.

At work, when my boss leaves I'm the supervisor. I have the power to control when the other workers get to go home, and when they can take their breaks, etc. My feelings don't change much when my boss leaves. I feel a little uncomfortable when I have more power than another worker who is much older than me, but other than that, I don't feel like an all-powerful person or any other feeling or thought like that.

There was a time when I was babysitting my younger brother and he asked me if he could go play outside with his friends and i said "no". He was pretty mad at me and went into his room. Im never usually the one in charge so it felt weird to be bossy and have to be super responsible for another person. I wanted him to go out and have fun but I was just worried that something would happen to him in my care. I felt sad afterwards when i saw him mad at me.

Just this past year I was the Program Co-Director and Assistant to Executive Director at my job for UCDPHSA putting on the largest national Pre-Health Conference in the nation. As Program Co-director I was able to determine if a coordinator's material makes it into the program and have a say in evaluating their performance since I recieve all their work through out the year in order to add it to the program. I think the job was really stressful because on one hand I was trying to be really strict and pick out all the bad apples of the group. However on the other hand I had to try and be understanding of the person's situation before bringing them up for review by the board. If I say this person didn't turn in any of their work then the person risk losing all their incentive and worse, fired. I spent most of the year being either too nice or too strict and it was hard to find that balance.

To be honest, it's hard to recall a specific incident of 'power' as the question defines it. In fact, I would say I can't name any time where I have felt that I had power, or was powerful in a certain situation.

Someone asked me for my opinion on their love life. It was in a restaurant, and there were 4 friends. I remember feeling powerful, like I had the ability to influence this person's life, by giving an honest assessment and suggesting next steps. At the same time, I felt flattered because this person trusted me enough to ask for my opinion. I enjoyed these feelings.

It was a time at work in which a customer complained about their food and I had to make the decision about how I would handle the situation. I was nervous and scared that the decision I would make would not be the decision that my manager would make. He was not there at the moment and I was the one had to handle the situation.

There was this one particular incident back in sixth grade where I decided to control a group project dedicated to finding a solution to an agricultural problem. I remembered I was frustrated with my group mates, thinking that they weren't smart enough to complete the project with an A. I  felt superior to them academically, and hence I took on and completed the project myself.

Last summer, I attended the audition of my high school's music club. I was asked to become one of the people who will decide the score of the candidates. I enjoyed their performance and tried to give their objective scores because this will effect the result of their audition. I felt very interesting because I can not only enjoy the show but also I can have an cherish experience of evaluate other people.

When I was in a position of power, I was captain of my high school's lacrosse team. In this position, I conducted practices, with the consent of the coach, to my own discretion in preparation for the next game. Though the thought of having the responsibility to lead the team was intimidating, I overcame my nerves and lead the team in a manner that I felt fit best. I felt that my duty was to encourage my teammates, as well as to establish discipline when the coach was talking. I usually was picked to go first in drills or used as the example; since I had more experience than most other players on the team and because I was captain for two years, I was confident and did not fear the attention. As captain, another duty was to be the "middle-man" between the coach and the players; so I was, essentially, representing the players and the coach and reporting to one about the other. One incident in particular was when I was asked by my coach to represent the lacrosse team at a school board meeting. I had the power to say anything that would affect outsiders' thoughts on the team's performance. I initially felt a lot of pressure, but when I went up to the podium, I was calm.

I felt like I was in a position of power back in high school when I was a president of my LEO club. I asked other board members to do things for the events and community services. Although I was in a powerful position, I tried my best to be polite and not hurt anybody's feeling. I was always cautious of what I was saying to other people. I also kept my mind open and was ready to listen to other people.

When I was in a position of power, I felt a sudden urge to prove myself worthy of the situation. I wanted to dominate. Usually, I feel in power and in control when i tutor. I feel like I am in control and with the greatest knowledge.

When I was in high school I was the brass captain in my marching band, which means I ran practices that had to do with all the brass players and also ran my own sections practice. I worked really hard at being the best because I constantly needed to prove that I was. I'm a trombone player and the majority of trombone players are boys, so I got a lot of disrespect. I've had people come up to me and say all girl trombone players sound the same and they all suck. I never felt sad or hurt that I had to work harder than boy trombone players to get recognized as a get player. I loved going on stage and playing lead and taking all the solos because I was one of the only girls in my school district to have the most power in her section. I would have people come up to me after performances to say how shocked they were that I was that good. I loved proving to people that I was the best, and that I could out play any guy. I know I ended up being a mean brass captain because I had to be. People didn't just give me the respect I need even though I was the best player and I knew what I was doing. I also couldn't earn their respect because everyone thought the teacher just gave me the title because I was the only girl. I had to demand and take the respect I needed to get my job done. A lot of people hated me because I wouldn't let them goof around and I would punish people when they got out of line. Being liked didn't matter to me when our brass section was getting awards and being praised for being the best in the district. I cared about my title and having the power a lot, and I took it very seriously.

I was in charge of stage crew at my high school. It felt good to be able to tell people what to do. At the same time I felt nervous about having to direct everyone and since I am in charge of them their mistakes are mine mistakes.

The only time I can really think of being in a position of power would be when i'm baby sitting. Often times, the children I take care of want something, but I do not give them want they want unless they have been behaving and have not done anything to get them in trouble. I do not feel powerful, I just feel that by not giving into the kids it teaches them to be self-competent. Over all though, I often do not find myself in positions of power.

When I drive my car I feel as though I have a lot of power. I can control where i want to go, how fast I want to go... I feel free as if I can go anywhere I want. When people want to get in a car with me, I am always aware of whatever I say goes because I am the driver of the car. For example: I get to choose which radio station, how farwaway/close to the destination we park... I feel like I am in control because i am the one operating the vehicle

Last year, I created a soccer team in IM sport men's league. I was the captain. As a captain, I did have some power in my team, such as I can decided who could play the game and who were the subs, etc. At first, I feel very proud of being a captain, because every members in my team need to follow my decision. As time went by, I gradually find out that I need to take the responsibility of my team, and every decision that I made should be convincing and well considered.

When I babysat for a few children I was in a position of power. I could control when they got to watch TV and when they had to go to bed. I felt a little uncomfortable because I did not want to do anything that made them unhappy, but also had to do what was right and what their parents expressed they wanted.

My friend asked me to do a favor for them since I was going to the same place anyway. I had the power of either accepting or rejecting their favor, so I had the ability of whether or not that person got what they wanted. I was neutral about the situation since it did not require me to do much out of my original personal plan, so I did the favor.

Over the summer, I worked in a restaurant as a server. As customers entered,  I was in a position of power where I could seat them wherever I chose fit. Also, I could make recommendations on the menu, which may or may not influence their order. After their food was prepared, I was in a position to handle their dish however I saw fit. After they have had their meal, I was in a powerful position of handling their money in the form of cash or credit. Throughout the process, I felt I was in a position of power and respect, yet at the same time, in a position of great responsibility and trustworthiness.

I was helping my brother pick classes for college. He didn't know what to major in so I tried to guide him. I felt worried because I felt like he didnt't know what to do at all. I didn't want him to make the same mistakes that I had made when I first entered college.

I was in charge of a committee in my campus organization. I was in charge of planning events for that organization with my committee. I had to always hold weekly meetings to discuss what to plan and how we were going to execute them. It was stressful in the sense that I had to to find time to meet up with them and scheduling is hard with many college students. There was also pressure as we had to perform well as eyes of our organization were on us. However, there were positives working with a team and depending on each other.

When I was in ASB I had to interview people to see if they qualified to join this program the following year. I was in charge of the interviewing process with two other of my friends and I felt in charge and powerful. I remember thinking that my actions can determine whether they get in this program or not and that made me feel  both nervous and powerful.

The situation i could recall is this summer when i was an intern. I started 2 weeks earlier than other interns and i was able to answer the questions when they were asking me for help. There's one time all the interns have to work together and finished a project. I was the youngest but i held the most power in the group. I knew the better way to finish the task more than everybody. I was able to tell how to do the task step by step and what is the best way to success on the project. This experience made me feel like i have the ability to controlled other persons

I am a Lab leader for intermediate algebra at the ARC. I have to prepare and teach a class full of 27 freshmen students who did not place well in the math placement exam. Knowing this, I feel that these students are careless because this is the material you learn in middle school. If this is the way they place into a university, I feel that they should not be here. As their lab leader, I feel they hold me accountable for their failures. This bothered me at first because i felt the same way, but as I continued on for a few weeks, I realized it is not my responsibility for them to pass. I am just an aid there to ask for help. if they are not understanding the material that is not my fault.
I was elected as my senior class president. I felt proud, but overwhelmed. Having power is a lot harder than people think. It comes with privileges, but also lots of responsibility.

I work as a staff member in UCR Housing as a Resident Adviser. Part of my duties include confronting residents about policy violations. I do notice that they are more compliant when i have a male staff member backing me up or when a male staff member confronts them. To gain compliance i have to be more assertive.

I recall a time I was comforting my friend after a bad relationship with someone. He came to me seeking advice and I was in a position to evaluate his thoughts and feelings. He expressed feelings of isolation and guilt. He kept blaming himself for something that didn't work out and I was just sitting there with him.

An incident in which I was in position of power was when I was in high school and was president of a club. I was in charge of making sure that everything was going well and that the secretary as well as members where doing their jobs correctly.

During this past summer I worked for a local business in my hometown as an administrative assistant. I was in charge of finding my replacement for when I returned to school. My job came with a lot of responsibility so I needed to find a trustworthy and hardworking individual. I knew this person would also be a reflection of me as they continue on in my position. I had to evaluate each applicant and consider the options knowing that this full time job that had a relatively high pay was coveted by each of them.

As a tutor for elementary aged children I am in a position of power the entire time i am with them. I feel close to the kids, because I am in a position where with my involvement it will either harm or help them, I like have the responsibility and always hope that I am doing the right thing.

I was in charge of the house for a weekend while my parents went out. I had complete control over my siblings, they had to do everything I said and follow my rules. I felt really powerful because everything was going my way.

last week, my ex boyfriend wanted me to come over to hang out with him. he called me late at night begging for me to come over so we could talk. he called about 10 times, left 3 voicemails, and sent 6 text messages. at this point in time, i was in the position of power to make the decision of whether or not i wanted to see him to talk. although i do miss him, i also knew it was not a good idea. being in the position of power, i answered the first two calls, but after that i declined the calls and ignored the text messages. in the end, i just went to bed and ignored the situation.

I was the Vice President of a club at school and we were looking to two spots for our club officers. In order to assess the member who wanted to become officers I had to make an application form which each individual had to fill out. On the form I asked questions which allowed me to see and evaluate the applicants strengths and weaknesses and how much effort and time they were willing to put into the club and its activities. Being in charge of this job made me feel responsible and a little pressured in order to find the right people for the positions. I wanted to give everyone a fair chance but I also needed to think about the club and who would help better it. In the end I found the right people for the positions and everything turned out well.

I work as a social worker for a non-profit organization. I conduct case studies on homeless youth to identify their delinquency factors. I am often responsible for finding resources for my clients and their families. Depending on my relationship with my clients, I can decide who I feel deserves or needs which resources. I also oversee four other case managers who report directly to me. This position is challenging because I have to be sensitive to the type of emotionally draining work we do, while maintaining some authority. I find it hard to balance being a respected leader while being friendly and understanding. There are often times where I hesitate to criticize an employee's performance because I understand that the work we do is very difficult and exhausting. I want to be supportive of them, while ensuring they are being efficient to benefit the company.

I was an academic tutor in my senior year of high school. There were many times where my teacher would allow me to grade the work of the students in the class, and would just give me a brief explanation of what to look for. It was up to me to decide whether or not they put effort into this or not, so I decided their grade. It was odd for me, because I didn't want to make anyone upset with their grade but I also didn't want them to be graded too easily. It was harder for me not to have favorites in the class so I'd always try to avoid looking at the names on the assignments. I didn't want to have biased opinions.

I was a bus coordinator for the UC Davis Pre-Health conference and I was told not to let people off the bus at a particular stop. One person wanted to go and use an outside restroom, but I didn't let them since there was a bathroom on the bus (it wasn't the cleanest). I felt bad, but I was sticking to the order of not letting people off the bus.
When I want something from my sister I am in power of her.

In high school I was a mentor for the incoming freshmen. Most of the time they needed to fill out information for the school year so they needed me to help them.
