I was babysitting my little cousin while his parents aren't home. For the most part, we spent our time watching TV and playing with toys. I like spending time with him because I think little kids are funny and cute, but there are times when he asks too many question that has no answer to them.
I would feel like there is a lot of pressure on me because I am responsible however, I would do my best to make sure the end result is a positive one.
Overwhelming

In my video editing class in high school I was the director. I had complete control over everyone in our group. I felt a little awkward giving orders to people that I did not know. I became use to it as the project went on, but i never let it go to my head. I just wanted to finish the project and try to be fair to everyone while doing it.

I have been in the position of power when I decided whether to come to UCR because of my mom's situation. She relies on me for almost everything, and that is why the decision was hard because it involved her feelings and her general needs of every day. Thus, I had power over many aspects of the decision. I decided to go with my gut feeling and the fact that this would make her happier by attending UCR.

I have taken care of an office before while my boss was gone to another country and the feeling of power is great. Actually taking charge felt amazing because you were able to do what you wanted if it felt right of course. I did not boss anyone around because that just seemed wrong but I was always helping people in other ways with their paperwork because they had to rely on me.

I was head of the costume theater department at Hollywood High. Everyday, my crew and I spent at least two hours organizing the clothes by color and style.  Organizing clothes everyday was not fun, but it was a nice feeling begin able to be in charge.

One situation that comes to mind was back in high school when I was the only person out of my group of friends who had a car and a license, so they had to ask me when they can go places and where they can go, unless their parents were able to take them. I liked being able to decide everything and do what I wanted, but I was very reasonable and would take them places a lot, and I would always take them if the place was important to them.

I was in a position of power when I took care of my little sister and cousin while our parents were either working or away. It was a fun experience though at times it did get stressful. Reasoning with children is sometimes hard because they just want what they want and do not like to listen to other people in moments of stubborness.

A few years ago I had volunteered at an elementary school and I was in charge of a group of fellow volunteers. I had to direct them on what to do and where to go. Considering I didn't know what to do myself, and wasn't instructed on what it was that we were required to do it was rather stressful, but we got everything done that needed to be done. So it went decently well.

I was teaching a class of Ghanaian students about public health issues and preventative health methods. I was nervous because the translator had to translate everything I said. What if the kids didn't understand or what if the translator interpreted the wrong thing? I was happy that I could make a major impact on their daily health routine, but if the translation was wrong then I wasn't making an impact at all.

The situation I recall in which I was in a position of power was in high school's anime club. I was the treasury of that time. The reason why I think I was in power at that time is I believe I have the authority over the club's financial flow and provide accurate data for the club's operation. I felt that the club members depended on me and it made me become more reliable to them. By having power, I think it is a way for me to establish a closer relationship and friendship with my team.

I often tutor people. In such events, I lead discussions relevant to the lecture material. I tend to use different methods of teaching to make sure the student is fully aware of the information and is capable of applying it. It makes me feel as though I have some value beyond my existence. I appreciate it when people look up to me, in fact, I thrive off those experiences. I am a very insecure person, so instances in which I have control reassure me of my competence and intelligence.

In event in which I was in a position of power was when I had to evaluate the essays of my peers in High school. I was able to correct, add side marks, or completely tell the students to change their essay. As I graded them I did feel as if I had power over the students as I graded. It comes to say that when one is in a position of higher power, even if its only slightly, one still feels like they have much power over the rest- in my case other students.

It was a group project and I was the leader of the project. I need to assigned tasks for each group members in order to finish the project. Being the leader did not feel good because you were responsible to most the situations in the project. However, when the project was finished and came out well, I did feel satisfied.

Growing up I have always been the child to cry to get what I wanted from my parents. As I have gotten older, I have come to the conclusion that I do not have that same power I once did and it is harder to adapt to not getting my way as often as I used to. It is frustrating at times but over time I let it go.
I used to organize a graduation party when I graduated for the high school. At that time, my all classmates followed my steps. Then, they said they were enjoy it.

The Beyonce and Jay Z concert was coming to a city near me so I purchased 2 tickets. The first person i knew would love to go was my little sister Isaura. I told her that if she finished her semester with at least all B grades she would be able to go so she worked harder and came home with As and Bs versus the Ds Cs and Fs she had come with from the previous semester. I felt that i had power over her school performance.

A time I was in a position of power was when I was able to assist my manager considering new hires for our store. I was on the varsity basketball team for four years during high school and my coached made me co-captain. Every single game I had to lead the team into warm ups, huddles, and the pre game pep talk. no incident comes to mind

I was Color Guard Captain when I was in high school and during our Finals championships performance, I motivated my peers and fellow marching band friends about making the best out of our last performance of the show. For us seniors, it was very nostalgic at the same time because we are at our final fall season of marching band which we have been a part of since we were in eight grade participating in the spring training session. It was inspiring and emotional because we watched each other grow individually as well as together.

At my job, I've experienced the position of a shift leader. At times, when my manager is present, I hold the power of the floor concerning jobs of other employees, tasks, and priorities of the store. I felt more responsible and have built leadership qualities. I liked being in charge, but I liked to divide the power. I believe someone with too much power can backfire as the person may abuse that power. Distributing the power among others creates a more fair and efficient way of function.

When my cousin was looking for a job, I had connections so I introduced her to a job she would be most likely be interested in.  I knew the manager and so I talked to the manager in helping my cousin get the interview while adding some good words in for her.  After that it was announced that she got the job, I was happy for her, because if I was not looking for one and someone I know was, I would help them anyway.

When I was a teacher's assistant for my math teacher, I felt that I was in a position of power because I was in charge of inputting the scores of the students into the grade book and to score certain assignments. I was babysitting my younger cousin, who was four at the time. He kept wanting to play with all my stuffed animals but he was making a mess of my room so I told him to stop and put them away. He did as I had told him. I wouldn't say that I felt an extreme amount of power over him, to be honest it didn't really cross my mind at the time. I was just pleased that I could find something else for him to do that kept him happy and essentially kept me happy because my room was no longer a mess.

Whenever I needed something from my younger brother whether it was a favor or money I felt like I could get what I wanted from him because I was older and bigger than him therefore I felt more power. I knew that it was wrong to sometimes threaten him, but hey I had the power and I usually got what I wanted from him which felt a bit pleasing at most, but of course not through violence just words.

I do this almost everyday in my line of work. I work as a DSP (Direct Support Professional) for the mental disabled so I am constantly in a position of power. Being a position of power is normal to me, but is gratifying in a sense that I helping them to help themselves in hopes that they learn and develop proper social norms and basic safety skills.

I work in retail, thus I come across many frustrating customers that try to have it their way. I have the power to authorize or decline any merchandise returns. People often try to return items that have been worn or try to save as much money as possible. I get annoyed by them very easily. Although I understand their intentions are just to save money due to the economy, they are very arrogant of understanding rules.

I used to tutor at a learning center and there, I taught kids from ages 1-5. I recall myself in a position of power when I was chosen team captain of the soccer team years ago. In choir class senior year, I was soprano section leader. I had to evaluate and teach the other sopranos the music, giving them tips on how to hit high notes and how  to improve the sound. I regularly help out a lifeguarding class so I am usually the co-instructor of the class. I have to make sure that the students preform there skills perfectly to be certified as lifeguards. I always feel proud when one of my students finally learns a skill that they were having trouble in.

In a class we had to fill out a form about who participated in the group project and how much work they put in. There is always one person who depends on the rest of the group to do the work. I cant recall a specific incident in which I felt in power. I think anytime someone is emotionally involved with anything you say or do, you become in power.

Once at work, ( I work as a waitress)  I was asked by my manager to train a new worker. I work at an elementary school, so an instance at work could be choosing a child for any particular activity or to do a responsibility. The club that i am participating had a pool and bbq party yesterday. I was told to prepare food and supplies for the event. I was excited because i could get involved and in charge with the event. I feel like i got the power to hold the event.

I remember having to babysit some kids. I felt like i had power but i had to use it responsibly. I could not tell the kids to do whatever they wanted. the last time i was in a position of power was during a class last quarter. We had to evaluate our partners in a project and that evaluation would count for 1/3 of the project grade. I felt the need to put that people participated even if they did not do very much.

A time I was in a position of power was when i was one of the cross country captains in high school. I had a say in who i thought should run what race, and I could decide who needed more practice. I was in power when i controlled what candies my cousins would receive. It felt good to be able to control their fate in a way. I felt like i was superior to them. However I did feel guilty when not all of my cousins were satisfied with my choices.

I was at work and I was told to train a new employee. I felt superior knowing I knew so much and another person didn't. It was rewarding to know that a person is paying close attention to what I do and say.

In eleventh grade i was the leader of my history group project. At the end of the presentation I got to give each person a grade. The grade I gave counted as one fourth of their overall grade. I felt powerful but I wanted to give grades that would allow them to pass the class.

I was left in charge of my little brother for a few hours while my parents went out grocery shopping. I had told him earlier that week that I would take him to the park to play with his friends. I was a person of power when I had to be the mediator between my best friend and his girlfriend. They asked me who the right one was in a specific situation they had. I felt like there was no real right answer because both sides had valid points.

In high school, I was the group leader of a big science project. In high school, I was a member of the student government and I conducted interviews for other students that wanted to be apart of student government. I along, with my advisor, were deciding which students would get a spot or not.

A time when I had the ability to control a person's thoughts was when a friend gave me their full trust and told me all their inner thoughts. It made me feel powerful, yet, scary in so many ways because I had the ability to be right all the time. It didn't matter if I was wrong or right, he believed what I said, and attempted to live out my words. There was one time when my roommate's glasses lost a screw and she asked to help her find a way to fix it because she couldn't see clearly without them. I had the position of choosing where me and my friends were going to go eat. It was late at night, and I was hungry for something warm and spicy. I then decided we were going to Buffalo Wild Wings.

i used to work in administrative service of a local hospital, and had to go department to department to address patient complaints. i was very dissatisfied of the job because it was difficult dealing with every individuals' problems, and having to come up with a solution while worrying about the outcome of the situation (whether it complied to hospital rules and regulations). i felt stressed!

At work, I have once helped the manager evaluate how a new cashier was doing on her first days of work. My thoughts were to be honest about how she was doing her job, her weaknesses and strengths, and emphasizing the positive things about her work.

I was a judge in a performing arts  program.  I was in the position of power because I was the one who decided which person would play which role in a play. I was captain of my high school's drill team and would always run practices over with my team mates. I remember recruiting members during try outs and a few of my friends would try to join along. The decision was made primarily by me, my co-captain, and coach. However, it was hard because some of them didn't meet the standards that were set. So I had to play the bad guy and break it to them that they didn't pass the rounds. It hurt to know that they really wanted something and I had the power to give it to them, but I wanted to be a leader that was unbiased and uninfluenced by connections and other outside factors. I'd rather have a person obtain something through hard work and dedication rather than not really caring at all.

I was on a committee to elect the next president of a club. I had to read their essays about why they wanted to lead and club and evaluate each one to pick the best candidate. I felt pressured and unsure about my capabilities but in time became confident about my decision.

I remember that when I was working as a lifeguard, there were many patrons who wanted to take control over me because I was 18 while most of them were about 30 years old. I took control of the situations and let them know that I was in charge and I'm the person who's looking after them if an incident is to happened. The patrons seemed a bit angry but then they got over it as they saw how dedicated of a lifeguard I am. I remember feeling powerful and assertive as I let them know that age doesn't matter and I am their superior when they're in the pool.

I was in charge of training a new employee that would be taking my position within the company, after I had left. It was my job to train him on everything that I knew. I knew that this would not get him fired, but that this would definitely warn my manager to be aware of this progress.
I've never been in a position of power where I had control over something that someone wanted in an obvious way.  I can't think of anything.

As a past sales associate at Juicy, I helped and listened to customers to see what it is exactly that they wanted, related to clothing, or dresses for an event that they were looking for. I persuaded my friend Annie to let Jenny come over. I was in position because I was really close to Annie. Jenny isn't as close to us but we felt bad for her.

I play a goal keeper in soccer, and I think that is a position of power because you are the head of the team, you have to direct people where to go and you help control the game. So the way I controlled the ability of other people to get something they wanted is by guiding the team to winning.

An incident in which I was in a position of power was when I had to babysit. The kids could not do much without asking. I would decide when it was time for them to eat and when it was time for them to sleep. When dealing with kids there is a feeling of exhaustion along with power because they look up to you and listen to you most of the time.

The situation was when i was a cashier at CVS and a woman said that i had not given her the correct change. i could have given her the money, ten dollars, that she claimed to be owed, but i knew that i had given it to her already and was not going to give in to her demands. I refused to give her the money and then called my supervisor up to handle the situation. I knew right away that I had given the money to her and that she was trying to deceive me because from the moment she walked in, i knew that she would not be a quiet customer. She walked in and shouted a question to me, which annoyed me because it was rude to shout and because i was with another customer. She then took one of the sample spray bottles and sprayed it all over herself, and then carried it with her across the store. I distrusted how she looked and acted and was sure that she was going to steal it. When she lied to me about the money, i was almost willing to give in but i was not going to be blamed for being ten dollars short in my drawer. I was also about to give her a refund for the eggs she had bought but i knew that giving her a little of what she demanded would not please her entirely and could cause her to demand more. I was scared she would do something drastic and that is why i called up my supervisor. Also, i had only been working there for about a month or so and I did not want my inexperience to show, should she take advantage of that.

The time I was in a position of power was when I decided whether or not my sister could buy the item she wanted. At that time, I just thought that she didn't need it, nor was it any use in the future. I didn't want her to spend money on things that will not be used in the future, especially since we were financially struggling.

I'm not particularly interested in being in a position of power. However, I once was the "leader" of a group project. If anything, it was a stressful task having to make sure everyone did what they were supposed to.

Back in the day. I was leading a class of forty students. I found the experience to be rather stressful, and I felt a responsibility to profile the best instruction and guidance for the long term success of my students despite their resistance. I believed the resistance was due to the lack of instant gratification and in retrospect the majority of my students surpassed their peers in other classes, and became successful individuals.

For the last half of my senior year of highschool, I was an aide at a physical therapy clinic. I spent a lot of time helping elderly people with their necessary rehab. One day, one of my patients stopped breathing and I performed CPR and got his heart beating again.

Every day at work I feel in a position of power. Working in costumer service gives me the ability to contribute to the needs of the costumers. I have the authority to decide whether some transactions will be made or if the costumes will get his money back for a returned item.

In high school i partook in a debate against a male that believed that men are more powerful than women. However, i was able to win the argument do to the fact i was well prepared and i knew the topics he was going to bring up. Knowing his topics allowed me to have power because i was able to have counter examples. In this way i never gave him a chance to fully argue. I felt strong and accomplished because i was prepared. I showed him that women are just as powerful as men.

As a lifeguard, a swimmer wanted to jump of the diving board but the diving board isn't open during lap swimming hours. The swimmer started using vulgar language and was very disrespectful. With the authority of being a lifeguard, I told the swimmer that if he didn't listen to me, I would have to bring out my supervisor and ask him to leave. The swimmer obeyed my authority and got out of the pool. I felt good because I reinforced the right thing. I politely told him the consequences and he listened.

When I was the captain of the wrestling team, I had the power to lead the team during drills, stretches, warm ups, and more. Though I had the power to get the wrestling team to follow whatever I instructed, I did not see myself above anyone else. The leadership given to me was a way to guide and help improve the team in every aspect possible. My leadership was used to organize and keep the team focused. When the wrestlers would want a break, I'd tell them to continue wrestling. Though the teammates did not agree with my decision at the moment, they later realized that it was more beneficial in the long run. My team chose me as a captain for a reason, and although I had the leadership and responsibility, I did not consider myself to be greater than anyone else in the team.

It feels rather easy to manipulate people growing up, but later on in life, they get wiser. Nowadays, there are people who let you in on their lives or become vulnerable for a moment. I met some first year UCR students, who wanted to explore what Riverside had to offer. They couldn't decide what to do, so I just asserted we can go eat and have drinks back at the dorms. Once everyone was drunk, they became easy to evaluate on what kind of person each were or who will they become. I avoided drinking that night and was able to keep a clear mind. They say a drunk person's talk is a sober person's thoughts. I was able to see who I can trust for the remainder of the years at UCR, who would be the "party animal", the alcoholic, studious person, and the natural smart person who didn't have to try to earn good grades. I was able to evaluate these individuals so I can choose who want to stay friends with and have a good four years at UCR.

During a group project in my English class a few years ago, i took on the role of writing a script for the project.
