I enjoyed writing the script as i controlled the information that would be fed to me so that i wouldn't have to research it myself. Also, no one complained about the positions they would have to act in the script as it made the story line better.
Actually, I do not have the memory of i was in the a position of power.

My last incident in which I was in power was when I was recruiting possible members to become a part of my group organization. I felt very calm, however, I assume that the person I was questioning was a bit nervous.

Before I came to UCR at my job I was a trainer. I was in charge of training the workers and deciding if they would be promoted. I sometimes loved my job and sometimes I didn't. Having power can be good and bad because sometimes it can change a person. I didn't always like having power because of the amount of responsibility that came with it. I had to make sure I was always on top of my job because people were watching me, I also had to do things I didn't want to do because it was my job.

As a close friend of the president of one of the clubs I used to frequent, I was given the responsibility of evaluating the possible candidates for certain club officer positions. I arranged meetings with these candidates and interviewed them. Then I decided which ones were suited to become officers in the coming year and which ones had to go. As I was doing this, I felt respected.
I was in charge of two younger siblings while away. I felt like they had to listen to me and ask me if they were hungry or needed anything.

When I was in high school I played baseball, I was captain of the team and was able to control what we did for practice when ever our coach didn't show up I had the authority to decide whether we even practiced or not, I controlled how much we ran or worked out and when we would leave. being in control felt great, I felt respected.

While grading someone else's essay, I've been in a position of power where I could choose to grade leniently or I could choose to grade harshly. When I was given the essay I recognized the person who wrote it as someone who I didn't care too much for. I decided to grade it more strictly and less laxly, because they hadn't committed actions that made me happy. They talked to me about the grade that I had given them, but I wouldn't give them a higher grade because I felt it was what they had deserved.
I was in a position of power during work. I was able to control what students would do for me while at work. It felt good because I was able to give them the tasks that I did not want to do.

The first event that comes to mind took place during my senior year of high school. Mr. Beerman, his actual name, assigned a simple group project. I'm pretty sure I did the exact same project in elementary school. We were supposed to create a maze using quotes from the books we had read over the year. I had been a student of Beerman's previously, so it seemed artsy and straightforward, which we were used to at that point. I was gathered into a group and we made plans to complete the actual maze. Those plans fell through and we rescheduled due to cancellations from pretty much everyone. They had excuses, believable, so I changed the date and time. Then one group member flaked, the other ordered food and ate the entire night while the last member slept on my couch. I finished the project by myself the night before it was due. It looked like I finished it within the five minutes before it was due. I could have told Beerman they did not contribute, it would have been true and he would have believed me. But their grades hung in the balance, in Beerman's class it could have been the difference between an F and a D or a D and a C. I chose to allow them to have the points, to have the A that we probably didn't deserve. No reason, I guess.

Right now I am in a position of power on the volleyball team. I was appointed captain this year which is a big deal. I was really happy because I want to learn how to lead a team because I have never done that.

I honestly can't think of such a situation, sorry. I didn't want to just lie by making something up... I just really don't think I've ever been in a position of power like that, and If I have I can't recall.

During senior year of high school I was part of the people who chose the girls for the team for the following year. I got to evaluate the girls and pick if they were eligible to be a part of the team. I felt nervous because I knew some girls wouldn't make the cut even though they tried out and gave it their all. That was a bit sad, but at the same time I was excited and happy for the girls that would make it.

As a member of my high school's Associated Student Body I was head of the Spirit Committee- which planned, organized, and executed school pep rallies, spirit weeks, and other events. I was in charge of ensuring the gym was set up and decorated properly and that everyone was on task and doing their part to contribute. I felt very productive and full of purpose, which made me content. I also liked helping people when they had questions or weren't sure of directions, so I got to help a lot in that way as head of Spirit Committee.
In my anthropology class, I was the group moderator, and I evaluated each person based on merit and participation. I evaluated each person in an unbiased manner.

I was trying to ask a person to go get dinner at this place, and when i said "must" go with me the person was somewhat not happy because i was forcing them. This is when i try to controlled the ability of another person, because i know the fact that the person has nothing to do other than staying home and relax. When i ask others to do something, they usually feel like i am demanding them.

A situation in which I recall this happened was in high school when I won the position for ASB Secretary.I remember one of the members really wanted this position, but at the end it really depended on who gave a very well/informative speech to the student body. I felt bad at first, but then again I knew the hard work i put into my speech had payed off at the end.

When I was in junior high, I was a RA. The experience was fun because my job was walking around the dorm and told students to go to bed at night. If I heard them talking, I would warn them once. And if they were being loud again, I could give them a ticket. I loved my job because I interacted with different kinds of people during that time. I also tried to send a ticket to anyone buy calming the students that had trouble going to sleep. Even though my power was limited, I understood how difficult it was to avoid a fight.

My parents left for vacation and left me in charge of the house and my little siblings. I was looking after my siblings and was able to tell them what to do because if they did not do as I said I would have told my mom. At times we would fight and I would be mad with my siblings. I ended up not telling my parents everything because then we would all get in trouble.

As I was growing up, I was in a position of power over my brother. He needed to ask for permission to have friends over or to go to a friends house as well as eating candy. I did not mind being in power, at times, because I am older than my brother therefore, I am the authority figure at the time. However, I did not like being in power if my brother had a tantrum because I would have to explain his behavior to our parents and be responsible for some of his actions at times.

I had to grade someone's essay. I recognized the person who wrote the essay but didn't have any good feelings towards her. She ended up asking for a higher grade than what I had given her, but I decided to keep her grade the same way because I felt that I had given her a fair grade and was in no mood to help her.

An incident in which I was in a position of power was when I accompanied my grandmother to the urgent care along with my mother. My grandmother was consistently vomiting and claimed that she was experiencing chest pain. Between both my grandmother and my mom, I was the most fluent in English and therefore the only one able to communicate to the nurses about my grandmother's pain. The urgent care physicians informed us that they have an ambulance waiting to take my grandmother to the emergency room for fear that she was suffering a heart attack. My mom refused to believe that my grandma's condition was as terrible as the nurses described and suggested to my grandmother to simply go home and relax. At this point, it was my decision to tell the nurse whether my grandmother will take the ambulance or not. Because of my deep care for my grandma's health, I decided it was best to have my grandmother escorted to the hospital under close observation of the emergency medical technicians. As a result, my mom and I stayed with my grandmother at the hospital for over twelve hours but fortunately, was not diagnosed with anything serious. Had I not agreed to take my grandmother to the hospital, we would not have known that she was okay.

I am currently in the admissions class for the Honors Program at the University of Florida. I help score the essays that determine which students are accepted into the program and which are not. It is gratifying to be on the other side of the admissions process; only 6 months ago I was applying to the honors program myself. However, being in a position of power is more stressful when you can empathize with those who will ultimately get a rejection letter, especially when you are the one deciding that they do not make the cut. I enjoy being in the admissions class and scoring essays, I only hope the students who are not accepted learn from the failure rather than resenting the organization overall.

I was the captain of my club soccer team. I dictated our strategies and called out the plays during the game or at half time. The position made me feel empowered. I felt like i could say anything and my team would follow without a second thought.The position I held as the captain gave me more confidence. I felt like I could do anything.  I would like to be in such a position again as president of club or organization.
I was the captain of a hockey team in which the coach frequently asked me about others' playing time. I never told the coach to bench someone out of spite, only to help the team.

Recently, I had a friend open up to me about her problems with her family and her friends. After listening to her I felt like I knew her better. I tried to be very objective when listening to her but at the same time offered my sympathy when needed.

I was President of the Homecoming Committee my Senior year. I really liked the feeling of being in control of the other volunteers, because it meant that I could accomplish exactly what I wanted to for the project. I felt very much so in control.

I was chief of properties in my high school drama department. I had to divide tasks among multiple underclassmen to find, create and distribute different objects for the productions. I felt kind of stressed because it was my responsibility to make sure that everyone did what they needed when they needed and to fix any mistakes they made. It was also fun to be in a position of power and decide what aspects of the job I wanted to do and what I wanted to delegate.

I was in a position of power during my group project last year in Warrington Welcome, which is an introduction business school class. I was in charge of a project where we had to create a fictitious business and create a business model for the company we created. I was in charge of delegating task and making sure that the project was correctly and efficiently. It was a decent amount of pressure but being in previous leadership positions helped me keep a level head and get the job done.
I guess when people are trying to get your vote to become president of an organization. You feel needed and important because they want something from you.
i was a gymnastic counselor and i enjoyed evaluating my students on their performance and help train them in there weaknesses to improve them for competition

When babysitting my younger siblings I am in charge of whether or not they receive rewards such as desert or television. When I am in charge they often try to take advantage of the fact that I am not the parent and will sometimes choose to ignore my authority; however, when they realize that I am in control of their rewards they will usually try to behave. It is sometimes frustrating to not be respected as an authority figure except when you are in control of what they want.

An incident when I was in power was when I was the Drum Major of my high school marching band. I was the man in charge in terms of making sure everyone was where they needed to be as well as controlling how the music was being played. It was stressful and demanding position because you are dealt with an extensive amount of responsibility but very rewarding in the end.

As president of my high school's italian honor society, I was able to appoint others to specific positions and tasks, hear out their interviews and ask directed questions, and control all operations of the club. It felt good to be in a position of power in order to get things done efficiently

I was in charge of a small group of people that was set to revamp our high school whole library (Collecting books, making orders, working with the principal, laying out floor plans, etc.). The result was that the experience was partially consuming, but mostly rewarding and if its worth mentioning, this wasn't the first time I was ever in charge of something, but the most recent one. It felt great to be able to lead people and teach them what to do, for example, I would teach my assistants where to move boxes and how to scan books and later they would work alongside me. I must admit sometime I got lazy and worked less  than most of my assistants and it is frustrating to think that I could've done more, but in my defense, I was meant only to organize and teach people what to do. I remember a particular moment when we lost a huge collection of books (The dual enrollment books where placed in a different school since they are really valuable) for Dual Enrollment and my principal was fuming mad at the assistant who lost the collection. I took the blame and made sure that the assistant was let go of the charges. I had to pay for some of the books, but managed to find most of them afterwards with the help of my assistants at the time. I think that when it came to leading people it wasn't much of a problem or very complicated, it was more like being a teacher if anything.
Being captain of my tennis team. I was able to make decision as to who would have the eligibility to play in a match and who would not
I don't think of having power, I simply believe in the delegation of tasks. Power can sometimes have a negative connotation.

I was a counselor and had an assistant and he would basically have to do whatever i told him to. I felt powerful and thought that it was a great feeling. Honestly  I couldnt force him to really do much other than menial tasks like grab things for me or take attendance but it was still a great feeling.

When I used to work at Subway, one time this man came in angrily demanding for a new sub because it got "too soggy in the bag."  I could've decided not to make a new one for him because he had already payed for it, he was being very rude, and it wasn't my fault that happened, but I decided the customer should get what he wants.  I was annoyed by the way the man acted.  If he had just asked nicely I wouldn't have been so unwilling to make him a new sub.

When I was captain of cheerleading, I had the power to decide what our routines would consist of, what we would wear on game days, and where we would attend team dinners.  This experience made me feel very stressed.

When I volunteered at the Miami Children's Hospital, I worked in the lab and handled patient samples. Having the opportunity to use the centrifuge was very exciting. I would scan the samples to log them, then I would organize them according to their color. Most of the blood samples had to go in the centrifuge and I felt very powerful when I got to use it because I was in control of something new and exciting. I was controlling where each sample would go for further analysis and when they would be distributed. I saw many different types of patient samples that looked strange and interesting. Just being in control while working their was a little nerve wracking because I knew that people's lives would change depending on how the samples were processed and analyzed.
I was babysitting and the kids wanted to have ice cream but werent behaving so they didnt get any. I have no feelings about this.

I was captain of my soccer team and was able to have a say in the positioning of the team (who played where, the amount of players in each position). I love being in control. I feel confident and powerful when I know that my say matters.

I was captain of my cheer leading team in high school, so I had power over those individuals. It's a struggle to establish yourself, as the "captain" after they have seen you for so long as another member of the team, or their "equal." I was determined to earn their respect, and I did. You just have to realize that sometimes you don't need to be their friend, but rather, someone who they can look up to, a leader.

I have been captain of my Hi Q team (trivia) so i could control who could join games or who had to leave.  To me it just felt like another task, something an adult assigned me to do and that I did just to comply with what I was told.

My senior year in high school I was Senior Coordinator for my health program and I was in charge of approving applications for an internship at the University of Miami Hospital. If people were rude to me, if I felt they weren't competent enough, or if I knew they would simply embarrass our school at the hospital, I declined their application. I didn't feel sorry for anyone.

It felt good to know that other people looked up to me and sought answers. They looked at me as if I had some greater power over them. They asked me questions and wanted my approval. It's nice to be in a position of authority.

The other day I had to go pick someone up to go shopping because they didn't have a car. If I hadn't had a car, I don't know how we would have gone shopping. I was frustrated by the fact that he didn't have a car, but I was also pleased and grateful that I did. It reminded me fondly of my freshmen year of college when I drove almost all my friends around because I was one of the only ones with a car.

I was in charge of a fashion team. I decided what each model was wearing, what fabric I needed to make the designs, and the coordination of the fashion team. It was stressful, exciting, and fun to be in charge.

Being the President of Senior Class Council, it felt at times great to be in power instead of doing the labor work but yet again very stressful because people were waiting for your every command. There was also high expectations to whether you would get the task done right.

Student org chair interview. I felt like I was determining there fate because I was one of the people that would decide whether or not they would get the position that they applied for. I felt powerful and above them.

In a leadership retreat, instruction on how to build a dinosaur was given. We were supposed to assemble it and then explain the instructions quickly to a group outside of the room which had never seen the dinosaur. When the group came in, there was some confused looks towards what they were going to do, and a lot of noise. I stood up in a chair and loudly told the groups to separate in two teams, one would do the lower body and the other would do the upper body of the dinosaur. I felt accomplished because the result was that they assembled the dinosaur faster than we did and without looking at instructions or pictures.

I was a camp counselor this past summer. I was in charge of ten 6-9 year olds for three months. I basically had to be their mother for that time. I had to be in control and tell them to clean up and be nice to each other. I didn't really enjoy constantly having to tell them what to do.

I was the student body treasurer of my high school and had the responsibility of interviewing those students who wanted to hold their class treasurer position. I was required to read their applications and interview those who I thought were the best fit for the job. I felt very in control of the situation and did my best not to abuse the power by making sure my decision was unbiased.

I was president of the Nation Honor Society at my high school. When the time came to introduce new members, i knew which ones were chosen and which ones became ineligible. Also, when officer positions became open, i had to vote for the ones i wanted to be in office. I felt really responsible for the whole situation and all of the outcomes. It was hard to take such a big responsibility on especially if i knew the people that were becoming members. I felt sort of bad most of the time because i didnt know if i made the right decisions.
I was Editor in Chief of my high school newspaper. I felt stressed and anxious, but slightly relieved that I got to control the process.

The last time I was in power where it affected the ability and wants of a person was last year. I was President of a club, and my director asked me to choose someone to speak to a group of students. Instead of choosing my Vice President, I instead chose another person whom my director and myself has given the title of Ambassador. U made this decision, because the Ambassador was outgoing and relatable, while my Vice President was somewhat dull. The VP only ran for the position because she thought that herself and our friend and the time would be President and Vice President together. I did not make the decision to not invite her, but to choose who qualified the most and who would bring more member to the club. I felt okay with this decision, and I wouldn't change it. I made a decision that bettered the club, not the decision that better suited the VP.

I was captain of the color guard team at my high school. Every practice the instructor would tell me what we had to get done. I felt like it was very difficult to gain the respect of other students who knew me before I was captain while the other students who I met as captain respected me and followed instructions. It was very frustrating getting lectures when the team did not finish everything on time but I felt like I had no control over them.
This past summer I worked at the YMCA summer camp as a camp counselor. I had a position of power over the campers, and I felt like I was respected as an adult.

In high school I was vice president of the senior class. I had the power to help make decisions regarding what we spent our money on, t-shirt designs, class song, flower, etc. Having this type of power was some what stressful because if something went wrong I was going to take a big part of the blame. I always had to think what was going to be best for everyone not just myself.

I was in charge of putting together a dodge ball tournament and the person under me was a boy.  He thought because it was a boy's sport that he could run it more efficiently than me.  I ran it the first year and it went off without a hitch he ran it the second year and everything was a disaster and I had to fix everything while he got all the credit.  I feel as if girls can do anything boys can do, sometimes even better.  He felt it was his right to run this male based event but when he was actually in charged failed and then relied on me to do everything, while taking the credit.

In high school I was founder and editor in chief of the online newspaper. This position gave me a lot of power because I was in control of the assignments the students had to complete, the curriculum of the class, their grades, etc. I don't really remember feeling a particular way for being in power, I just remember feeling like I wanted to bring the staff together to provide other students with credible and timely information. In the beginning of the school year it was a little difficult for the other students to take me seriously because I was a similar age as they were, but once they realized that I wasn't in my position for power, but rather was in it to bring everyone together to provide for others, they began respecting me.

In the summer I had a job as a valet. There was a small group of us an we took turns being in charge of the keys and the incoming cars. when it was my turn there was a rush of cars so i had to tell everyone which car to get in and tag them so we could handle it all. it was very interesting, I was able to stay calm even when everyone was parking cars. I was happy with myself when we finished because everything went smoothly.

I was in a position of power in last weekend when I was responsible for giving my friends a ride home. I had to take 4 of them back to Orlando and so 2 of them were being very nice to me because they knew that at any second I could tell them that they could not ride back with me. I felt as though it was only right that I gave them a ride back home because I would want them to do the same for me. They said they were extremely thankful that i gave it to them and so they gave me gas money because they would have spent it riding the bus anyway.

As the vice president of a county-wide organization two years ago, I felt pressure and responsibility to get many plans and events into action. It was a good feeling to complete tasks but the pressure from others within the organization was substantial.

Being a coach of a high school cross country team that I attended. I would organize practice, meetings, races etc. The athletes felt very confident with me as there coach and knew that I knew what I was doing and they trusted me. I felt our team relationship as a whole was very good and we had great team commrodary which in turn ended up with a state championship in Track.
Coaching a pop warner team of children between the ages of 12 and 15 I frequently experienced being in a position of power. I felt the same amount of responsibility for every success and failure.

I was a drum major in high school. I had to evaluate section leaders performance. I didn't want to give anyone a bad report even if they did something wrong, but it was necessary in order for them to get better.

I worked for three summers as a camp counselor. One day, my five year old camper demanded extra snack and threatened to call her mother if I didn't comply. Since I was the one in charge, I took away her phone and denied her request. I also made her have a time-out for being so rude. I enjoyed that I was able to tell someone else what to do and stop bad behavior. Being in a position of power makes me feel more confident.

When I was younger, I was the captain on my cheer leading team and I was able to choose different events that I wanted to participate in and had the opportunity to choose 5 people I wanted to work with. Nobody else couldn't choose and I was the only person with that opportunity.

I was the captain of a Relay for Life team for two years in my hometown. I had to organize fundraisers and events that would allow our team to participate in the Relay for Life event that is held once a year. I loved being a team captain because I felt much closer to the event and I liked feeling that I was in control of what was going on with my team, and I knew that I could make sure that we got everything done that needed to get done. If people wanted to be a part of the team and get the community service hours that they wanted, they had to participate in a way that I felt was honorable by the American Cancer Society and in a way that made our team look good.

In high school, I stepped up to run French club because no one else would do it and meetings and events were not be run properly. I planned meetings, times, activities, projects, etc. I felt relieved because it felt like me and everyone else actually enjoyed the club and we were finally doing exciting things. I was also stressed because if something didn't go right, people would blame me and people often came to me with their problems.

When working on a group project for physics, I took the lead and directed everyone to get it done. It was stressful and annoying; the group members would not focus and kept messing around while I was trying to work.

I used to be a Sunday school teacher and I was in charge of a class of 5th graders. I felt important because I was the one making all of the decisions and I was instilling the information in them. It made me feel good that if they had a question or needed something they came to me about, and I was the one with the final say and approval.

A few weeks ago I was selling my UF football ticket and was discussing my price with the buyer. The buyer realized I would not change my price and decided to pay me the price I was asking for the ticket. In this situation I had control over the buyers ability to get something they wanted. Being in control of the situation allowed me to sell the ticket for the price I wanted, because I had something the buyer wanted. Being in control allows me to be more comfortable and confident.

I was captain of my high school's softball team my senior year. I instructed them during practices and games. I felt good that people were listening to me and following my instructions because it made me feel like I had gained their respect. Although I enjoyed the power that I had over my team, I was never power hungry and never treated anyone with disrespect.

anagrams1: try, pry, pay, pat, ray, tap, at
anagrams3: one, nice, ice, on, no, in, once
highpower: I was team captain of my high school's volleyball team. I had a lot of input on who got to play in the games and how the practice was ran. I always tried to make sure everyone could play, but still made sure the team was able to win as many games as possible. It was stressful at times because not everyone was always satisfied and they would always complain to me.

In high school I was Co band captain and Section Leader. I ran my section and I taught them how to be good musicians, I also would press the fact that school came first and without school they wouldn't be in the band. One of my freshman had received a couple of F's on his report card and as the section leader that made me look like a terrible leader. I sat down and talked to him to figure out why his report was terrible. He was a class clown and therefore I punished him and he couldn't participate in any band events.  It was sad for me to but I had to teach him a lesson and me doing that he improved his grades. I used my power for good, because he improved on his school work.

When i was back in high school i was a captain on my football and track team so i could get freshman and sophomores to do what i want because they have to listen to me. I felt like i was the king and they were my servants i didn't have to do anything i didn't want to do. They thought it was mean but everyone have to go through it in high school unless you become a captain your freshman year like me.

As a members of the board it was my duty to assess potential new recruits by interviewing them. I would conduct the interviews in a casual setting so that the interviewee would feel at ease, however I made sure to be completely serious about the questions, taking notes and scoring their answers on a rubric. I made sure my language and conversation pertained to the matters at hand and I corrected the interviewee at the end of the interview, pointing out the flaws in his or her answers. I felt like a teacher and guide to the interviewees.

I am a treasurer for the BSW club here at Southern Miss. As treasurer I balance our club's finance and am in control of writing checks to other members if needed for certain projects or functions. I like having this control because I know i'm very fixated on ensuring that our club stays on budget while also helping.

Being put in a situation of power is a stressful one. Telling someone what to do or that they can or cannot have something they desire is stressful. Evaluating individuals based on the way they are presented is also difficult. Telling someone what to do is an easy task. Delegating someone to perform a certain task is simple and does not take any certain amount of fear or uncertainty.

I was once in charge of a classroom filled with 5th graders. I had to teach them their lesson for that day and make sure they were behaving as if their teacher was in the room. I was only in one grade higher than so I felt afraid to teach them. I was thinking that they wouldn't respect me being that I wasn't much older than some of them.

One occasion that I had power in was the time I was placed in charge for a few hours while my manager ran to another store to deliver supplies. I had somewhat of authority and was able to get the employees to do what is asked of me. As being in charge, I was able to see how a person did each task. I could examine if the job was done properly and efficiently. I liked being in charge, but it was only temporary.

My friend needed a place to stay and at the time I did not have a lot of money for my bills.So because I had power over her, I made her pay most of the bills that I did not have money for or she would have to move out. For awhile I felt bad because I was using her but after I examined the situation I felt it was fair because she could not stay anywhere else for free.

One time back in high school i was in charge of the entire woodwind section in my high school marching band. Being the only senior that day that was responsible enough I had to take charge and keep all the underclassmen in my section under control and on task. I did not like the feeling of being in charge of them very much because I thought that if I slacked up at all that day the would go wild and lose focus.

An incident that I can think of in which I was in a position of power is when my husband let me choose what we were eating for dinner. My thoughts were that I wished that he would make the decision. I would give him an idea of what I wanted or didn't want and tell him to choose from there. In another words, I would give my power back over to him.

In high school I was in office of many organizations. For National Honor Society I was the president. At my school, we did our "Honor Roll Programs" on stage. I conducted the whole thing, I decided who would sit on stage and who wouldn't. I also determined who would make a speech or call out names during the program. I felt very honored to be the president, I was organized and was always ready. I hated being the determining factor of who sat on stage sometimes because I did not want my friends to get upset if I felt like their grades was not high enough for the honor.

I was in charge of a scavenger hunt and so I determined who would win first, second, or third place.  I also had the ability to decide if the photos taken by the teams would actually count for the vaguer questions and which photos only counted as a half of point.  I remember feeling sad that I couldn't participate since I was in charge and I also felt glad because I was tired and I wanted to take a nap.  When judging the photos I felt the need to be unbiased because I knew a lot of the people who participated in it.  I also remember thinking that some of the people were lazy and didn't even try to find things on the list and came back a whole hour early and only completed half of the list.

I once participated in sorority recruitment as a member of a chapter.  In that time I played a part in the sorority's skit. This position of 'power' felt nice at first, especially a month before recruitment, because I felt included and excited to contribute.  My anxiety grew worse as the date approached and I was eating and drinking less and less the more intense my feelings got.  This resulted in dehydration and ketoacidosis by the time the skit date arrived, and I was very sick.  Other members of the chapter tried everything they could to get me to do my part, so I carried out my role although not to the best of my ability.  I am terrible with power.

When I volunteer at the DuBard school, I feel as though I have "power" over my students.   They look up to me and always ask me questions.  I am always willing to help them.  Sometimes if the children are misbehaving, they don't always get what they want, and if the bad behavior persist, they will have to go stand in the corner.  The child always gets upset with me but I know that this is best for them.  They need to learn how to respect their teachers whenever they are asked to do something.

A time where I have been in control was when I was asked lead my track team in stretches and warm up to get prepared for out team race and it was a good feeling because I  knew that the coach seen that I was a leader and that my teammates would listen to me and it felt good to know that my teammates respected me and looked for me for what to do next.

I was over my mom's salon for about two days because she was out of town on a business trip. I had to run it exactly like she would. I had to be able to tell the girls what they should be doing, selling the products, and making sure mom was still making profit. This was nerve racking and it made me fearful because I felt like I could never do as good of a job as my mother could. She was always a "god-fearing" woman that no one really wanted to cross. I was just her "wimpy" son and I was scared how my mom's girls were going to perceive me as I began taking over as their new boss for a few days. I was also at least 6 or 7 years younger than all of them.

As president of my organization, I was in charge of distributing tasks and following up on those tasks provided to members. I enjoyed being in charge; however, it is a lot of responsibility holding everyone accountable for their actions.

I was in a situation when a costumer and the store had lost their phone and wanted me to rewind the tape to see what had happen. after looking at the tape someone had stolen her phone and I was able to catch him before he left the store. my thoughts about the situation was that I feel like no one should ever steal from anyone. People work hard for their money.

I was in a position of power when I had to babysit my friends 4 year old daughter, sister and brother. I had to keep them occupied by playing games with them, reading to them and also entertaining them. I also had to make sure that all of their needs were met, and also that they were safe and well looked after. This event was very nerve racking to me. To have the lives of 3 other humans in my hands made me feel a great deal of pressure. However, it was quite rewarding when I saw that I was doing so many things right and making sure that they were well taken care of.

When I worked at the boys and girls club I had the power over all of the kids that I had in my class. I had the power in which I had to tell them what to do and how to do it. I was a lot of fun because I was the one in control of the entire events that took place but I was also extremely worried and stressed because I did have all of the power and all of the kids looked up to me when I was in charge.

I used to work at a deli when I was a senior in high school, and my manager would sometimes leave me in charge. By me being young and cool with just about everyone who I worked with, they felt as though I did not really have a say so as to whether they should do their job just as well as they would if my manager was around. Several of my coworkers felt they did not have to follow any of the usual set rules, and that I would not tell because we were friends and close in age. They felt they could just half do the job, and it would not be an issue until I started telling them what rules were set for them. They did not think I was serious- some even laughed. I immediately called my manager and told her exactly who was not following the guidelines. She was amazed to see me call because she thought I could not handle myself, but she then fully gained my trust. One of my other coworkers who she had left in charge previously told her that the same group of workers did the same things to her. She knew exactly what she had planned for them when she returned. I lost a couple friends on my job after a couple of weeks of them suspended. This did not bother me, though. My manager trusted me, and I felt a sense of security at my job.
basketball games and practices
I feel that the particular was about a position to evaluate those individuals.

I was volunteering for a forensics debate competition about 2 years ago and had to judge their performance. They would stand there and recite the monologues that they had to memorize or the dialogues that they had to memorize. The feelings that I had towards it were nervousness because I did not know what forensics debate is because I am not from Mississippi. After a while of judging, I was able to better figure out what to do and how to evaluate their performances.

It was my senior year in high school and I was student body president. I had to conduct a program and be mistress of ceremony. I was very nervous about the whole situation because this was my first time being apart of it as the coordinator and not just a student. The rush that was running through my body was great, but actual doing it made it even better. I over came my fear and I spoke in front of individuals I did not know and brought them through a journey.

During my Eagle Scout project, I was the one who was completely in charge. At first, I felt a little nervous about telling people what to do, but I eventually was able to overcome the nervousness and do the job.

I am a leader in a nursery group for children. I work with my other co-workers to get thing done. I feel like I am taking over the nursery lessons and crafts but that is what I am supposed to do for my job. I sometimes feel that my other co-workers may judge me and view me as controlling. I think I am not controlling and will listen to their ideas and opinions but they never give me any feedback.

A friend owed me a favor for driving him from the bar because he was too intoxicated to leave. He said he would do me any favor that I wanted the next day. So the next day, I went out to the bar but I made him pick me up whenever I wanted. I controlled him and his schedule for the entire night.

In my class we were divided into groups and each group was assigned three papers written by classmates not in the group. We were asked to evaluate and critique these papers. I did not want to be harsh in my criticism, but I also wanted to provide adequate feedback, so that the author of the paper could improve. I was also somewhat eager to find a correction or suggestion that the other group members would agree with. The approval or disapproval of my suggestions by other group members probably made the criticism more reasonable and constructive. All in all, it was good to feel like you could help a classmate improve, even though criticising is not easy.

I take photographs for the yearbook and one of the instances that I can recall having a position of power was when I was trying to get everybody in line and in order for a group picture to be published. It isn't the most pleasant experience because not everyone has a positive attitude and wants to pay attention. The picture came out wonderful but I had to retake it a lot to make sure every face looked perfect.

In a culinary class I took in high school I was in charge of the group I worked with. I made the decisions of who did what that day and when it came down for our class competition, I had to make sure that everything was done right and everyone did what they were supposed to. Most of the thoughts that I had during this time was just making sure things were done properly. Although, when we had a similar competition later on in the year and I worked with a different group, my main concern was getting one of our group members to step up and do some work. I guess some of the feeling that I have during this time are a little bit of anxiety and just wanting to make my someone proud and feel like a winner.

When our manager leaves work I am left in charge and must instruct everyone of their duties and critique them on their side work and efforts.  It feels good to know you are in control, but even better to know that people respect you.

Over the summer I coached a 16u baseball team where it made the authority figure and made me in charge. What ever I said went and they respected all of my decisions and I respected them for that. It made me feel good being in control, but it also meant that everything fell on me too whether we won or lost. However though it was something that I loved being the guy that everyone dependent on for answers.

I was in a position where I had to critique my friend's performance of a dance in practice. I felt more serious in the situation because I wanted to make sure she did not look sloppy and that her movement was flowing correctly so that it would look good when she actually performed the dance. I had more negative thoughts about her dancing than positive because I was in a different position: friend vs critical onlooker.

In high school, I was elected prom queen. After the exciting dance my friends wanted to celebrate by eating ice cream. I expressed my opinion and told them the queen wanted to celebrate by getting frozen yogurt. We ended the successful night by eating frozen yogurt.

I was the captain of the soccer team in high school, and I pretty much had just as much power as the coach. I could call practices, punish the girls, and had influence on who made the team. I felt important, and like everyone looked up to me. I may have gotten a little arrogant.

I was in the position of power when I was teaching my Sunday school, and the only way they could get a snack was if they answered the question correctly. I called out a question from the day's lesson, and they had to raise their hand to get called on. The person who was first got to answer first. Then each person's name was called until everyone answered a question correctly and received a snack.
I have never actually been in a position of power.

I was working at my job and my manager had to handle some important business. I had to watch the floor and register and maintain the store. It was hectic and a lot, but i was able to get through the day without any problem. The store actually made the goal for the day.

In my hometown, I work at Hibbett Sports. I was promoted to team captain. Being team captain, at the end of each month I was responsible for evaluating the team players and rookies work ethics. I was a deciding factor in whether or not those sales associates remained employed by Hibbett Sports. In certain situations, I felt bad. There were times were my colleagues were having a bad day and it showed in their work. Of course, I was responsible for documenting it. One too many of those documented comments could result in someone losing their job position.

I was student body president of my high school and it was very demanding and stressful trying to please everyone and better the school.  I tried to get what the students wanted and I also had to make sure everyone was doing their job correctly to do that.

Earlier this year, I was asked for my input, as a leader in a religious organization, on how another leader was doing and was ultimately given the decision on whether I felt she should remain a leader or not.  I felt that she wasn't doing that well, but still had a heart for it, but ultimately I decided the best thing for us to do would be to demote her from a leader to an assistant leader at the end of the semester.  It saddened me to come to that conclusion, especially since we are all friends as well, but I had to think about the future of the ministry as well, and I don't feel as if she's following the same path we are.
My nephew wanted some candy at the store so I bought it for him, to see his face light up was wonderful. I enjoyed the ability to give him something that he wanted.

I was in a position of leadership recently at a retreat. In this retreat I was in charge of a small group of high-school aged kids. My job was to help inspire discussion within the group. I felt good as a leader but I was very nervous. I was more concerned about how I would get them to have a meaningful discussion on the topic than anything else. I was afraid I would not say knowledgeable or wise things. I was less afraid of them acting out or misbehaving. I guess I just felt that the simple answer would be to direct their conversation back to the topic at hand. If they did start messing around with each other and moving around I knew that I'd have to stop them. I knew that I couldn't let them goof off and I wasn't about to let them.
TO be the monitor of the class. When students are talking and laughing, I have the power to ask them to be quiet. At that time I feel that I have the power of the teacher and I feel good.

During the transition of summer to school last month the place at which I work was going through many changes. The majority of the people were leaving and numerous new, younger, people were being hired. I was one of the few who stayed and therefore held a greater power over the new employees. It was a very confidence-boosting experience as they all approached me with a great deal of respect. It felt really good to know that I had the ability to instruct other people and they would listen just based on the fact that they respected me and the amount I had already spent at our workplace.
I have never been in such situation.

I was a teacher in a private school in summer. I realised the power of my pen. I can pen down future of any student. For e.g  the marks I gave to one of my student allowed him to go to a University he dreamt of. I never let my power overcome my moral responsibility of evaluating students properly. I was forced by principal to give extra marks or credits to students without doing course actually but I was firm.I was a little stressed out and had many arguments.The school is new and disorganised. I did not change marks at any cost because I believe that a student should get only what He/she deserves

I feel like I am in a position of power whenever my diet is successful. I feel like I can control my body in terms of what it can eat. Stopping myself from eating junk foods like chips and ice cream is extremely hard since it tastes so damn good but when I do, I feel in control of my body.

I was the team captain of my basketball team and when the team was at risk of folding, I was the one who got to determine our fate. I felt I had a tremendous amount of power and that everyone looked up to me. My coach was constantly yelling at me to decide and my teammates were nervous for the outcome. I loved basketball and to this day, still do. It was an easy decision for me to make sure that our team stayed together. Tense feelings were felt amongst all but a sigh of relief was made when I had decided to keep the team together. I never knew that so many people would look up to me and count on me to make the best decision for the whole. Looking back , I am glad that we stuck together because basketball was, and is a passageway to many greater experiences and opportunities.

In summer 2013, China had a serious earthquake in Gansu Province. I was working in a SPY company as a waitress during summer holiday. I made some friends there, and some of them are from Gansu Province. I decided to organized a donation for them within the company. Therefore, I told the manager and the manager discussed with the boss. The boss agreed with me and gave me the power. There were 7 SPY companies in total, I wrote a letter in order to encourage people in the companies to participate this events. The letter is published on the company website and company newspaper. Almost everyone in the company was participate. In the end, those money was collected by managers in each company and gave to me. I divided them and sent them to our workers' homes. Actually, I did not feel much about this event. I think it was just the thing that I wanted to do at that time. I should take good advantage of the power that the boss gave me.

A situation where I felt I was in a position of power was when I would grade student's report cards in swimming lessons. I felt as if I had their future in my hands and that I had the ability to shatter their confidence. I controlled the ability of the students to pass onto higher levels and also evaluated their performance, which I did not find to be an easy task. I do not like making people feel as if they are not good enough to succeed, therefore I often had a difficult time having to fail students who were physically not prepared to pass into higher class levels. This was a difficult thing to do and I did not enjoy holding such a large amount of power over these individuals.

A situation when I was in a position of power is usually around younger children, such as babysitting related events. It feels great because they tend to listen to you and look up to you. I like when people look up to me and ask for advice because it means that they trust me and like me as a person. I think that feeling power is a nice feeling, not when you are doing something negative, but when you do something positive that makes you feel better about what you did. I enjoy hanging out with younger peers because they look up to me, as they think I am more mature and knowledgeable on many more subjects, and it feels good to be able to provide that.
normal

I was amazed that I could be at such a position but at the same time, I felt the need to create better result than other people who were in similar position as I was. I felt the right to drive the people who were under my influence into working harder but at the same time felt the need to make them feel like they were having fun.

I do not particularly enjoy having to evaluate others that I know. I have difficulty being critical of those I know, making my evaluations overly easy of them. I don't critique as thoroughly as I might for some anonymous person.
Uncomfortable

I used to  be an administrator of an online BBS group, and I was able to cancel or delete the replies or new posts of those who joined the discussion. Sometimes I was strict with those who did not respect others and might delete their online replies. However, I did feel somewhat uncomfortable about that, since they might not be happy with that and it seemed that I was somehow mean to others. I did make some wrong judgements when evaluating their thoughts or words. When that happened, I felt guilty, and sometimes did not want to be an administrator any more.

My friend wanted me to go with him to buy something, but I didn't care if I went with him or not. I would get him to try to convince me to go with him by paying for my transportation or buying me a drink, or anything that would benefit me. I felt like I had control over my friend at that time because I was able to easily convince him to go out of his way to do something for me because he really wanted something from me.

I was the director of the Information Dept. of Student Union in my high school. Apart from the routine jobs, I led my team to hold photography exhibition. Even though I was leader, I tried to listen to their opinions even assigned the work according to their abilities and interest. Actually, I don't like being too dominate especially they were peer.

About a week ago a friend of mine came to me for some advice on how to behave with her parents after having a huge fight with them over something trivial. She was very frustrated about her parents never considering as a priority and always being forgetful when it comes to her. She acknowledged the fact that her parents don't care much about her and more about her brother, however she got so angry this time because her father forgot to do something which lead to problems regarding her university. Given that were very close and I have always been honest with her, I told her that maybe her parents keep postponing deeds regarding her university deliberately. At first she got extremely defensive and starting lying (something she uses as a defense mechanism often) about something unrelated to what we were talking about just to change conversation. Then I told her that she should talk to them in a calm manner about their absent mindedness towards her and gradually tell them what bothers her, unlike her usual aggressive approach. A week later, she tells me that they have been more attentive towards her needs and show little acts of love more often, like bring her food, etc.

Supervising a specific area of the store that I work in.  I was in charge of making decisions regarding discounts on defective items, and delegating tasks to other team members.  Although I really enjoyed having that role given to me, I wanted to ensure that I was assertive but not coming off as being "bossy" towards the other team members.
I was the head of my high school orchestra and was responsible for arranging practices and encouraging those who are lack of skills to enhance their performances.

my friend is not very good at writing. when it was time for writing university applications and essays, she was extremely confused. she was afraid that she wouldn't get accepted to any universities if she couldn't write a well-written essay for university. I suggested that I could perhaps write the essay for her. She was so impressed with the results that she came back with four of her friends. they all wanted me to write some sort of essay for them. I felt in power because I've only learned to write in English for the past 5 years, but those who asked me to write for them were mostly native English speakers. I felt superior to them because I knew I had probably acquired more writing skills in the past 5 years than they had in their entire lives. or maybe they were just lazy. either way, they offered me money. and a lot of money too, for a high school student.
i will control the a fatty person to lose their fit. To do exercise every day,and let her think it is very easy without any effort. It will make me fell happy .
One of my friends was struggling with her homework and needed my notes. So I gave them to her considering they will help her.

I have organized a presentation about explaining one kind of dances to people. My group have five people and I feel it is very hard to make everything go through when I do this. For example, someone will complains his task is the most difficult and does not want to do it. Eventually, we gave a good presentation, I feel really relax when we done.
As an only child, I have power over my parents. Whatever I want or need, I will get if I ask my mom for it.

In my high school in Nigeria, I was made the dining hall prefect. This meant that I was in charge of making sure that people had enough to eat and that the food was made in a conducive and hygienic place. During my one year holding this position, I understood what it meant to be in charge and in control. Sometimes, I had to do things I didn't want to but I had to. In the end, it was a good experience.

An example of this is when I was in high school and apart of my student leadership committee. I was able to help pick and chose who would be apart of our group. I had to sit in on interviews, and ask questions which would determine if the person would be grantee membership to our club. I felt bad most of the time because I knew majority of the people applying and they was about a 100 people and we could only chose 30 so that was a hard job in choosing who would get chosen and who would not be. My thoughts on it is that we should be able to expand the program because even though we are the voice of the student body, a group of 30 people are not necessarily going to be able to get everyone's opinions across accurately. At the same time i understand because too many minds can lead to chaos.

I have organized an activity for helping the students who cannot continue their study just because of money. I asked my friends collected the used toy and pack it up to sell at my community. Before I did it, I feel very excited. However, I feel it is difficult to control people's behaviours when I really tried to start do it. For example, my friend's parents felt this activity influences her study and asked her do not continue do it. In the end, we still sell out those toys and make profits. I did not feel very happy as I imaged before.

I was a tennis coach over the summer for little kids where I had power over them, so I was able to order them to do certain drills, pick up the balls, and pay attention to the other coaches. A lot of times the other coaches and I would bribe the kids with candy, or threaten them with having to sit on the bench for a certain amount of times. It was nice being in power, but at times I felt as if we were ordering the kids around too much. It was also upsetting when the kids showed little or no respect towards me and the other coaches.

In high school, I helped start a dance team. During practices, my friend and I both watched other members perform the choreography to make sure that they were doing everything correctly. If they were doing something wrong, we critiqued their dancing in order to help them improve. The purpose of giving critique was to help the members improve their dancing.

When going through the process of who I was going to live with my second year, I was put in the position of providing my opinion of some of the people with whom I had gone to high school so that we could reduce the number of people in our group. It was a difficult thing for me to do, because even though I like them a lot as people and I would have been happy to live with all of them, I knew that we had to bring our numbers down and I also had to take into account whether or not they would get along with the group. I experienced a lot of conflict in my mind while doing so.

During high school I was captain of the fencing team. Every day during practice I, along with the other captains, ran drills and organized. There was one day in particular in which we had trouble managing a younger fencer. She was talking back and giving attitude, which caused me to be frustrated and angry. She was completely disrespecting the authority we were given and had no regard for her own position. It worried me because we did not want to let the other younger kids think they could get away with doing the same thing. Eventually another captain and I had to go speak with our coach to resolve the situation.

I am one of two captains of the women's club lacrosse team here at UVa and I am in charge of planning practices and determining line-ups for out games.  I have to think about what drills will benefit everyone the most as well as who will be the best players on the field together to bring about win in games.  I like having the influence on the team, but it stressful knowing that it is my responsibility and I have to deal with the opinions and feelings of 30 other girls.

I was president of my school's chapter of the National Honor Society, and one time we had an opportunity to visit an opening of a museum. I was asked to choose 5 people to join me, and I knew that many other people really wanted to go since it was going to be a very fancy and upscale event. When I first heard about the news I was excited but then I started to feel conflicted about how to choose who would come with me. So I decided that I would choose those who had put in the most effort into the work they were doing within the National Honor Society, and asked other members to rate them on a scale of 1-5. That made it easier to choose, it satisfied most people and I felt like I was being fair.

For my senior prom in high school, I was in charge of planning locations, dinner, transportation, and the after party. To ensure that we would have a great night, I assign jobs to other members in the group, such as contacting the limousine service and finding a good restaurant. On the one hand, I felt very stressed because we were running out of time and I did not have much experience at planning, but I also felt comfortable in assigning tasks as a leader. For this reason, I decided to pursue a leadership role by joining the First Year Council.

As the field hockey captain, I had the authority to run drills and time the girls' mile intervals. Through encouraging the girls and disciplining them at the same time, I gained lots of leadership skills as well as realizations that being too harsh or pushing the team to their challenge point was not the most beneficial approach. Balance and rest are vital for succeeding in a majority of high-intensity sports.

I was once the head coach of a youth basketball team. I did not feel like I was ever on a "power trip," though the autonomy to run my own practices and command the players was satisfying. I felt pressure and responsibility however, as I wanted to be liked by my players and their parents. Therefore, I would listen to the opinions of the players and parents and consider their ideas seriously before acting. In this regard I feel as though I was a democratic leader, but firm when I needed to be.

This past summer I helped lead a mission trip to West Virginia. We had 10 kids sign up for the trip, all between 10-13 years old. We were assigned to construct a roof for a porch attached to a trailer in the Appalachia area. Building a roof with a younger group was very challenging. My patience was definitely put to the test because the kids really couldn't participate much (they couldn't reach!) and got super rambunctious. It was my job to keep them safe in a dangerous place and I struggled to keep their attention and enforce the rules. It was frustrating.

I was working in the nursery at church on Sunday. Obviously, I had responsibility of the kids and therefore had to control the group in order to promote safety of all of the kids as well as maintain order.

Looking for housing for the next academic school year, my roommates and I were looking at our options. There are some criteria that I want the new place to meet, if they're not all met, I would strongly veto the place. Since my roommates want to live with me, they allow me to be choosy and even veto the places they they liked. I feel strongly about how I want the place for next year to be like. So I may come off very headstrong and irrational, but during the time I feel that what I want is as important as what my roommates want. So there are things I'm not willing to compromise.
I have younger brothers. Whenever I am responsible for them I am in a position of power. I have no distinct feelings or thoughts about these situations.
Never really been in a position of power.
There was pressure to choose the best situation. I had to weigh what I would lose or gain from each situation. I was nervous as I tried to minimize negative outcomes and decrease anger towards me.
I was at a flea market and I was able to bargain for a product by lowering by 50% off.

I have a lot of power when I enter the dining hall. I can eat anything I want due to my high metabolism. I can choose between a plethora of options. The hard part is determining what I want to eat the most. I am in complete control of this situation.

I was on the judicial council at my high school. I often had to determine classmates' punishments with my peers on the council. I had a great feeling of responsibility, and I often felt uncomfortable when a friend had to go to council. On one occasion, a guy in my grade had to be evaluated for beating up a student much younger than himself. His actions clearly reflected his immaturity, and I feared that he would dislike me after I had to confront him.

The one time I remember I was in a position of power is when I tutored an underclassman in high school on SAT. By being in the higher position of the tutor rather than the tutored, I controlled whatever my student's next plans and goals were in the future. By being in this position, I felt constant burden and pressure for him to do well in his exams, and if he did not get the problem correct, I would think about what I am doing wrong. Being in this position did not give me any feelings related to superiority or power, but rather I felt vulnerable and prone to mistakes.

I volunteer at a day care in Charlottesville and am often able to tell the children what to do and what not to do. Last week when they were fighting over the swings I was able to tell them to stop and that someone needs to get off of the swing and let another kid on. I enjoy knowing that they will listen to me however I wish I didn't have to tell them what to do very often. It's nice to be in a place of power in an atmosphere of such chaos.

We held auditions for the improv troupe I'm a member of this year and we were able to evaluate and judge the auditionees on their performances to decide whether or not to extend an invitation to join our group. This was my first time being on the evaluating side of improv auditions so I felt pretty powerful, thankful, and energized. During the second round of auditions the members of the troupe perform with the auditionees and felt so much more relaxed and confident doing it than I had when I auditioned because I knew my spot was secure. I also knew that no matter what I did in auditions, to a certain extent, there would be very few consequences. This put me at ease and made me much better at improv to be honest.

I was captain of the soccer team and I had to evaluate the performance of my teammates. During training I would give them feedback and try to encourage them to do better every time they came in touch with the ball. My main goal was to motivate them to be better, rather than pressuring them. I enjoy encouraging people to do their best work.

In my high school finance club I was made in charge of overseeing and evaluating the portfolios of some of the newer members to then give them feedback on how they performed. I felt powerful and in my mind I knew that what I would say would hold weight on how the new members would go on to think of me and the club. With this came a sort of pressure to be fair and not too harsh, but at the same time judgmental.

I was a tennis instructor over the summer. So, I was in charge of children. I helped them develop their skills and taught them new ones. This gave me power because if I taught them poorly they may not turn out to be that good of a tennis player. Yet, if I taught them well, they had the ability to succeed. I really enjoyed this job, and it was quite satisfying.

A position of power I was once in would be during high school when I was one of the coaches of the World Scholar's Cup club. The World Scholar's Cup is an academic competition, much like the international version of the American Decathlon in structure and content. I and my teammates have been participating for several years and as seniors we were called as veterans to coach the teams. It felt very good to be able to have been there and done that and to share my experiences. I liked the idea that I was able to use my abilities to influence others. Overall it was a good experience.
I was a captain of my high school soccer team, therefore I had limited power, but it wasn't anything serious in particular.

I was the Senior level Copy Editor of my school's yearbook and I was responsible for managing all the staff writers and ensuring that the content going into the book was correct, appropriate and exciting. Many times I would have to delegate different tasks or give constructive feedback, and even sometimes reprimand staffers who were not handing in work on time. When I had this position I felt good about myself and confident in my own abilities. I have never felt smarter. I think it was a very good activity for me to be involved in because it strengthened my interpersonal skills and self-confidence.

I was an instructor assistant at a wilderness school this summer. Together, the instructors and I planned activities for, guided, and generally looked out for our groups of kids (ages 7-8 and 11-14). Being kids, they did things that they were not allowed to do, so our response was taking time out of fun activities to address the issues. We laid out our logic and the consequences of bad behavior clearly, and most kids got it down pretty fast. Of course, there were always the troublemakers, which led to us developing some inventive tactics since the school operated on the principle of guidance rather than blunt forcing. It was a subtle kind of power, but ultimately, the adults called the shots.

I was teaching a karate class and one kid wanted to be first in line. I said he couldn't be because that spot was reserved for kids who were a higher belt than he was. I recall being annoyed with his persistence.

I tutored a primary school student when i was in high school. Once i could decide when to finish the tutoring based on how the pupil performed. I felt relax with the power because i had to care about nothing stressful, and thought he might be a little bit stressed.

It was ski team elections last year.  We were choosing who would be on the executive board for the team this year.  It was crowded, and it was fun to be around everyone, but it wasn't fun choosing.  All of the candidates were very well suited for the positions and I knew them fairly well.  Picking one over the other was not just a difficult decision, but also came with a little guilt feeling like you were betraying one of the candidates who was your friend.

Last year I was in Photojournalism at my high school. It was my first year in the class and one of my best friends was an editor of they yearbook and she convinced me to take the class. Around December I was taken off my original team and placed in charge of a different team who was having trouble. I had to approve the designs of spreads, the placement of picture, edit copy and text, manage the creation of graphics, decide who would cover events, what pictures where good pictures, who to get quotes from, what questions to ask people, the list goes on and on. I was in charge of 8 practically incompetent people, and when they did not do their job right it was my responsibility to fix it. I would stay after school until 9pm, skip my lunch breaks, etc just to get it done right. They would listen to what I told them but I guess it never processed right because, no matter how many times I explained exactly what I wanted, they would never get it right. My team members would listen to me freak out (and I mean yelling and cursing-one time I even cried) and my friends in the class would empathize, but they were going through almost the same thing. The faculty adviser and the editors knew that there was a problem with my team and they tried to help but couldn't. My friends would joke that I had become a dictator and on my paper plate award they used the hash-tag, #ameliaocracy. The final product of the yearbook was not worth the stress that probably took away years of my life. Its so cliche but with great power comes great responsibilities-and unless you have a great team, to get things right, you have to do everything yourself because its your ass on the line not theirs.

Last semester I worked in a group project for my UNIV 112 class. I decided that I would have to take the initiative and text all of them telling them the times I was free and what worked for them and by the end of that I had sort of become the leader of the group. Everyone would text me asking me to look over their work to make sure it was good enough, and whenever there was a question about the game plan they would refer to me. At first I was kind of frustrated because why should I have to take all the responsibility, when they were just as capable? But as time progressed and I watched us work as a group under my supervision, we were able to finish a decent project and turn it in on time. We were given an A and I felt elated because to some degree I knew we wouldn't have gotten as good of a grade if I hadn't made the decision to take control of the situation.

At the Sunday Children's Ministry at my church, I was a teenage volunteer who worked with Kindergarten through 4th grade children in leading them in fun worship songs with dance movements, learning memory verses, assisting the children's pastor in teaching the Bible lesson, and also asking Trivia questions about the lesson/story learned from the previous Sunday. As an incentive to pay attention to the lessons and participate in answering questions, I would reward correct answers to the Trivia questions with a single piece of candy the children could select from a variety in a box. My thoughts at each session were "I really hope the kids were paying attention last week, so we don't take more than 10-15 minutes to answer seven questions...". I was hopeful in wishing the kids to actually learn useful, important life lessons as well as enjoying the reward of candy and having fun, but at the same time, I was also used to them having no idea and simply guessing, giving general answers like, "Jesus!" or "God". I felt horrible when they gave the wrong answers, because I would have to reply, "Nope, sorry, that's not quite it", "Want to try again?" with no results. Despite feeling a little guilty when the kids were disappointed in getting the answer wrong (potential for embarrassment there, I suppose) and especially for not receiving candy, I understood that I was the teen leader and was a role model, and couldn't act "flaky" or "wishy-washy" with the kids and just give them the candy whenever they gave a off-the-mark answer. If they were rewarded every time they knowingly gave incorrect or incredibly vague answers, they would not benefit at all from the activity, and wouldn't come away from church having learned important lessons. I felt the position of power to be a slightly undesirable yet necessary role.
